Opinions and Options</I> (Washington, D.C.: National Defense University
Press, 1995), pp. 22&#173;25.
<P>
<li>There is nothing that would prohibit NATO
from establishing, at least for a transition period, constraints
on the ability of new members to impede fundamental NATO activities
and objectives. For example, new members could be prohibited from
vetoing the admission of other prospective members.
<P>
<li>See &quot;The Process of NATO Expansion&quot;
for details.
<P>
