in 1991 to provide an overall political framework for interaction
between the former Communist nations of Europe and Eurasia with
NATO. The PFP, currently with 26 members, was launched by NATO
in January 1994 as a vehicle for implementing concrete programs
(such as joint humanitarian relief exercises) and opening up military&#173;to&#173;military
contacts.
<P>
<li>The suggestion has been offered by former
Reagan Administration official Constantine Menges for the establishment
of a formal security structure for the nations of Central and
Eastern Europe. In his view, this would be in lieu of NATO membership,
at least in the near term.
<P>
<li>The WEU is composed of 10 Western European
nations who have pledged to protect each other against attack
and is envisioned as the military arm of the European Union. The
international coalition which responded to the Iraqi invasion
of Kuwait is an example of an ad hoc arrangement which utilizes
NATO resources.
<P>
<li>The OSCE (formerly knows as the CSCE)
is composed of 53 nations and addresses a variety of areas, including
the development of international norms of behavior, institutional
support for democracy and human rights, and efforts at confidence&#173;building
and conflict resolution. The EU is composed of 15 European nations
and is the instrument for efforts to integrate Europe politically
and economically.
<P>
<li>Richard Kugler estimates that the new
members could use around $1 billion to $2 billion annually in
Western defense&#173;related loans and grants; <I>op. cit.</I>,
p. 198. Leases of equipment can play an important role. The U.S.,
for example, is considering the leasing of F&#173;16s to Poland.
<P>
<li>The founders of NATO clearly anticipated
expansion. Article Ten of the NATO Treaty defines the process
for admitting new members.<BR>
</ol>

