<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Choice in 1996 -- Issues '96 -- Heritage</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<center>
<h2>Issues '96: The Candidate's Briefing Book</h2>
<b><A HREF="/heritage">The Heritage Foundation</a></b>
</center><p>
<h3>Introduction</H3>
<P>

<CENTER><H2>THE CHOICE IN 1996</H2>
<CITE>By <a href="/heritage/staff/butler.htm">Stuart Butler</a> </CITE></CENTER>
<P>
</P>
<P>When Bill Clinton was elected in 1992, he promised America  a different way
of doing business in Washington. He promised  an end to gridlock, saying that
now there would be a President  willing to work closely with Congress to deal
with the problems that  afflict the nation. He promised fiscal integrity in
Washington and  a reduction in taxes on overburdened working families. He 
promised to reinvent the federal government. And he promised to &quot;end 
welfare as we know it.&quot;
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>He has done none of these things. Worse still, when a  Congress was elected
in 1994 prepared to send Clinton the  legislation needed to do the things he had
promised, he did not cooperate  with Capitol Hill to fashion a reasonable
compromise. Instead,  he worked actively against passage of the legislation and
then  vetoed most of the key bills he was sent. The result: the very gridlock 
he promised to end. The main reason for this impasse is that  while Congress
generally has been prepared to face up to the tough  decisions that must be made
to balance the budget, reform  entitlements, and restructure failing programs,
Bill Clinton has failed  to confront the constituencies that oppose change.
Moreover, he  has failed to exercise leadership by using his presidency to 
force Americans to recognize that hard decisions have to be made.  As veteran
journalist Robert Samuelson put it early in 1996:
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 2 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>     President Clinton no longer has a coherent agenda, if he 
ever did. Mainly, he favors everything that might make people  feel good and
opposes anything that might make them feel  bad. He (reluctantly) supports a
balanced budget while  denouncing congressional cuts in popular programs like
Medicare,  Medicaid and food stamps. Clinton exploits these issues  without
illuminating the practical choices government  faces. <TT><B><A
HREF="ftntintr.htm#1">1</A></B></TT>
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>Much like the citizens of many other Western  democracies, Americans have a
habit of trying to avoid major decisions  about the scope and finances of their
government until they cannot  escape such choices. The actions required then
typically are far  more extreme than would have been needed had prudent steps
had  been taken earlier. America today faces a number of issues on  which
well-conceived and decisive action now will avoid  panic-driven and drastic
action some years in the future. Correcting the  structural financial imbalance
in the Medicare program now, for  instance, can avoid collapse early in the next
decade. Action now,  in other words, will forestall the severe cutbacks or huge
tax  increases that will be needed to provide health coverage for  today's baby
boomers when they retire. Similarly, unless Congress and  the states tackle the
spiraling growth in illegitimacy within the  context of true welfare reform,
America is headed for a social  catastrophe. And taking steps now to reform
America's inefficient and  costly tax system will give the American economy the
incentive it  needs to boost entrepreneurship, productivity, and wages so that 
Americans are not scrambling in the next century to catch up with  other
nations. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>In 1995, Congress was prepared to tackle these and similar  issues of
enormous consequence to the future of the country. But  time 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 3 -->  and again, the new leadership was
thwarted, and  fundamental choices over policy were grossly caricatured by
opponents as  being &quot;for&quot; or &quot;against&quot; children, or the
elderly, or even  allowing visits to the Grand Canyon. The 1996 election is
likely to be  the only opportunity for some years to force a real national 
discussion over the historic challenges facing the nation, and so to resolve 
the impasse in Washington. Conservative candidates must seize  the opportunity
to debate the real choices for dealing with these  challenges.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>There are several particularly important domestic issues for  conservatives
to frame in the 1996 election. Among them:
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><UL>
<li>     <B>Washington must balance its budget through real reductions
 in spending and reforms in the way government functions.
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Politicians in Washington promise to balance the budget  with about the same
eagerness as they pause to shake hands or kiss  babies. But only rarely are they
willing to take the serious  action needed to eliminate red ink. Congresses in
the past invariably  have passed budgets that use creative accounting to reach
balance  well into the future, but then have failed to make the changes in 
programs needed to achieve balance. On many such occasions,  Congresses have
combined phony spending controls with real  increases in taxes. But rather than
reach balance, the new tax  revenue merely reduced the political enthusiasm in
Washington  for making tough decisions on spending. This is why huge tax 
increases enacted under George Bush and Bill Clinton have  done virtually
nothing to bring the deficit under control.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The Congress elected in 1994 sought to break this pattern by  proposing a budget that would reach
balance within seven years  while repealing about one-third of the Bush-Clinton
tax increases.  Unlike most Washington budgets, this one focused much more on 
real changes in programs, much less on gimmicks. Thus, the  budget legislation
passed by Congress in 1995 included structural  changes in Medicare, Medicaid,
and welfare, as well as the termination  of programs.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>President Clinton vetoed that legislation. Before and after that  budget
reached his desk, Clinton spent month after month  finding ways to avoid
offering a budget that would achieve the fiscal  responsibility he promised
during his election campaign.  Clinton's first set of budgets simply did not
even balance, and put off  policy decisions to achieve even modest spending
controls until into  the next century. As 1995 ended, the President seemed
content to  have no budget rather upset any constituency.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>In the 1996 election, conservatives must make the case that  the budget must
be balanced and that it can be balanced only by  reducing the growth in
spending, not by raising taxes.  Conservatives also must make the argument that
the way to reduce the growth  of spending is not to squeeze good and bad
programs alike, but  by such actions as making tough changes in entitlements and
 terminating obsolete and inefficient programs and departments,  shifting
functions to the private sector that should not be in the public  sector.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><li>     <B>There must be structural changes in Medicare if the
program is  to exist for the next generation of retirees.
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P>One of the most noticeable, and disturbing, trends in  federal 
spending in recent decades has
been the shift to entitlement  spending. According to the 1994 report of the
Bipartisan Commission  on Entitlement and Tax Reform, entitlement spending has 
consumed an increasing share of total federal spending, rising from 22.7 
percent of all spending in FY 1963 to over 47 percent in FY  1993. This means
that almost half of all federal spending is on  &quot;autopilot,&quot; driven by
statutory rights to certain services rather than  by budgets voted on each year.
Worse still, the largest  entitlements, including Medicare and Social Security,
are hopelessly out of  balance over the long haul. In particular, spending on
Medicare  is rising at such a clip that the program simply will have no money 
to pay any hospital benefits within six years. Already it is so out  of balance
that it is adding tens of billions of dollars each year to  the general budget
deficit, and this drain on the budget is projected  to rise sharply.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The Congress elected in 1994 was the first since the major  entitlements
were created to address the runaway growth of  entitlements and to restructure
the programs to achieve better value for  money. The Balanced Budget Act of 1995
contained historic reforms  of several entitlements. It ended the entitlement to
welfare  and shifted the design and operation of welfare to the states. It 
ended the entitlement to Medicaid, again moving control of the  program to the
states. And it restructured the Medicare program, curbing  its rate of growth
and increasing competition and consumer choice  to improve efficiency and
achieve savings.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Clinton vetoed that legislation. According to the White House,  no decisive
action was necessary, and taking serious action  would hurt people. On Medicare,
the White House response was  merely to predict that Medicare growth would slow
down and to  offer tighter price controls on doctors and hospitals -- and to  denounce Congress's efforts as draconian and
anti-elderly.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>In the election, conservative candidates need to point out that  most of
today's working-age voters will find literally nothing  in Medicare's hospital
trust fund with which to pay their  medical bills when they retire. So there is
a clear choice open to voters,  and candidates must press the public to make it:
Either voters can  send the message to Washington that they want to avoid doing 
anything, and let benefits be cut deeply and taxes raised sharply  sometime in
the future, or they can tell Washington they want  prudent steps taken now to
restore the finances of the system.  Candidates also must persuade voters to
face the fact that other  middle-class entitlements cannot be allowed to grow
unchecked if the  programs are to pay promised benefits to America's children
when  they reach retirement.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><li>     <B>There must be an end to welfare as we know it and a
national  strategy to reduce illegitimacy.
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P>America has spent over $5 trillion in today's dollars fighting the War on Poverty -- more than on defeating Germany and Japan  in World War II. But as every
taxpayer and welfare mother  knows, the War on Poverty has been a ghastly
failure. Not only has  the poverty rate, for many years, shown no sign of
falling  significantly, but -- even more ominous -- the rate of illegitimacy  has
risen remorselessly. In the black community, two out of  every three children
today are born out of wedlock, and for the  general population one-third of
babies are born to mothers with no  husband. Studies show clearly that being
brought up in a  female-headed household is potentially very damaging to a
child.  Even 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 7 -->  liberals no longer dispute the
findings. Such things as high  levels of teenage crime, poor school performance,
and low future  earnings can be traced to the lack of a father in the home.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The new Congress agreed with President Clinton that welfare  as we know it
had to be ended and that urgent action was needed  to curb the dramatic rise in
illegitimacy. So Congress passed  legislation that would have begun the
transformation of welfare,  ending the entitlement nature of many federal
benefits, allowing the  states to make major changes in the design of programs,
and laying  down modest goals on work and illegitimacy for the states to 
achieve. But rather than sign the legislation, Clinton first criticized and 
then denounced it. His own proposal: limited authority to states,  a larger
welfare bureaucracy to &quot;help&quot; people to leave welfare  rather than
strong incentives to do so, and no real action to back up  the talk about
stemming the tide of illegitimacy. Virtually any effort  to discourage
illegitimate births was attacked by Clinton as  tantamount to child abuse.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The utter failure of the liberal welfare state, including the  explosion of
illegitimacy, is shredding America's social fabric. In  the 1996 election,
conservative candidates must urge Americans  to make a clear choice. They can
accept the arguments of those  who say that the only problem with the welfare
state today is that we  do not spend enough on it. According to this line of
argument,  what Congress should do is commit huge amounts of additional 
resources to child care, training programs, and other services to  enable
welfare mothers to become employable. This argument  is advanced most
vociferously by those who would be paid to  deliver the services.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The other option, conservatives should point out, is to move in  the
direction that Congress charted but Clinton vetoed. This  means facing up to the
obvious fact that spending more money on  welfare harms children rather than
helping them and destroys  families rather than strengthening them. The
conservative option is to  concentrate on reducing the rate of illegitimacy  the
root cause  of America's social problems  by discouraging  out-of-wedlock births
and reducing the burdens on two-parent families. In  addition, the conservative
option would give wide authority to states  to redesign programs while insisting
on clear national goals to  reduce illegitimacy and require work, and would
implement real  evaluations of state efforts. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P> Further, conservatives must make the case that if poor  Americans are to be
held responsible for their actions, as other Americans  are held accountable,
they also must be given the power to take  responsibility. That means giving
poor Americans the same right  to choose the school that is right for their
child, through vouchers,  as the President of the United States enjoys. And it
means  enabling these Americans, through housing vouchers and the right to 
manage or own their own homes, to escape the crushing and  dangerous environment
of many public housing projects.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><li>     <B>It's time to reduce the tax burden on families with
children and  to introduce a flat tax.
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Americans have grown increasingly frustrated with the tax  code. Quite
correctly, they see it as complex and unfair, full of  loopholes for those with
the means or sophistication to exploit them. That  is why a simple, flat tax is
so attractive to so many voters. But  besides its mind-numbing complexity,
today's tax code has two  other 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 9 -->  severe deficiencies. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>One is that over the years the burden has shifted decisively  to families
with children. Because of the erosion, through  inflation, of exemptions and the
rise in Social Security tax rates,  families with children have faced an
increasing share of taxes when  compared with other groups. This has accentuated
the perverse  incentives of the welfare system and made it harder for 
middle-class families with children to make ends meet.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The other deficiency is the treatment of savings and  investment. The tax
code almost seems designed to discourage investment  and risk-taking by
subjecting saved income to multiple taxation.  The result: Saving has been
discouraged, and those who have  saved find the nest egg they accumulated for
themselves and their  children eaten away by the IRS.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The Congress elected in 1994 tried to take the first steps to  correct these
problems. Concentrating on the most immediate problem -- the bias against
families with children  Congress enacted  legislation that would have given a
$500 credit per child to families  with children. This across-the-board credit
recognized that the  purpose of the original exemption for children was to
relieve all families  of taxation on income used to raise children. Congress
also  included in the legislation a reduction in the capital gains tax and the 
reduction of taxes on certain new forms of savings. Unfortunately,  despite
pledging a middle-class tax cut in 1992 and raising  taxes since then, President
Clinton vetoed the legislation, invoking  traditional class warfare arguments.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Conservatives need to use the 1996 election to frame the issue  of 
taxation. They need to argue that
the time for tinkering with  the tax code is over: What is needed is a new tax
system that is  simple and flat, taxes earnings only once, and redresses the
unfair tax  burden on families with children. Such a flat tax not only would 
bring back fairness and help ordinary working families, but it would  end the
tax penalties currently ranged against those Americans  who invest in the future
of their own children and that of the nation.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><li>     <B>The American economy is the world's most powerful engine 
of jobs and wealth creation. Washington should stop slowing  down that engine.
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P>While it is natural for people to be concerned about their  economic future,
conservative candidates must not allow these concerns  to be channeled into bad
policies based on a phony reading of  history. This means that candidates must
remind voters of the  real nature and strength of the U.S. economy. And they
must  remind voters, too, that government can do little to improve on the 
workings of the free enterprise system, but much to damage it.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Many politicians play to fears of economic insecurity and  suggest that
ordinary working Americans are somehow the victims of  Wall Street greed or
underpriced foreign competition. Some of  these politicians go on to argue,
surprisingly, that Americans should  turn to the federal government to assure
their security and  economic well-being. Yet the facts refute the premise behind
this line of  argument, and hard-learned experience indicates that a more 
active federal government is no answer to insecurity. In particular, 
conservatives need to remind Americans that constant change is  the key to
America's traditional economic strength. That is  why America has created 46
million jobs since 1970, while Europe  has 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 11 -->  languished. And conservatives
must remind Americans that  the tough competition of international trade
sharpens efficiency  and brings prosperity to all Americans, while defeatist 
protectionism leads to long-run stagnation.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Nevertheless, the U.S. economy still has performed less well  than it could
for many years, and so has rewarded American  workers less well than it could.
There are three main reasons for this.  The first is that government has
increased the cost of hiring  Americans, through regulation and taxation, and
has taken more and more  out of each paycheck. This has meant fewer jobs than
otherwise  would have been created, especially for lower-skilled Americans. 
Over the last 20 years, for instance, regulation alone has probably  cost more
than three million jobs. The solution is deregulation and  reduced taxes on
labor  less government.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The second reason is that the shortcomings of the public  school system have
caused many Americans to lack the basic skills  they need to be productive, and
thus command good wages. This  government failure in basic education is not
corrected by  maintaining a public school monopoly, or by creating government
training  programs to try to correct the deficiencies of government schools. It 
is addressed by giving parents the power to demand better value  for money,
establishing real standards to enable parents to  evaluate schools, and ending
the public school monopoly.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The third reason is that the tax code's bias against saving and  investment
has slowed down the introduction of the new tools  and equipment in the economy
that workers need to be more  productive and earn higher wages. The solution to
this problem is to  reduce taxes on capital.
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 12 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>This Congress has attempted to reduce these government  sources of long-term
drag on the U.S. economy. It has sought to  reduce capital gains taxes and taxes
on working Americans. It has tried  to eliminate regulations whose meager
benefits do not justify  the heavy cost in jobs. And it has encouraged states to
take the lead,  as they should, in overhauling the education system. 
Unfortunately, President Clinton has obstructed or vetoed all of these  efforts.
Meanwhile, he has fostered the enticing but false notion that  government can
provide an economic security blanket for all  Americans. To his credit, however,
Clinton has worked with the  new congressional leadership to resist
protectionism and reduce  worldwide barriers to trade.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Conservatives need to draw sharp lines in the debate over  the economy
during the election cycle. They must point out that  there are those who would
maintain  even increase  the current  burden on taxation and regulation on the
economy, and then seek  to expand government programs and protections to &quot;correct&quot;
the  apparent shortcomings of the economy. But this is the road to  stagnation,
not jobs and wealth. They must argue instead that the  only way to create jobs,
prosperity, and long-term security is to end  tax and regulatory policies that
hamper job creation and wage growth.
</UL>
<P>
</P>
<P>Other issues also must be raised in the 1996 election.  Americans need to be
presented with the clear choices that exist on such  issues as health care, the
environment, crime, education, and  congressional reform. In all these policy
areas, critical choices have  to be made  indeed, should have been made many
years ago.  Since the last election, the country has had a Congress willing to 
confront the choices and to take action, and a White House trying  to 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 13 -->  persuade the nation to cling to
the cozy illusion that no  hard choices need to be made. It is up to
conservatives during this  election season to make sure that Americans
understand this, and  that they are presented with the clear decisions that no
longer can  be avoided.
</P>
<P><center>
