<center>
<h2>Issues '96: The Candidate's Briefing Book</h2>
<b><A HREF="/heritage">The Heritage Foundation</a></b>
</center><p>
<h3>Chapter 3</h3>
<center><h2>REGULATION
</H2>
<B><i>By <a href="/heritage/staff/antonel.htm">Angela Antonelli</a>
</i></B>
<P><A HREF="chpt3.html#ISSUES">The Issues</A> | <A HREF="chpt3.html#FACTS">The Facts</A> |  <A HREF="chpt3.html#RECORD">The Record</A> | <A HREF="chpt3.html#Q&A">Q&amp;A</A>| <a href="chpt3.html#EXP">Experts</a> 
</center>
<p>
<a href="regs_t1.gif">Table 1</a>: Ten Most Expensive Interventions<br> 
<a href="regs_t2.gif">Table 2</a>: Median Cost Per Life-Year Saved: Estimates for Regulatory Agencies<br>
<a href="regs_t3.gif">Table 3</a>: Alternative Ways to Reduce Risk of Death<br>
<a href="regs_1.gif">Chart 1</a>: Median Cost Per Life-Year Saved<br>
<a href="regs_2.gif">Chart 2</a>: The Opportunity Cost of Selected E.P.A Regulations<br> 
<a href="regs_3.gif">Chart 3</a>: Regulators vs. Job Growth<br>
<a href="regs_4.gif">Chart 4</a>: Real Wages Fall When Regulations Increase<br>
<P>
<a href="chpt3text.html">Additional Text</a><p>


<B><A NAME="ISSUES">THE ISSUES</A>
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Government regulations affect all Americans: from the food  they eat, to the
medications they take, to how they use their  private property, to how they run
their businesses. Excessive  government regulation today is vast in scope and
staggering in its impact,  both on individuals and on the U.S. economy.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Government regulation has shown itself to be both  far-reaching and
counterproductive in its impact on American business. It  increases the cost of
doing business and hiring workers, which  results in fewer jobs and lower
salaries and makes U.S.  companies less competitive in world markets.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The burden is bad enough, but much regulation also is poorly  designed and
thus unnecessarily costly. Federal regulatory  agencies do not have a system for
making rational, well-informed  decisions on how to allocate limited resources
most efficiently to  maximize health, safety, and environmental  protection.
<TT><B><A HREF="ftnt3.htm#1">1</A></B></TT>  Today,
Americans spend approximately $170 billion a year just complying with  rules
designed to protect the environment. The total cost to the  economy of all
regulation is estimated to be between $600 billion and  $700 billion annually.
This represents a hidden tax of more than  $6,000 per year per family. The
regulatory process must be reformed  so 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 2 -->  that government resources at all
levels can be allocated more  rationally and business can devote its resources
to becoming more  innovative and productive.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Although the direct costs of regulation typically are imposed  on businesses
and governments, ultimately they are passed on  to American consumers in the
form of higher prices, reduced  quality or availability of products and
services, or higher taxes. In  addition, regulation can increase the cost of
employing workers  and thus act as a tax on job creation and employment. For 
example, American businesses must carry the costs of federal labor laws  that
constrain the freedom of companies to hire and fire workers and  to engage in
negotiations with employees and labor unions.  Similarly, employers often are
required to provide such benefits  as health insurance, unemployment insurance,
workers'  compensation, retirement benefits, paid family leave, or child care  
the costs of which are passed on to consumers through higher prices  or to
workers through slowdowns in the creation of new jobs or  reductions in wages.
<TT><B><A HREF="ftnt3.htm#2">2</A></B></TT>  Federal
mandates on state and local  governments also may force the diversion of
resources from other  government priorities such as education, police, and fire
services.  To continue providing these services, state and local government  may
be compelled to raise taxes. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The vast majority of Americans agree that some government  regulation is
desirable and necessary. Most highway regulations,  for example, save lives and
improve the flow of traffic at  minimal cost. Such regulations obviously provide
a huge net benefit to  everyone, but regulations also can be both
counterproductive  and harmful to society. The problem is that regulation today
is  far more costly and less effective than it should be.
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 3 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Conservative candidates and legislators should focus on  bringing common
sense to the regulatory process in 1997 by enacting  reforms that incorporate
five key principles:<TT><B><A HREF="ftnt3.htm#3">3</A></B></TT>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>1. Cost-Benefit analysis.</B> Federal agencies should be required  to
consider the benefits and costs of a range of regulatory  alternatives and
choose the options that maximize net benefits to society.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>2. Sound science.</B> Agencies should seek the most advanced  scientific
knowledge available.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>3. Risk assessment and risk management.</B> Agencies must  develop more
scientifically objective methods to determine the nature  and extent of a &quot;hazard.&quot;
 The process for assessing risk should be  distinct from the process for
determining what risks are significant  or unacceptable and how they should be
managed.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>4. Risk-based priorities and public education.</B> Agencies  should
prioritize their regulatory actions based on a consideration of  risks, how
those risks compare to risks familiar to the public, and  the costs of reducing
them. Agencies also must educate the  public about their risk-setting
priorities.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>5. Market incentives and performance standards.</B> To the  extent
possible, agencies should give regulated parties the flexibility  to meet
established regulatory objectives in the most efficient,  low-cost manner rather
than through a command-and-control,  one-size-fits-all approach.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><A NAME="FACTS">THE FACTS</A>
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 4 --> 
</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     Even conservative estimates
indicate that the cost of  complying with federal regulation was at least $668
billion in 1995 and  will increase to $721 billion in 2000. <TT><B><A>4</A></B></TT>
 This is more than $6,000  per household. By the year 2000, these figures are
expected to  increase to almost $7,000 per household. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P> <B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     In 1995, according to Americans for Tax Reform,
the  average American had to work full time until July 9 to pay the costs 
associated with government taxation, deficit spending, and  regulations. This
means that 53 cents of every dollar earned went to the  government directly or
indirectly.
</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>Estimating the precise cost of federal regulation is extremely  difficult.
Unlike federal spending, regulatory costs are not  accounted for in the budget
process; and while agencies are supposed to  calculate the costs and benefits of
proposed  regulations, <TT><B><A HREF="ftnt3.htm#5">5</A></B></TT>
their calculations vary in quality and often grossly underestimate the true 
cost or substantially overestimate the benefits of  regulation. <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt3.htm#6">6</A></B></TT>  The Contract with America
called for the application of cost-benefit  analysis to new rules and
regulations. The idea was to force  Congress and regulatory agencies to assess
the costs and benefits of  regulations before they are enacted. Critics argue
that too often the  costs and benefits of a regulation are hard to identify and
quantify,  and that it is difficult to place a dollar value on a human life that
 may be saved by a regulation. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P> <a href="regs_t1.gif">Table 1</a> presents ten examples of how regulations can impose  astronomical
costs relative to the benefits they produce.  Kent Jeffreys, a Senior Fellow at
the National Center for Policy  Analysis, summed it up well in a recent report
on regulatory  reform: 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 5 -->  &quot;One reason why the cost
estimates appear so outrageous is  that the risks the regulations are trying to
eliminate are so tiny. One  of the advantages of cost-benefit analysis is that
it helps  alert policymakers that the regulation of trivial risks can be very 
expensive.&quot; <TT><B><A HREF="ftnt3.htm#7">7</A></B></TT>

</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     We can save more by increasing
medical treatment, and to a  somewhat lesser degree, to curbing fatal injuries.
Trying to save  lives by regulating pesticides or other toxins, on the other
hand,  squanders resources. <a href="regs_1.gif">Chart 1</a> shows the cost-ineffectiveness of the 
majority of toxin control measures. To put the numbers in  perspective, Dr. John
Graham, director of Harvard University's Center  for Risk Analysis, notes &quot;the
median toxin control program costs  58 times more per year of life saved than
the median injury  prevention program and 146 times more than the median medical
 program.&quot; 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     A comparison of regulations for different
federal agencies  shows that there is no consistent cost-benefit standard. In
fact, as <a href="regs_2.gif">Chart  2</a> shows, the median cost effectiveness of federal regulation 
varies; an EPA regulation can cost 100 times more than consumer  product or
highway safety regulations. <TT><B><A HREF="ftnt3.htm#8">8</A></B></TT></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>The enormous costs of complying with many environmental  regulations often
are not justified by the minuscule health dangers  the rules are meant to
address. As a result, limited financial  resources that could be used more
effectively are wasted in pursuit of  a &quot;zero-risk environment.&quot; <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt3.htm#9">9</A></B></TT>  As Dr. Graham points out, &quot;Our
 environmental policies suffer from a syndrome of paranoia and  neglect.... We
go after minuscule risks, such as pesticide residue  in food, and at the same
time we're tolerant and neglectful of  major 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 6 -->  problems in our daily life.&quot;
<TT><B><A HREF="ftnt3.htm#10">10</A></B></TT>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>A world of competing needs and limited resources requires  rational,
well-informed decisions about how best to allocate those  resources. Using
resources one way means not using them in  other ways that could save more lives
or produce other more  desirable outcomes. For example, the Environmental
Protection  Agency's hazardous waste disposal ban costs $4.2 billion for each 
premature death averted. These same resources could be used to keep  47,890
dangerous criminals in prison for an additional three and a  half years.
Similarly, the $168 million it takes to avert one death  under a benzene
standard could be used to put 3,064 more police  officers on the street. <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt3.htm#11">11</A></B></TT>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Growing Regulatory Burden on Business and Local  Government</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Although Ronald Reagan succeeded in reversing the  growing regulatory burden
for a time, regulatory growth exploded  under George Bush and by all indications
is accelerating under  Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     The Code of Federal Regulations
(CFR), the annual  accumulation of executive agency regulations published in the

<I>Federal Register</I>, including regulations issued previously and still in
effect, now  fills 202 volumes and 131,803 pages, taking up 19 feet of shelf 
space. In 1970, the CFR filled 114 volumes and 54,834 pages.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>- </CITE></B>    The total annual length of the <I>Federal 
Register</I>, the daily government publication in which all proposed regulations
are  announced, was 20,036 pages in 1970. During the eight-year presidency  of 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 7 -->  Ronald Reagan, the number of pages
declined by more  than 33,676, from an all-time high of 87,012 in Jimmy Carter's
 last year (1980) to 53,376 in 1988. In 1995, the 
<I>Federal Register</I> was 67,518 pages.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     As the number of regulations has grown, so has
the number of  federal regulators enforcing these rules. The number of 
permanent, full-time positions at the more than 50 primary federal  regulatory
agencies grew from 69,946 in 1970 to 128,566 in 1994. The  number fell by 17,379
under Reagan, from what had been a record  high of 121,791 in Carter's last year
to 104,412 in 1988. Under  Bush, however, over 21,000 new regulatory bureaucrats
were added for  a new all-time high of 125,666 in 1992. By 1994, the Clinton 
Administration sustained 128,566 federal regulatory  employees. <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt3.htm#12">12</A></B></TT>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     The annual cost to the taxpayers of
administering federal  regulatory programs grew from $4 billion in 1970 to $11.8
billion  in 1994 (in constant 1987 dollars), according to the St.  Louis-based
Center for the Study of American Business, and it is projected  to exceed $12.4
billion in 1996. <TT><B><A HREF="ftnt3.htm#13">13</A></B></TT>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     An October 1993 Price Waterhouse survey
commissioned by  the National Association of Counties estimated the cost of just
12  federal intergovernmental mandates on counties during the year  at $4.8
billion. <TT><B><A HREF="ftnt3.htm#14">14</A></B></TT> 
Unfunded federal mandates remove the ability  of state and local governments to
direct their tax dollars toward  established community priorities by forcing
them to devote a  growing share of their budgets to the costs of complying with
these  mandates. In some cases, local governments have found it necessary  to
raise revenues and cut services.
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 8 --> 
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Loss of Jobs</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Another heavy cost of regulation is reduced employment  opportunities for
Americans. This toll is not usually apparent, because  in most instances
regulation merely leads to a slower growth in  employment rather than a more
visible loss of existing jobs.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Regulation destroys jobs in several ways. <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt3.htm#15">15</A></B></TT>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>First,</B> reductions in efficiency, productivity,
investment, and  economic growth due to regulation mean fewer jobs created. A 
weak, slowly growing economy creates fewer jobs than a booming,  rapidly growing
one. This effect destroys jobs even in sectors that  are not directly regulated.
For example, because of federal efforts  to protect the northern spotted owl,
millions of acres of land in  Washington, Oregon, and Northern California are
closed to logging  operations. Tens of thousands of loggers have lost their jobs
 because of the regulations and thousands of other jobs have been lost  in
communities that depend on logging as the principal industry.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Second,</B> regulations may raise the costs of doing business by 
curtailing the number of workers hired. The costs of regulation  may contribute
to forcing a company out of business or preventing  a new company from starting
up and creating new jobs. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The U.S. Health Care Financing Administration's 1,600 pages  of regulations
implementing the Clinical Laboratory  Improvement Amendments (CLIA) of 1988 add
between $1.2 billion and  $2.1 billion annually to the cost of performing
clinical laboratory  tests in doctors' offices. <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt3.htm#16">16</A></B></TT>  The result: tens of
thousands of  physicians' office labs forced to curtail their operations or shut
down  alto
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 9 -->  gether. <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt3.htm#17">17</A></B></TT>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Third,</B> regulations may raise the cost of employment by  imposing
specific costs tied to each new employee hired. Employers  often are required to
provide various benefits such as health  insurance, unemployment insurance,
workers' compensation, retirement  benefits, paid family leave, or child care.
They then pass their  increased costs on to consumers in the form of higher
prices or  to workers in slower job creation or reduced  wages. <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt3.htm#18">18</A></B></TT> <A></A>
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>Federal regulatory officials currently face no explicit  requirement that
they consider the employment effects as they develop  new rules. Nor do
lawmakers. Federal regulatory agencies should  be required to consider the
cumulative effects of existing  regulations, including their deleterious effects
on job creation.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Even where regulations may be justified as producing  desirable social
benefits, they often impose unnecessary costs because  of how they are written,
and these costs may result in unnecessary  job losses. For example:
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     While the number of federal
regulators declined in the early  1980s, the number of jobs soared; but as the
number of federal  regulators increased in the late 1980s, job growth declined
sharply (see  <a href="regs_3.gif">Chart 3</a>).
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     As the surge in regulation began around 1970,
the sharp growth  in real wages enjoyed by American workers over the prior two 
decades stopped. This was due to the higher regulatory costs  borne by employers
and the resulting lower wages for workers (see  <a href="regs_4.gif">Chart 4</a>).
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 10 --> 
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Loss of Life</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Compliance with costly regulations means less real income  for individuals
to spend in other ways, including ways that might  improve their health and
safety. <TT><B><A HREF="ftnt3.htm#19">19</A></B></TT>  The
wealthier a society is,  the healthier it tends to be. <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt3.htm#20">20</A></B></TT>  Low income has its
adverse effects,  including poor diet, high incidence of heart disease, and a
high  suicide rate relative to the rest of the population. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     Estimates show that for every
reduction in national wealth in  a range of $2 million to $6 million, one
additional premature  death will occur.<TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt3.htm#21">21</A></B></TT>
</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>Regulations intended to reduce health and safety risks, and  thereby reduce
premature deaths to Americans, cost billions of dollars  annually. Whether these
regulations are worthwhile depends, in  part, on whether the costs of a specific
regulation induce more  fatalities than the regulation itself is expected to
avoid. <a href="regs_t3.gif">Table 3</a>  illustrates how very large regulatory costs imposed with little 
commensurate benefit actually may result in a net loss of lives. Even without 
taking into consideration the lives lost because of economic  impacts, the more
direct opportunity cost of a regulation such as  uranium mill tailings can be
enormous. If, for instance, $71.6 million  was devoted to additional colo-rectal
blood tests, which save an  estimated one life for every $24,964 spent,
approximately 2,858  lives could be saved.  <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt3.htm#22">22</A></B></TT>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     A recent Harvard study concluded
that we incur opportunity  costs of approximately $31.1 billion, 60,200
premature deaths,  or 636,000 years of life lost every year in order to maintain
 our 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 11 -->  present pattern of investments in
risk reduction. <TT><B><A HREF="ftnt3.htm#23">23</A></B></TT>
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Destruction of Small Businesses</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Small businesses are the engine of economic growth in this  country. Today,
two out of every three new jobs in the United  States are created by small and
medium-sized businesses. More than  90 percent of all business establishments
employ fewer than  100 workers, and more than 80 percent employ fewer than 20. 
Less than one percent of all firms in the United States employ 500  or more
people. <TT><B><A HREF="ftnt3.htm#24">24</A></B></TT>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>A report recently released by the U.S. Small Business  Administration (SBA)
points out that &quot;small business owners often fear  that they will
inadvertently fail to comply with some obscure rule,  and that a government
inspector will show up, close down the  business, and drive them into
bankruptcy. Many believe, with  some justification, that the government is more
interested in  obtaining penalties than in promoting compliance with the  law.&quot;
<TT><B><A HREF="ftnt3.htm#25">25</A></B></TT>  They have
good reason to be concerned: 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     OSHA inspected Gary Adams's pastry
shop in 1994 and cited  him for violating the &quot;lockout&quot; standard
because the switches in  his ovens were not padlocked while the ovens were being
 repaired. Adams, who was doing the repair work himself, had removed  the fuses
and appliances so the ovens could not possibly work.  This explanation was not
good enough for OSHA  the agency  fined Adams $1,250 for each of his three
ovens. OSHA's area  director told Adams that &quot;Washington reviews us to see
how much  money we collect,&quot; to which Adams responded, &quot;Are you in the
safety  or money business?&quot;<TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt3.htm#26">26</A></B></TT>
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 12 --> 
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>For small business owners, Washington looms as &quot;public  enemy number
one,&quot; and they want to get government off their backs  so they can do what
they do best  create jobs and tax revenue   without the excessive burden of
reporting and regulatory  compliance. <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt3.htm#27">27</A></B></TT>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>In June 1995, the White House convened a conference on  small business with
more than 1,600 delegates representing small  businesses from around the
country. The vast majority of the  delegates ranked regulation and paperwork
reduction among their  highest priorities for federal government action.
Excessive regulation  and taxes are by far their biggest concerns.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Regulation does not affect all businesses equally. It imposes  the heaviest
burden on small and medium-sized businesses  because they find it harder to
spread the high overhead costs of  paperwork, attorney and accountant fees, and
staff time needed to  negotiate the federal regulatory maze. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     According to the SBA, the average
annual cost of regulation,  paperwork, and tax compliance for firms with fewer
than 500  employees is about $5,000 per employee, compared with  about $3,400
for firms with more than 500  employees.
<TT><B><A HREF="ftnt3.htm#28">28</A></B></TT>  Very small
businesses  those with fewer than 50 employees  have  costs running about seven
to ten times higher than those borne by  firms with 50 to 100 employees. <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt3.htm#29">29</A></B></TT>  Firms with 20-49
employees  spend, on average, 19 cents out of every revenue dollar on 
regulatory costs.
<TT><B><A HREF="ftnt3.htm#30">30</A></B></TT>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     For small businesses, says the SBA, tax
compliance and  payroll 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 13 -->  record keeping are the two
largest components of the  regulatory burden: about 80 percent of the total paid
by firms with fewer  than 10 employees. <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt3.htm#31">31</A></B></TT>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     The burden of regulation on small business was
documented in  a study by Lowell Gallaway of Ohio University and Gary  Anderson
of California State University, <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt3.htm#32">32</A></B></TT> who found that the total 
per worker, including taxes and regulations, declined for a  typical small
business from 1982 to 1989. At the same time,  employment in the American
economy was booming. From 1989 to 1992,  however, these costs increased by 34.4
percent; the Reagan-era  job boom stopped abruptly, with over two million jobs
lost  between 1990 and 1992 as regulatory costs exploded  again. <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt3.htm#33">33</A></B></TT>
</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Regulatory Absurdity</B><TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt3.htm#34">34</A></B></TT>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Unfortunately, there are too many examples of out-of-control  regulatory
policy. Regulations are developed or enforced in a way  that unnecessarily harms
both individuals and businesses, stifles  creativity and the entrepreneurial
spirit, and simply wastes  taxpayers' money.
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     &quot;The IRS spent five years
proposing, revising, and re-revising  and finalizing pension regulations barring
pension plans that  discriminate against lower-paid employees. The regulations,
when  finally issued, took up 600 pages. About a month later, the Department  of
Labor proposed to eliminate a big chunk of  them.&quot; <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt3.htm#35">35</A></B></TT></P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     In November 1995, Hooters, a national restaurant
chain, paid for  a full-page advertisement in <I>The Washington  Post</I> to
complain about actions taken against it by the Equal Employment  Opportunity
Commission. <TT><B><A HREF="ftnt3.htm#36">36</A></B></TT> 
According to the ad, the EEOC required the  res
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 14 -->  taurant, which hires women to
work as provocatively dressed  food servers, to teach its employees to be more
sensitive to  &quot;men's needs&quot; by providing sensitivity training for its
employees and  establishing a scholarship fund for men. For the next five 
years, owners must have key business decisions approved by a  federally mandated
&quot;administrator&quot; who reports to the EEOC. As the  ad points out, &quot;The
government has a 100,000 case backlog of  job discrimination claims. It's hard
to believe that replacing  `Hooter Girls' with `Hooter Guys' is one of the
EEOC's top priorities.&quot;
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     In 1990, Stephen Lathrop bought a parcel of land
in  Madison County, Illinois. The land was an overgrown dump covered  with
trash, concrete, bricks, and rubble. It also was frequently  flooded, and the
U.S. Army Corps of Engineers had spent thousands of  taxpayer dollars studying
the site. After purchasing the land  and checking with local government
agencies, Lathrop began to  clear the property and dig a reservoir. The Corps of
Engineers then  took control of Lathrop's land in December 1990 and, in April 
1991, ordered him to restore the swamp and fill the reservoir. He  refused and
wound up facing daily fines of $25,000 and criminal  prosecution as a &quot;negligent
wetland offender.&quot;  The Army Corps  justified its action by arguing that
Lathrop's intent was to develop his  property, not to provide habitat or prevent
flooding (even though  these were the benefits of his action), and therefore was
 illegal. <TT><B><A HREF="ftnt3.htm#37">37</A></B></TT>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     The Good Shepherd United Methodist Church in
Prince  William County, Virginia, in November 1995 ended a two-year battle  with
the Environmental Protection Agency over a $26,000  fine. <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt3.htm#38">38</A></B></TT>  Apparently, the church
decided to have asbestos insulation  removed from its 30-year-old building, but
a surprise visit from the  EPA resulted in a citation and penalty for violating
federal  regulations 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 15 -->  on asbestos cleanup. Evidently,
the EPA found small amounts  of possibly contaminated dust in several places.
Although the  church cleaned up the dust before reopening the building, the EPA
did  not drop the penalty, which constituted about 10 percent of  the church's
$300,000 budget. The dispute eventually landed in  court, only to have the EPA
change its mind and go after the  engineering firm responsible for the work even
though the overall risk  was negligible. In the words of Victor Bras, chairman
of the  church's administrative board, &quot;We were making a statement that,
for  once, we were not going to let the EPA beat up on a small  institution....
We thought they were taking action that had a lot of  destructive purposes.&quot;<TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt3.htm#39">39</A></B></TT>
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>As Stephen Breyer discusses in his book, <I>Breaking the  Vicious Circle</I>,
federal regulatory agencies often consider a problem  and end up promulgating a
&quot;standard so stringent... that the  regulatory action ultimately imposes
high costs without achieving  significant additional safety benefits.&quot;
<TT><B><A HREF="ftnt3.htm#40">40</A></B></TT>  Although
Breyer concentrates  on how regulators handle cancer-causing substances, his 
conclusions apply broadly to all federal regulatory actions. Today,  federal
regulators are seen as out of control because the regulations  they promulgate
produce few benefits at great cost, are often  inconsistent with other federal
actions, and are of little overall  consequence relative to other actions that
might produce greater  benefits to society. In other words, the process is
haphazard and chaotic.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Regulatory actions intended to deal with toxic substances are  the best
examples of what is wrong with this process. The  assumptions and quality of the
scientific data agencies use to evaluate risks  can vary. Thus, risk assessments
by different agencies may result  in different answers about whether a
particular chemical at a  particu
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 16 -->  lar dose level causes cancer.
Agencies should have a  consistent method for assessing and managing risk. Risk
assessments  should reveal all the assumptions, uncertainties, and value
judgments  in the analysis.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>For example, when the government identifies a hazard, it  makes assumptions
about the degree of human exposure to  contaminants. Often these assumptions are
arbitrary and are of no value to  those trying to determine the best ways to
reduce the overall risk to  society. <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt3.htm#41">41</A></B></TT> 
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>      Under the Superfund program, the
EPA assumes that sites  should be cleaned so that a child could eat bits of mud
for 250 days a  year without becoming seriously ill. <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt3.htm#42">42</A></B></TT>  This kind of assumption 
generates cleanup standards that are more costly than necessary,  particularly
when the risks are overstated by as much as 10,000 times  the actual threat to
the public. <TT><B><A HREF="ftnt3.htm#43">43</A></B></TT>
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>The lack of effective risk assessment has led to federal  programs that
spend more and more money to reduce fewer and fewer  risks. Unrealistic
assumptions and exaggerated assessments do little  to help federal regulators
make reasoned decisions about risk.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     A 1992 study by the Office of
Management and Budget shows  that federal regulations ranged in cost from
$100,000 per  premature death averted (mandated car-safety standards) to as much
as  $5 trillion (designation and regulation of wood-preserving  chemicals as
hazardous wastes). <TT><B><A HREF="ftnt3.htm#44">44</A></B></TT>
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>By improving how they assess and manage risk, federal  regulators can
identify real and significant risks to the public more  effectively. This will
reduce the amount of money the federal  government drains from the economy
whenever it forces private  busi
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 17 -->  nesses and state and local
governments to comply with  unnecessary and costly mandates. A business forced
to spend $10  million to comply with a particular regulation has less money to
pass on  to workers in the form of higher wages or new jobs. Similarly,  state
and local governments must forego other types of services  (education, police,
or fire) or raise taxes every time they are required  to implement a new federal
mandate.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><A NAME="RECORD">THE RECORD</A></B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>THE CLINTON ADMINISTRATION
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     While President Clinton is critical
of the federal  government's overregulation, his actions do not match his
rhetoric. In fact,  even as Clinton calls for change, his Administration appears
even  more aggressive than its predecessors in wielding its regulatory power.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     For example, on October 4, 1993, President
Clinton issued  Executive Order 12866, &quot;Regulatory Planning and Review,&quot;
replacing  a Reagan Administration order requiring executive branch  agencies to
submit proposed regulations with a cost in excess of $100  million to OMB for
review and approval. In the new executive  order, the Clinton Administration
reaffirmed its commitment to 1)  using the best scientific and economic data; 2)
using analysis to  inform decision-making; 3) considering flexible,
cost-effective  performance standards; and 4) allowing early public
participation in  an open and accountable regulatory process. However, there is 
little evidence that the order has had any significant impact or that  the White
House is encouraging agencies to comply. An April  1995 study by the Institute
for Regulatory Policy examined all EPA  proposed and final rules published in
the<I> Federal  Register</I> during the 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 18 -->  second six months after the
Clinton executive order took  effect. Based on an analysis of 222 substantive
rulemakings, the  study found only six for which the demonstrated benefits
justified  the costs involved. In addition, only 14 examined regulatory 
alternatives, and only eight of these specified that the most  cost-effective
rule had been adopted. <TT><B><A HREF="ftnt3.htm#45">45</A></B></TT>

</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>On February 21, 1995, President Clinton directed federal  agencies to
conduct a page-by-page review of existing regulations to  determine which should
be eliminated and which should be  streamlined, updated, overhauled, or
otherwise improved. By June 1,  the Administration claimed the agencies had
identified over  16,000 pages in the Code of Federal Regulations (CFR) that they
 would be eliminating. In addition, they supposedly are &quot;reinventing&quot; 
over 31,000 additional pages. The challenge now is for the public  to figure out
what this all really means. While the number  sounds impressive, when put in the
proper context it is considerably  less impressive. Today's CFR is more than
131,000 pages, more  than twice as large as it was twenty years ago. Eliminating
 16,000 pages is only about 12 percent of this total, and that is  assuming that
no new regulations are added in the interim, which is not  the case. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>On November 28, 1995, the Administration published its  1,700-page
semiannual agenda of federal regulations, which  presents very brief
descriptions of all planned regulatory actions.  The Administration's lack of
seriousness in achieving real  reductions in burden is evident. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>While EPA claims to be streamlining various permitting,  review, and
reporting requirements for a number of programs, the  Clinton 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 19 -->  Administration is simultaneously
pushing forward with  burdensome regulatory initiatives, such as expanding the
universe  of sources that must be reported as part of the Toxic Release 
Inventory. <TT><B><A HREF="ftnt3.htm#46">46</A></B></TT> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P> The Administration has reviewed the Community  Reinvestment Act (CRA) in an
attempt to &quot;strengthen and streamline&quot; the  rules. However, this
streamlining process resulted in more than  140 pages of new CRA rules and
regulations. As Congressman  Bill McCollum (R-FL) notes, &quot;Only in
Washington can streamlining  be defined as going from a rules that takes up 14
pages in the  Federal Register to one that takes up 145 pages.&quot;
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>In addition, a number of agencies admit that they have not  reviewed their
rules for twenty to forty years. Some of the  pages being eliminated are for
rules for which the underlying statute  has long since been repealed, treaties
that no longer exist, etc.  This alone could easily achieve a 10 percent
reduction in the CFR  without accomplishing any real changes in the way in which
the  federal government goes about regulating the public.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Clearly, the Clinton Administration effort is windowdressing  and does
little to curb the rising costs and inefficiencies of  regulation. The
Administration is not being completely honest with  the American public when it
claims to be reinventing regulation  but goes about implementing new, burdensome
regulations about  as fast as it can take old ones off the books.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The Clinton Administration also has done little to change the  way in which
federal agencies regulate the public. In fact, it has  worked tirelessly to
block the enactment of comprehensive reform  legisla
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 20 -->  tion that would codify many of
the principles found in  the President's executive order; the Administration
continues to  take the position that fundamental reform can and should be 
achieved through administrative change, not through statute.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>THE 103RD CONGRESS</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>During the 103rd Congress, Members became more serious  about easing the
burden of federal red tape. Even though the  Democratic leadership and the White
House ultimately killed the main  reform efforts of 1994, four reform measures
either passed one house  of Congress or received serious consideration by
congressional  committees; until 1994, none of these measures was even given a 
hearing by the committee of jurisdiction. The proposals were  intended to reduce
the paperwork and regulatory burdens on  businesses, evaluate the economic and
employment impact of regulation,  and curb unfunded federal mandates. While
federal regulations  would continue to impose costs, the legislative proposals
were  intended to force Congress and the executive branch to consider more 
thoroughly the economic impact of proposed legislation and  regulation.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>In 1994, unlike past years, a strong grass-roots coalition  helped rally
bipartisan support for these bills and convinced  reluctant committee chairmen
that they could no longer block the  legislation. The business community became
a key part of this  coalition by actively supporting measures aimed at
controlling the  regulatory burden. Adding extra impetus to this effort was a 
powerful coalition of state and local officials who organized themselves  into a
potent political force to fight onerous federal regulations  and Washington
mandates that fail to provide the funding to  imple
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 21 -->  ment them. In the end, however,
the efforts of these groups  were not enough to keep the congressional Democrats
and the  White House from blocking passage of any legislation.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>THE 104TH CONGRESS</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Regulatory reform became a real political possibility with  the 104th
Congress. As part of the Contract With America, the  Republican majority made
one of its promises the passage of a number  of reforms designed to enhance
private property rights (see  Chapter 4) and economic liberty and make
government more  accountable for the burdens it imposes on individuals and
businesses.  During the first 100 days, Congress enacted and President Clinton 
signed into law two of its reform priorities:
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>The Unfunded Mandates Reform Act of 1995.</B> The federal  government
increasingly has been involved in activities considered to  be state and local
in nature. In response to the increasingly  hostile reaction of states and
localities to unchecked and costly  federal mandates, Congress enacted the
Unfunded Mandates Reform  Act of 1995 (Public Law 100-4), in March 1995. The Act
represents  &quot;a bipartisan agreement that something is wrong with American 
federalism as it has evolved in recent  years.&quot; <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt3.htm#47">47</A></B></TT>  The Act establishes a
$50 million threshold on the costs Congress and regulatory  agencies can impose
on state and local governments. A &quot;mandate&quot;  includes any requirement
that a state take an action, under the  threat of penalties or loss of
assistance, that would increase state and  local costs beyond existing levels.
New and reauthorized  legislation would have to specify how programs would be
funded. The  law also requires the Congressional Budget Office to issue an 
analysis of each piece of legislation containing a federal mandate.  The 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 22 -->  analysis must describe the
mandate, specify its expected cost  to state and local governments, and state
whether it is to be partly  or entirely funded.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>In January 1996, the Advisory Council on Intergovernment  Relations (ACIR),
which is tasked under the Act to &quot;investigate  and review the role of
federal mandates in intergovernmental  relations,&quot; issued a preliminary
report with recommendations to  Congress for addressing existing federal
mandates on state and  local governments. State and localities identified more
than 200  separate mandates affecting them which involve more than 170  federal
laws. Among ACIR recommendations: revise the Safe  Drinking Water Act, the Clean
Air Act, and the Endangered Species Act  to promote greater flexibility and
increased consultation betwen  the federal government and states and localities,
and modify  the Americans with Disabilities Act and the Clean Water Act to 
reduce budgetary and administrative constraints. <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt3.htm#48">48</A></B></TT>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>The Paperwork Reduction Act of 1995.</B> Intent on lessening  the burden
imposed by the federal government on individuals  and businesses, the 104th
Congress voted overwhelmingly to pass  the Paperwork Reduction Act of 1995, and
President Clinton signed  it into law on May 22, 1995. The Office of Information
and  Regulatory Affairs (OIRA) in the White House Office of  Management and
Budget (OMB) is responsible for implementing the Act's  objectives. In March
1995, the Office of Management and  Budget estimated that Americans spend more
than 6.4 billion hours  during fiscal year 1994 filling out forms, answering
survey questions,  and compiling records for the federal government.<TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt3.htm#49">49</A></B></TT>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The law, which came into effect in October 1995, sets a  govern
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 23 -->  ment-wide paperwork reduction
goal of 10 percent in each of  the first two years after its enactment and 5
percent from fiscal  1998 through 2001. It also reauthorizes for six years the
Office of  Information and Regulatory Affairs, which remains responsible for 
carrying out the law. The Act's most controversial provision  would overturn a
1990 Supreme Court decision holding that OMB's  authority under the Paperwork
Reduction Act of 1980 did not  extend to regulations forcing businesses to
provide information to  third parties, including employees and the public. The 
reauthorization provides that all third-party paperwork requirements will be 
approved by OMB, and this is expected to increase OMB's review  of paperwork by
50 percent.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Corrections Day.</B> A regular Corrections Day has been  established for
passing corrective and non-controversial legislation with  bipartisan
supermajorities (three-fifths). Through this process,  Congress is able to
revise regulations that have become outdated or  obsolete, correct agency
errors, or simply eliminate regulations that do  not make any sense. In the
House, the Speaker's Correction Day  Advisory Group, chaired by Representative
Barbara Vucanovich  (R-NV), reviews and recommends legislative proposals for 
consideration under the Corrections Calendar. Bills on the calendar can  be
considered at the discretion of the Speaker of the House on  the second and
fourth Tuesday of each month. The following are  two examples of bills passed by
one or both houses of Congress:
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>The Federal Reports Elimination and Sunset Act (S.790)</B>
to  abolish or reduce the statutory requirement for a list of over 200 
congressionally mandated reports, and to require the President to  submit his
own list of unnecessary or wasteful reports in his next  budget request
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 24 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>The Edible Oil Regulatory Reform Act (H.R. 436)</B> to require  the
government to differentiate between petroleum oils and animal  and vegetable
fats, oils, and greases. The Oil Pollution Act of  1990 places prohibitive
financial requirements on oils and does not  distinguish between non-toxic,
biodegradable animal and  vegetable oils, which are less of an environmental
hazard, and  petroleum products. The Department of Transportation was going to 
implement the Act through regulations that would have required  24 hours of
hazardous material classroom and field training for  workers who responded to
butter or salad oil spill emergencies.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Congressional Accountability and Regulatory Relief for  Small Business.
</B>In response to the recommendations of the White  House Conference on Small
Business, Senator Christopher Bond  (R-MO), chairman of the Senate Small
Business Committee,  sponsored S. 942, the Small Business Regulatory Enforcement
 Fairness Act of 1996. This bill passed the Senate with a vote of 100 to 0  on
March 19, 1996. The bill authorizes judicial enforcement of  the Regulatory
Flexibility Act of 1980, allows small business to  recoup expenses and legal
fees incurred when agencies make  excessive demands for penalties that cannot be
sustained in court  and provides for an independent ombudsman to receive 
confidential complaints from small businesses about their dealings with  federal
regulators. In addition, the bill was amended by Senator  Nickles (R-OK) and
Senator Reid (D-NV) to allow Congress 60 days  to review agency regulations.
This amendment effectively  incorporated a previously approved Senate bill (S.
219) that provided  for such congressional review. The House already had passed
a  similar small business legislation (S. 926) in March 1995. The  House and
Senate finalized the bill and attached it to legislation to  raise 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 25 -->  the debt ceiling. The President
signed the bill on March 29, 1996.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Industry Deregulation</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The 104th Congress succeeded in passing the  Communications Act of 1995,
signed into law by President Clinton on February  8, 1996, which is the most
important industry-wide deregulatory  initiative undertaken by Congress in over
a decade. The Act  removes unnecessary layers of federal rules governing
telephone, cable  and broadcasting competition. Specifically, the Act  
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>Removes</B> restrictions on competition between local and 
long-distance telephone companies, as well as cable companies, so  that they may
eventually enter each other's business;
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Will eventually eliminate</B> the disastrous 1992 Cable Act rate 
regulations;
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Loosens</B> ownership restrictions on broadcasters and expand  the
amount of the national audience one station is allowed to reach;
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Enables</B> the Federal Communications Commission to eliminate  or
greatly ease regulations on industry segments that are shown to  be effectively
competitive.
</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>Although the legislation is an important step, more extensive  initiatives
are still needed to eliminate subsidies and regulations,  end the socialization
of wireless spectrum management, and curtail  the powers of the Federal
Communications Commission.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Unfortunately, other important legislative regulatory reform  efforts have
been stalled by the Democratic congressional leadership  and 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 26 -->  the White House.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Four other important reform proposals also were considered by  the 104th
Congress:
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>1. A Moratorium on Regulation.</B> After the November 1994  election,
Republican Members of Congress asked President Clinton  to freeze new federal
rulemaking during the first 100 days of the  new Congress. When President
Clinton refused, the House of  Representatives passed H.R. 450, the Regulatory
Transition Act of  1995, which would freeze regulatory activity retroactively
from  November 20, 1994, until 1996 or the passage of regulatory reform 
legislation. The purpose of the bill was to provide for a &quot;time-out&quot; 
period, during which Congress and the Administration could  debate and study the
large number of regulations currently being  developed and evaluate proposed
efforts to reform the way in  which regulatory decisions are made and
implemented. Although  the Senate bill started out the same way, a substitute
bill requiring  that all federal rules lie before Congress for 45 days to be
reviewed  and &quot;vetoed&quot; before becoming final ultimately was passed. 
Because the two versions turned out to be significantly different, the 
House-Senate conference on the bills stalled.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>2. Comprehensive Regulatory Reform.</B> Just two months into  the first
session of the 104th Congress, the House passed H.R. 1022  on February 28, 1995.
Although the Contract With America was  a Republican election platform, H.R.
1022 was passed with a  substantial bipartisan majority. The purpose of the bill
is to impose  a requirement  on existing statutes and new regulations  that  the
risks, costs, and benefits be considered before implementation  of new rules.
Where the estimated economic impact is $25 million  or 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 27 -->  more agencies would be required
to conduct risk assessment,  as necessary, before regulations take effect. In
addition, they  would be required to evaluate the costs and benefits associated
with  the set of regula-tory alternatives, including no government action;  to
show that the benefits outweigh the costs and that the net  benefits to society
would be greater under the proposed rule than  under alternatives; and to assess
the effect on businesses with fewer  than 100 employees and the effect on
employment. A federal  agency's compliance with the requirements of H.R. 1022
would be  judicially reviewable under the statute granting the agency the 
authority to act and, where applicable, under the Administrative  Procedures
Act.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Unfortunately, comprehensive regulatory reform proposals in  the Senate were
killed by the Democrats and the White House.  Two bills in the Senate were the
focus of the debate. The  Comprehensive Regulatory Reform Act of 1995, S. 343,
sponsored by  Senator Robert Dole (R-KS), started out prescribing the risk and 
cost-benefit studies in a manner similar to that found in H.R. 1022. The  bill
also would allow citizens to petition agencies to apply  cost-benefit analysis
to regulations already on the books. The Regulatory  Reform Act of 1995, S. 291,
sponsored by Senator William Roth  (R-DE), was less prescriptive, giving federal
agencies more latitude  to make regulatory decisions. The standard for weighing
the  costs and benefits of regulation also was less stringent than in the 
original S. 343. Eventually, the Senate's efforts focused on S. 343,  and the
Democrats and the Clinton Administration were successful  in negotiating changes
with Senate Republicans that severely  weakened the bill relative to similar
provisions found in H.R.  1022. Despite the concessions to Democrats, supporters
of the bill  were unable to garner the necessary 60 votes to impose cloture on 
de
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 28 -->  bate, and the bill stalled in the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>3. &quot;Sunset&quot; and Review.</B> Many believe the regulatory 
system would be more reasonable if the law required that agencies  review and
revise their rules periodically and if those regulations not  re-evaluated
within the prescribed time could no longer be  enforced. Senator Dole's
comprehensive regulatory reform bill  contained &quot;sunset&quot; and review
provisions. In March 1996, the House  attempted to incorporate a bill sponsored
by Representative  David McIntosh (R-IN) that would require agency review of 
regulations into a package of reforms that included small business relief  and
congressional accountability. Strong opposition to this type of  review, from
the White House, House Democrats, and public  interest groups, brought the
renewed House effort to move even a  modest regulatory bill in 1996 to a
standstill. The Senate then moved  forward with a bill that included
congressional accountability  and small business relief. This was conferenced
with an earlier  House-passed bill that did not include administrative review
and was  sent to the President and signed on March 29, 1996.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>WHAT TO DO IN 1997</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Congress must pursue regulatory reform efforts that not  only streamline the
way in which the federal government issues  rules, but also improve the
underlying scientific data, information,  and analysis used to make decisions
about how or whether to  regulate. A major reason regulation imposes such
tremendous costs is  that Congress and the executive branch often regulate
without  adequately weighing the burdens placed on employers and the  increased
cost to the economy in terms of jobs and  competitiveness. The following reforms
can build upon existing regulatory  review 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 29 -->  mechanisms to force the
government to prioritize regulations,  assess their costs and benefits, and
adopt the least burdensome  approaches.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Strengthen White House oversight of executive branch agencies.
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Executive branch agencies are required to submit proposed  regulations to
the Office of Information and Regulatory Affairs  (OIRA) within the Office of
Management and Budget. OIRA was  created by the 1980 Paperwork Reduction Act to
reduce federal  paperwork burdens, and President Reagan added to OIRA's 
responsibilities by issuing an executive order requiring executive branch 
agencies to submit proposed regulations to it for review. But if the  White
House does not make deregulation a priority, OIRA allows  agencies a long leash.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Legislation should be adopted to establish OIRA's statutory  authority and
responsibility to review regulation. Because  OIRA's regulatory review function
currently is derived solely from  executive order, a new Administration that
disagrees with this  function could withdraw it simply by revoking the
applicable  order. OIRA's authority also should be expanded beyond the  existing
executive orders to cover rulemaking by independent  agencies such as the
Federal Communications Commission and  Securities and Exchange Commission.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Establish in statute a set of principles to guide  regulatory
decisionmaking.
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The regulatory process needs to be reformed so that scarce  economic
resources can be allocated more efficiently to achieve  the 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 30 -->  most good. The concept of smarter
regulation is an important  one to understand in the regulatory reform 
debate.50  The following principles are key elements of this concept:
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>Cost-benefit analysis.</B> Federal agencies should be
required  to evaluate the costs and benefits of all new regulations. Critics 
will argue that costs and benefits can be difficult to identify or hard  to
quantify, and this may be true. Nevertheless, it is very useful  to begin to get
agencies to think more systematically about the  economic impact of new
regulations by requiring an accounting  and weighing of costs and benefits, to
the extent possible, in  making their decisions.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Sound science.</B> Federal agencies should be required to use the  most
advanced and precise scientific methods to calculate the risk  estimates that
form the basis for agency decisions, and  regulations should be updated to
reflect changes in that scientific  knowledge. Unfortunately, agencies use
extremely conservative or  worst-case assumptions to make up for the lack of
data and high degree  of scientific uncertainty that characterize the current
risk  assessment process.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Risk assessment and risk management.</B> Risk assessment  methods need
to be improved (for example, by using sound science),  and agencies need to
establish a clear distinction between  assessing risks and deciding how to
manage them. Federal agencies  should work closely with the scientific community
to improve risk  assessment guidelines. Today, agencies too often allow policy 
decisions about how to manage risk to influence the determination of  risk. Only
when a risk is identified should a policy decision about  how to handle it be
made.
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 31 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Risk-based priorities and public education.</B> Government has a 
responsibility to inform the public of risks and to minimize the  distortion and
exaggeration of those risks. By using risk  comparisons, federal agencies can
help the public understand the familiar  risks they face every day, such as
being struck by lighting, and  how these compare with unfamiliar risks, such as
exposure to a  particular chemical in the community.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Market incentives and performance standards.</B> Whenever  regulation is
necessary, it should be accomplished to the extent  possible by setting a goal
and allowing the market to decide how it  will achieve that goal. For example,
instead of requiring businesses  to use specific technology to reduce pollution,
a regulation  should mandate the amount of pollution reduction and allow
businesses  to decide how they will achieve that reduction. Each business  then
has the freedom and the incentive to adopt the least costly  means of achieving
the goal for itself, minimizing the total cost  burden that compliance imposes
on the economy. In contrast,  command-and-control regulations provide no
incentive for the regulated  entity to exceed a regulatory goal.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Establish a regulatory budget.
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The President and Congress should establish a federal  regulatory budget
that places a ceiling on the total estimated cost that can  be imposed on the
economy each year by all federal regulations.  If the budget total was reached
by existing regulations, an  agency wishing to add a regulation with further
costs would have to  repeal or modify an existing regulation imposing the same
or greater  cost. A regulatory budget would place a politically accountable
limit  on 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 32 -->  the total burden that could be
imposed on the economy by  federal regulation. It also would give agencies a
strong incentive to  review existing regulations to discover which could be
safely  eliminated or modified to reduce costs. Overall, government would be 
forced to prioritize its regulations and abolish the least beneficial. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Require federal agencies to review existing regulations to  ensure that
they meet sound regulatory principles. 
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P>If Congress codifies a set of principles for smarter regulation,  it also
should require that federal regulators go back and review  all existing
regulations to make sure they also meet those principles.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Deregulate specific industries.
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Although reform of the regulatory decisionmaking process is  necessary,
policymakers also should continue to push for  deregulation of specific
industries. In the late 1970s and early 1980s,  Congress deregulated several
industries, including the airline, railway,  and interstate trucking industries
and natural gas. The 104th  Congress succeeded in making 1996 the year we see
significant  deregulation of the telecommunications industry. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The Congress should continue the success of the 104th  Congress and take
action to deregulate the following industries:
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>Banking.</B> Congress should continue to deregulate the
banking  industry. Three specific areas of banking regulation need to be 
addressed. First, structural restrictions such as the Glass-Steagall  Act of
1933 retard bank stability and expansion and limit the  credit opportunities
banks can offer to businesses. Second, the  current 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 33 -->  federal deposit insurance system
is a government-operated  safety net that distorts the banking industry at a
great cost to the  taxpayer. Finally, direct banking regulations such as the
Community  Reinvestment Act (CRA) cost consumers and businesses millions  of
dollars each year without correcting the perceived problems  which they are
meant to cure. Banking deregulation will mean that  consumers benefit from being
able to make more profitable  investments, and businesses benefit from the more
efficient flow of  capital through the financial sector.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Utilities.</B> Policymakers should completely overhaul  regulation
within utilities markets. All consumers should have the right  to purchase
electric services in competitive markets, but  customer choice in electricity
requires the deregulation of the existing  monopoly-controlled industry. The
Federal Power Act and the  Public Utility Holding Company Act are the major
federal statutes  that require the regulation of existing electric utility
monopolies.  Competition, not regulation, is the best way to spur innovation and
 the development of new technologies and services. Opening up  the utilities
market will mean lower cost energy that helps spur  economic growth, create
jobs, increase productivity, and improve  international competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>The Maritime Industry.</B> Congress should repeal the Jones  Act
(Section 27 of the Merchant Marine Act of 1920), which  increases the
transportation costs of many U.S. businesses by requiring  that when their
merchandise is transported entirely or partly by  water between United States
points  either directly or via a  foreign point  it must travel in US. - built,
U.S.-flagged,  U.S.-manned, and U.S.-owned vessels. That monopoly raises costs.
No  other U.S. industry has such a costly lock on the economy. In  addition, 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 34 -->  the Jones Act contains liability
provisions that expose ships,  shipyards, terminals, and other companies in the
marine industry  to onerous open-ended liability claims.
</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>Repeal of the Jones Act should remove the prohibitive  doing-business
restrictions that require all domestic waterborne cargo to  be carried on
U.S.-flagged, owned, manned, and built vessels. In  addition, the rigid labor
(crewing) requirements and labor pool  restrictions on U.S.-flagged ships should
be removed to  improve industry flexibility and increase productivity.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><A NAME="Q&A">Q &amp; A</A></B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Q. Isn't regulatory &quot;reform&quot; just another way of saying &quot;let's
 roll back twenty years of health, safety and environmental protection?&quot;
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>A.</B> No. Regulatory reform is an attempt to bring common sense  to the
way federal agencies make decisions about whether and how  to regulate.
Effective regulatory reform means smarter  regulation. One of the consequences
of making smarter decisions is that  we may decide a regulation is not needed,
and this means  reducing regulation. Republicans, like Democrats, want clean
air, clean  water, and safe food and consumer products. Unfortunately,  however,
federal regulators have not done a very good job of allocating  our scarce
economic resources efficiently to achieve these goals.  By making sure that
regulators sensibly and consistently  evaluate risks, compare them to the types
of risk faced by people every  day (such as driving a car or getting hit by
lightning), and consider  the costs and benefits of their actions, we can do an
even better  job protecting the environment and public health and safety  while
spending less.
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 35 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Q. What role should the federal government play in regulation?
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>A. </B>Most Americans want society to regulate who can be a  doctor or
who can fly an airplane, or to decide what pharmaceuticals  are safe enough to
be placed on open shelves. But most also  would agree that there are good and
bad regulations, some that  make sense and others that are silly and
incomprehensible, and that  the benefits of some are simply not worth the cost,
while others  provide no benefit at all. The federal government should be 
required to consider certain questions about regulations to make sure  they
achieve their intended purposes. These questions include  whether the benefits
outweigh the costs, whether the level of risk  justifies the cost, whether the
regulatory solution being chosen  minimizes the disruption of the free market,
and whether the regulation  is understandable and easy to implement.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Q. How do you decide when the benefits of a regulation  outweigh its
costs?  For example, how can you decide how much one life  is worth?
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>A.</B> Many ordinary daily activities pose a greater threat to  human
life than the hazards that are regulated. Such risks as driving  without a
seatbelt, which individuals can control, generally pose a  far greater risk than
certain pesticides. Yet the public focuses on  the risk from pesticide. A
10-minute bicycle ride poses the same  risk of death  one-in-a-million  as the
lifetime cancer risk  from wood-preserving chemicals. But only the latter is
regulated.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Because society has limited resources, it makes sense to  apply them where
the risks are greatest. Environmental regulation  alone 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 36 -->  now costs America approximately
$170 billion annually.  That means lost jobs, which can pose a far greater risk
to the health  of an individual than many of the problems currently targeted  by
regulations intended to protect health. Thus, it is not a case of  putting an
acceptable &quot;price&quot; on a life, but of determining how  much risk is
avoided by one expenditure as opposed to another. Is  health improved more by
forcing firms to spend money on certain  costly pollution controls, for
instance, or by leaving them free to  spend the same money creating jobs and
improving living standards,  or even hiring more police?  A better appreciation
of risk and cost  has led both Democrats and Republicans to support prioritizing
 risks so that the nation's limited resources are used to deal with  the
greatest threats to human health.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Q. What can be done to relieve the tax, paperwork, and other  regulatory
burdens on small businesses?
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>A.</B> The message from small business owners is loud and clear:  The
federal government gets in the way of their ability to survive  and thrive.
Following through on tax and regulatory reform will  give small businesses the
relief they need to create jobs and expand  the tax base. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Today's tax system is a disgrace (see Chapter 2). Billions of  hours are
spent each year to comply with an increasingly  incomprehensible maze of tax
forms, regulations, and documents. In  addition, the current system of
deductions and loopholes is too easily  manipulated by special interests for
their own advantage.  Although the 1995 tax legislation makes a small step
toward easing  these problems, the need for fundamental reform is compelling. A 
flat tax would resolve many of the tax problems we face today. It  rep
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 37 -->  resents a straightforward, fair
system that can be implemented  by two simple postcards, one for individuals and
one for businesses.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Similarly, small businesses today face increasing federal  regulatory
burdens. Too often, command-and-control,  one-size-fits-all federal regulations
put small businesses at a disadvantage.  The cost of compliance falls
disproportionately on small  businesses. The 104th Congress took action to
correct these problems by  passing a small business regulatory reform bill in
March 1996.  This legislation takes step to make sure the economic impact of 
regulation on small businesses is taken into consideration. This  includes
evaluating the economic impact of regulations on small  businesses as well as
ensuring that small business interests are  adequately represented in the
development of regulations. Small  businesses, like any other businesses, also
should have the right to  challenge federal regulations in court, and courts
must have the ability  both to block the implementation of harmful and costly
regulations  and to require agencies to reconsider them. 
</P>
<P>
