<HEAD>
<TITLE>Environment - Issues 96 - Heritage</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<center>
<h2>Issues '96: The Candidate's Briefing Book</h2>
<b><A HREF="/heritage">The Heritage Foundation</a></b>
</center><p>
<h3>Chapter 4</h3>
<center><h2>
ENVIRONMENT
</H2>
<CITE><B>By John Shanahan</B></CITE>
<P><A HREF="chpt4.html#ISSUES">The Issues</A> | <A HREF="chpt4.html#FACTS">The Facts</A> |  <A HREF="chpt4.html#RECORD">The Record</A> | <A HREF="chpt4.html#Q&A">Q&amp;A</A> | <A HREF="chpt4.html#SELECTED">Selected Heritage Foundation Studies
</A> | <a href="chpt4.html#EXP">Experts</a> 

</CENTER>
<P>
<a href="envir_1.gif">Chart 1</a>: How America's Air Is Getting Cleaner<br>
<a href="envir_2.gif">Chart 2</a>: The Myth of Global Warming<br>
<a href="envir_3.gif">Chart 3</a>: Endangered Species Act Doesn't Save Species<br>
<a href="envir_4.gif">Chart 4</a>: Land Required for Current Level of Food Production<br>
<p>
<P><B><A NAME="ISSUES">THE ISSUES
</A></B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Americans want a clean, healthy environment. They also want  a strong
economy. But environmental protection is enormously  expensive, costs jobs, and
stifles economic opportunity. On the  other hand, before government stepped in,
robust economic activity  such as manufacturing led to a deteriorating and
unhealthy  environment. The challenge is how to achieve both a strong economy 
and a healthy environment. After all, what Americans actually want  is a high
overall quality of life.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Three decades ago, as people perceived that their quality of  life was
beginning to deteriorate, they began to support  aggressive policies to reduce
pollution. These policies frequently failed to  live up to their sponsors'
claims; they also became increasingly  and unnecessarily expensive. But the
environment did improve,  especially in the early years. Now, however, Americans
are  becoming aware that many of these policies are unreasonable and that,  even
when they work, they result only in small improvements at a  heavy cost in jobs
and freedom. Americans also are beginning to  recognize that there often is no
sound scientific basis for assertions  of environmental harm or risk to the
public. The pendulum  finally has begun to swing the other way. 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 2 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Conservatives, like Americans generally, have no wish to return  to the days
of black smoke billowing out of smokestacks. But they  do believe common sense
can be brought to bear in dealing with  the environment: that it is possible to
protect the environment  without sacrificing the freedoms for which America
stands.  Conservative candidates and legislators therefore should stress the 
following themes:
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>Examples of regulatory abuse.</B> It is important to show
that  &quot;good intentions&quot; often are accompanied by oppressive, senseless
 regulations.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>An ethic of conservation.</B> Candidates need to explain that 
conserving  or efficiently using  natural resources is not in dispute.  The
debate is over how best to do this: through markets or  through government
controls.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Economic freedom.</B> Candidates need to point out that many  government
&quot;solutions&quot; to environmental problems conflict with  basic economic
freedoms. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Property-based solutions.</B> Candidates need to explain that 
environmental objectives can be achieved best not by issuing thousands  of pages
of rules that people will try to circumvent, but by  capitalizing on the
incentives associated with owning property.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Sound science.</B> Candidates need to argue that we need  policies based
on sound science, not &quot;tabloid science.&quot;
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Priority setting.</B> Candidates must explain that not all problems  are
of the same importance or urgency, and that regulating all  risks 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 3 -->  equally means fewer lives are
saved for the dollars spent  than would be saved if priorities were set.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><A NAME="FACTS">THE FACTS</A></B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>While pollution levels have fallen dramatically since 1970,  most reductions
were achieved early and at relatively low cost.  From 1970 to 1990, total
emission levels fell 33.8 percent. Over  the same period, lead levels in the air
fell 96.5 percent, and  carbon monoxide levels in the air fell 40.7 percent. But
reductions  have slowed dramatically.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>As recently as 1985, the annual cost of environmental  protection was $82
billion. Since then, it has more than doubled to $171  billion, while
environmental gains have slowed to a trickle. The  estimated $171 billion spent
in 1995 represents about 3 percent  of America's gross domestic product (GDP).
Put another way,  these poorly crafted environmental regulations cost each 
American household almost $1,800 per year. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The pattern is consistent: What economists call the marginal  rate of return
on investment falls dramatically as government runs  out of easy fixes and then
attempts to eke out minuscule  improvements in the environment at skyrocketing
extra cost. The resulting  drain on the economy is both enormous and
unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Unworkable Regulations</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Environmental regulation does more than just cost too much.  Candidates also
should use the growing litany of horror stories to  demonstrate how
ill-conceived environmental regulations, while  deliv
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 4 -->  ering little benefit, lead to
unintended consequences for  businesses  especially small businesses, which are
disproportionately  minority-owned and minority-run.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     Larry Mason's family owned a
sawmill employing 40 workers  in Beaver, Washington. In the mid-1980s, based on
harvest  assurances from the U.S. Forest Service and loan guarantees from  the
Small Business Administration, the family invested $1 million  in its business.
Then, says Mason, &quot;in 1990, the spotted owl  injunctions closed our mill,
made my equipment worthless, and my  expertise obsolete. The same government
that encouraged me to  take on business debt then took away my ability to 
repay.&quot; <TT><B><A HREF="ftnt4.htm#1">1</A></B></TT>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     While the Clean Water Act (CWA) requires a waste
treatment  facility to submit a simple form stating that a fence restricts 
access by the public, the Resource Conservation and Recovery  Act (RCRA)
requires an additional 25 pages detailing the fence  design, the location of the
posts and gates, a cross section of the  wire mesh, and other minor technical
matters. RCRA is so wasteful  that one plant, whose CWA permit application was
only 17 pages  long, had to file a seven-foot stack of supporting documents with
 its application.<TT><B><A HREF="ftnt4.htm#2">2</A></B></TT>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     Ronald Cahill, a disabled Wilmington,
Massachusetts, dry  cleaner, purchased expensive dry-cleaning equipment to
comply with  EPA regulations governing the use of trichlorotrifluoroethane 
(CFC-113). But the EPA levied a tax on all chlorofluorocarbons  (CFCs), making
CFC-113 hard to find and extremely expensive. In  1995, Cahill's business went
under. Washington, says Cahill, &quot;has  put me out of business with excessive
taxes and  regulations.&quot;<TT><B><A HREF="ftnt4.htm#3">3</A></B></TT>
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 5 --> 
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>Regulatory abuses like these usually are a direct result of the  way
government bureaucracies attack environmental problems.  Typically, these
agencies regulate without regard to the cost  imposed on individuals and
businesses. Yet it makes no sense to issue  a regulation for which the burden
far outweighs any benefit  that might be conferred. In fact, it often is unclear
whether there will  be any benefit at all because the science on which many 
regulations are based is so poor.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Also, instead of setting realistic performance standards and  giving
businesses the freedom to develop innovative ways of  meeting them, agencies
typically rely on inflexible  command-and-control regulations that, for example,
specify what technologies  companies must use. Since businesses differ in their
operating  structures, this one-size-fits-all approach rarely leads to
cost-effective  solutions compared to more flexible and dependable performance 
standards. Moreover, by eliminating the incentive for companies  to seek out
these cost-effective solutions, it stifles innovative  technologies or
techniques that reduce costs. In the end, of course,  the consumer is the one
who pays.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Perhaps the most troublesome aspect of current  environmental policy is the
fact that bureaucrats and liberal lawmakers  generally consider regulation the
only option. Creative solutions shown to  be less expensive, more effective, and
more respectful of human  liberty are rejected out of hand. Instead of setting
up a system of  incentives to lure businesses into operating with environmental 
impact in mind, the system relies on punishment regardless  of whether this
accomplishes the desired goal or creates  unintended consequences. 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 6 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Rejecting Property Rights</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Regulations have become increasingly unfair. The  Environmental Protection
Agency (EPA), Department of the Interior (DOI),  Army Corps of Engineers, and
other federal agencies operate on  the premise that property should be used to
satisfy government's  needs and objectives without regard to who owns the
property or the  financial burden imposed on them. It is this mentality that 
leads government reflexively to reject the creative solutions advanced  by
free-market advocates, including incentive-based approaches  to protecting
endangered species. By ignoring property rights,  establishment
environmentalists, bureaucrats, and liberal legislators  also ignore the
benefits to be derived from free trade and free markets.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The most unfair and burdensome hardship inflicted by  government &quot;regulatory
takings&quot; is that property owners are not  compensated for their losses. For
instance, if an elderly husband and wife  spend a large portion of their
retirement savings to buy land on which  to build their dream home and that land
subsequently is designated  a wetland, they lose the value of their property as
well as their  savings. They are stuck with property they cannot use and the 
government does nothing to reimburse them for their loss.  Unfortunately, tales
of financial hardship caused by government designation  of land as wetland or
endangered-species habitat have become  common. For instance:
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B><CITE>- </CITE></B>    Bill Stamp's family in Exeter,
Rhode Island, has been  blocked from farming or developing its 70 acres of land
for 11 years,  yet has been assessed taxes at rates determined by the land's 
industrial value  up to $72,000 annually. As a result, this  fifth-generation
farm family may lose its life savings. The government,  however, 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 7 -->  appears unmoved. Stamp relates
what one Army Corps of  Engineers enforcement officer told him: &quot;We know
that this is  rape, pillage, and plunder of your farm, but this is our  job.&quot;
<TT><B><A HREF="ftnt4.htm#4">4</A></B></TT>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     A small church in Waldorf, Maryland, was told by
the Army  Corps of Engineers that one-third of its land, on which it planned to 
build a parking lot, was a wetland and could not be used. Part of this 
so-called wetland is a bone-dry hillside which almost never  collects water.
Says Reverend Murray Southwell of the Freewill  Baptists, &quot;this obvious
misinterpretation of wetland law made it  necessary for us to purchase an
additional lot [for $45,000, which] has been  a heavy financial burden on this
small missions  church.&quot; <A HREF="ftnt4.htm#5">5
</A></P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     Developer Buzz Oates wants to develop less than
4 percent of  the Sutter Basin in Sacramento, California, where an estimated 
1,000 giant garter snakes live. But the federal government mandated  that he pay
a &quot;mitigation&quot; fee of nearly $3.8 million for the 40 or  fewer snakes
he might disturb: $93,950 per snake. Says Oates, in an  age of &quot;depleted
[fiscal] resources and deteriorating school  infrastructure, this is a very
tough pill to  swallow.&quot;
<TT><B><A HREF="ftnt4.htm#6">6</A></B></TT>
</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>Hundreds of such stories have surfaced over the past few  years, and many
analysts suspect that far more are never made  public. According to Bob Adams,
Project Director for Environmental  and Regulatory Affairs at the National
Center for Public Policy  Research, &quot;the stories we have compiled are just
the tip of the  iceberg, but many people are simply too scared to come forward 
or feel powerless against the government.&quot; <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt4.htm#7">7</A></B></TT>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Ironically, federal agencies and the Clinton Administration  argue that it
would cost too much money to compensate  landowners. 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 8 -->  Leon Panetta, then Director of the
Office of Management  and Budget, told the House Committee on Public Works  and
Transportation's Subcommittee on Water Resources and the  Environment on May 26,
1994, that paying compensation for  wetlands regulation would be &quot;an
unnecessary and unwise use of  taxpayer dollars&quot; and a drain on the federal
budget.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Property owners counter that regulatory takings are a drain on  the family
budget. Nancie Marzulla, President of Defenders of  Property Rights, points out
that &quot;what people don't realize is that  these landowners typically are not
wealthy and powerful  corporations, but normal Americans  schoolteachers and
elderly couples   whose lives are destroyed by stretched interpretations of a 
single environmental law.&quot; <TT><B><A HREF="ftnt4.htm#8">8</A></B></TT>
 Moreover, the federal government  already owns about one out of every three
acres in the country (with  even more owned by state and local governments).
<A HREF="ftnt4.htm#9">9</A>  If the federal  government can
afford to maintain one-third of the nation's land,  it should be able to pay
landowners for regulatory confiscation  of their property. If not, maybe it
should consider selling the  least ecologically sensitive land from its vast
holdings to pay for  the land it wants. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Lost Opportunities, Lost Lives</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Ask the average American how much a human life is worth,  and the answer
likely will be that &quot;no amount is too much.&quot;  This  is how Congress
and federal agencies justify imposing  sometimes staggering costs on businesses
to reduce the risks of death by  infinitesimal amounts. What policymakers fail
to understand is  that wasting resources in this way means not being able to use
them  in other ways that might well produce better results and save  even 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 9 -->  more lives. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>If lawmakers ever did consider which environmental policies  actually save
the most lives, they would scrap many existing  rules, freeing up resources to
be used in other ways. This  commonsense approach would lead to regulation that
is very different, in  its scope and fundamental assumptions, from that which 
burdens America today. In fact, as the following charts illustrate, if  the
private resources used to comply with federal mandates were to  be left with the
industries or individuals concerned, or used in  other ways in the local
economy, in many cases Americans would  benefit more, and far more lives would
be saved.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Ill-conceived environmental regulations designed to  &quot;protect&quot;
people may even cause deaths. The best example is the set of  Corporate Average
Fuel Economy (CAFE) standards, intended to  conserve energy and encourage lower
oil prices. The only way  auto makers can meet the CAFE standards is by building
lighter  cars. Unfortunately for drivers and passengers, however, lighter cars 
are less able to withstand the impact of crashes. The result: more  highway
deaths. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Robert Crandall of the Brookings Institution and John Graham  of the Harvard
Center for Risk Analysis have found that 2,500  highway deaths should be
expected as a result of CAFE's impact  on the weight of cars made in the 1989
model year  alone. <TT><B><A HREF="ftnt4.htm#10">10</A></B></TT>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Some environmental regulations may cause deaths indirectly.  Statistical
analyses have shown that for every $7.5 million in costs  the government imposes
on the economy, lower overall living  standards cause one additional statistical
 death. <TT><B><A HREF="ftnt4.htm#11">11</A></B></TT>  When
this formula 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 10 -->  is used to compare the number of
lives &quot;saved&quot; by a  particular environmental regulation with the
number lost through lower  living standards, it becomes obvious that many
regulations  actually increase the death toll. For example:
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>Spending $178 million</B> may avert one death under the 
diethylstilbestrol (DES) cattlefeed ban, but 24 other lives are lost due  to
lower living standards. The reason: Lower living standards  cause increased
mortality rates.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Spending $111 million</B> may avert one death under the  asbestos ban,
but 15 other lives are lost.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Spending $72 million</B> may avert one death under the uranium  mill
tailings cover rule, but 10 other lives are  lost. <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt4.htm#12">12</A></B></TT>
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>What America Thinks About the Environment</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>When asked by the media, pollsters, or politicians, Americans  routinely
answer that they want a clean and healthy environment.  Indeed, the majority of
Americans consider themselves  &quot;environmentalists.&quot;  This does not
translate, however, into automatic  acceptance of the environmental lobby's
agenda. Conservative  candidates need to make this clear to discourage voters
from  supporting policies they do not believe in simply because they are 
portrayed as &quot;pro-environment.&quot; 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The dichotomy in public opinion shows up in polling data.  When respondents
are asked general or theoretical questions that  involve little personal
sacrifice, or that do not identify those  burdened, government intervention
fares well. In one poll, for instance,  60 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 11 -->  percent of respondents agreed
that we must protect the  environment even if it costs jobs in the  community.
<TT><B><A HREF="ftnt4.htm#13">13</A></B></TT>  In another,
72 percent of respondents said they would pay somewhat higher taxes  if the
money was used to protect the environment and prevent  water and air pollution.
<TT><B><A HREF="ftnt4.htm#14">14</A></B></TT>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>On the other hand, when respondents are asked questions that  are more
specific, that involve greater sacrifice, or that identify  the people losing
jobs, government intervention is less popular.  When respondents are asked to
pay much higher taxes to protect the  environment, support drops by almost half.
By the same token,  only one-third would be willing to accept cuts in their
standard of  living. <TT><B><A HREF="ftnt4.htm#15">15</A></B></TT>
 When asked to pick between spotted owls and  Northwest workers who stand to
lose their jobs because of efforts to  protect the owls, respondents choose jobs
by a margin of 3 to  2. <TT><B><A HREF="ftnt4.htm#16">16</A></B></TT>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>More Americans than not believe that environmental  organizations are too
extreme  a perception that is partially responsible for  recent significant
declines in membership among these groups.  Perhaps the most consistent finding
is that Americans think EPA  is doing a poor job: More than two-thirds think the
country gets  poor value for its investment in environmental  protection. <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt4.htm#17">17</A></B></TT>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Perhaps the most refreshing change in attitudes in recent years  is the
recognition that the country can have economic growth  and environmental
protection simultaneously. Vice President Al  Gore has made the point that
economic growth and environmental  protection are not incompatible. This is
true, but only if  America's environmental laws are structured correctly to
encourage  responsible behavior as part of the business decision-making 
process. Gore advocates stringent command-and-control regulations  that 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 12 -->  are inconsistent with growth and
lead to little real gains in  environmental protection. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P> Whenever this question comes up, Americans must be told  that the way to
promote both environmental protection and  economic growth is to allow them to
work hand in hand. The  government must stop regarding them as mutually
exclusive and stop  pitting economic freedom against the environment. Laws must
be  based on, and work with, a free market. Only then can Americans  maximize
their economic and environmental quality of life.
</P>
<P>The Need for Common Sense 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Given Americans' ambivalence on the question of  environmental protection,
it is all the more important for conservatives to  approach the issue in a
commonsense way. People must  understand that environmental protection need not
come at the expense  of jobs, but will cost jobs if the socialist model of
centralized  control for protecting the environment is not set aside. It doesn't
 work. Rather, the country should adopt a reasonable, commonsense  approach to
environmental protection that is based on:
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE>     Freedom with Responsibility.</B> Conservatives
traditionally  have stressed economic growth while ignoring the importance of 
environmental problems. Thus, they have fought  environmentalists step by step
and have lost step by step. The reason, while  unpleasant, is not complicated.
Environmentalists have had the moral  high ground, even though they typically
have not provided the  most beneficial solutions. In short, conservatives have
been on  the wrong side of an emotional issue. <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt4.htm#18">18</A></B></TT>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Two lessons demonstrate why. 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 13 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>First,</B> leftists and the public at large understand that
 publicly owned goods, free of constraints on usage, will be depleted  over
time. Garrett Hardin, Professor Emeritus of Human Ecology at  the University of
California, in his seminal 1968 work 
<I>The Tragedy of the Commons</I> showed that when a good is publicly owned, 
or &quot;owned&quot; in common, no one has an incentive to conserve or  to
manage it. In fact, there is a perverse incentive to use the  good inefficiently
 to deplete it. This fact is at the heart of most  environmental problems, such
as air and water pollution and  species extinction. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Second,</B> if there are incentives to conserve resources, people  will
conserve out of self-interest. People with a vested interest in  providing
environmental benefits  through property ownership  or other positive incentives
 will provide them voluntarily,  without coercion.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>When it came to certain resources like air and water,  conservatives tended
to ignore the first lesson, and consequently lost the  opportunity to implement
the second. In this one area, conservatives  have been inconsistent with the
principles that define their  movement: that decisions should be left to
individuals who are accountable  for their actions.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>&quot;Freedom with responsibility for one's actions&quot; should be the 
conservative message. Responsibility restrains wasteful  behavior. Ironically,
the old environmentalist slogan &quot;Make the  polluter pay&quot; is consistent
with this message. But when they say this,  conservatives and liberals mean
different things. As Al Cobb,  then Director of Environment and Energy at the
National Policy  Forum, 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 14 -->  has said, &quot;What the
environmental lobby means by that phrase  is that corporate polluters should be
punished severely for any  pollution whatsoever. What conservatives mean,
however, is that  polluters should bear the full cost of environmental
degradation,  but no more.&quot; <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt4.htm#19">19</A></B></TT>  At the same time,
individuals and corporations  also should be rewarded for conservation and other
 environmentally sound practices.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE>     Conservation Through Property Rights.</B> The free
market  reflects the conservation ethic better than any command-and-control 
regulation from Washington. A free market can occur, however,  only when private
citizens engage in trade, and people can trade  only what they own: some form of
property. Thus, property is the  cornerstone of a free market. If property
rights are insecure or  publicly owned, a market cannot function effectively.
Some  critics misleadingly call this &quot;market failure,&quot; but it is
really a failure  to use markets and their main engine: property rights. As a 
result, both environmental protection and personal liberty suffer. A  resource
that is not owned will deteriorate or be depleted  because neither protection of
nor damage to that resource is part of  the individual's usual decision-making
process. Others, however,  are still forced to bear the consequences.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Conservative candidates should concentrate on explaining the  innovative
ways in which property rights can be used to protect  the environment. The most
efficient method  and the most  protective of individual rights and freedoms  is
to enlist self-interest in  the service of environmental protection. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Consider some examples of how the principle of property  rights-based
environmentalism works:
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 15 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     In the decade from 1979-1989, East
and Central African  elephant herd populations dropped from more than 1 million
to less  than half that. Yet, in Zimbabwe, elephant herds have increased 
dramatically. The difference is that hunting in Zimbabwe is  permitted as a
property right. Small villages that own the land on which  elephants live and
graze charge safari operators to conduct  hunts. Since the villages profit
directly, they have an incentive to  promote herd growth to increase their
income. In surrounding  African countries, government bureaucrats seem unable to
curb  incessant poaching; in Zimbabwe, however, villagers are constantly on  the
lookout for poachers because poaching means lost income.  Zimbabwe and a few
other countries reward the conservation of  elephants by allowing the
conservationists themselves to profit  from their protective behavior. In each
country that has adopted  this approach, herd sizes are increasing.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     In Scotland and England, the popularity of
fishing has  burgeoned in recent decades. Property rights to fishing sites have 
developed as the building block for markets to provide access to prime  fishing
spots. As a result, many private, voluntary associations  have been formed to
purchase fishing rights  access. <B><TT><A
HREF="ftnt4.htm#20">20</A></TT></B>  In Scotland, &quot;virtually
every inch of every major river and most minor ones is  privately owned or
leased....&quot; <TT><B><A HREF="ftnt4.htm#21">21</A></B></TT>
Owners of fishing rights on  various stretches of the rivers charge others for
the right to fish. These  rivers are not overfished because it is not in the
owner's best  interest to allow the fish population to be depleted. Because he
wants  to continue charging fishermen for the foreseeable future, the  owner
conserves his fish stock, allowing them to reproduce, and  prevents pollution
from entering his stretch of the river. If a  municipality pollutes the water
upstream, the owner of the fishing rights can  sue 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 16 -->  for an injunction. Everyone wins,
including fishermen looking  for quality fishing with some privacy. <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt4.htm#22">22</A></B></TT>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     One group's approach to wetland protection has
shown the  power of property rights to achieve environmental goals. Ducks 
Unlimited, a group consisting of hunters and non-hunters alike, is  dedicated to
enhancing duck populations. To do this, it has  purchased property or
conservation easements with privately raised  funds. Unlike other groups (for
example, the National Wildlife  Federation) that began as organizations of
hunters and outdoorsmen  but later lost much of their original focus and joined
forces with  the more extreme elements of the environmental lobby, Ducks 
Unlimited still focuses on protecting duck  habitat. <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt4.htm#23">23</A></B></TT>  In the last 58 years, it
has raised and invested $750 million to conserve 17  million acres in Canada
alone, an effort which benefits other wildlife  as well as ducks. In 1994, it
restored or created about 50,000 acres  of wetlands. <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt4.htm#24">24</A></B></TT>  Since Ducks Unlimited
itself pays for the habitat  it protects, in many ways it embodies the essence
of the  conservative message: that the market should be allowed to determine the
 best and highest use of a good or resource  in this case, duck habitat.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>Unfortunately, property rights are under attack from the  environmental
lobby. The Fifth Amendment to the U.S.  Constitution states, &quot;nor shall
private property be taken for public use,  without just compensation,&quot; but
this has been interpreted as protection  primarily against the physical taking
of property. Most  infringements, however, involve federal decrees that deny
owners the right to  use their property as they see fit  for example, to
continue  farming. Since the courts have been unclear on the degree of 
protection property owners should have from such intrusions, legislative 
protection is needed. 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 17 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE>     Sound Science, Not Tabloid Science.</B> Before
issuing regulations  to protect health, regulators should ask whether the
science behind  a measure justifies the often enormous expenditures involved. 
Unfortunately, however, the federal government often acts in  response to strong
environmentalist-generated public pressure  without adequate scientific
justification. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     In 1989, for example, the Natural
Resources Defense Council,  actress Meryl Streep, and other activists teamed up
to create a  national panic over the pesticide Alar. The basis for the scare 
stories was a scientifically flawed 1977 study. As a result of this  misbegotten
campaign, Alar was banned and billions of dollars were  lost by the apple
industry. Most reputable scientists now admit Alar  is not dangerous. <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt4.htm#25">25</A></B></TT>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     In 1992, the National Aeronautics and Space 
Administration (NASA) reported that a hole in the Earth's protective ozone 
layer might open up over North America that spring. This  hypothetical hole,
which would have been in addition to the annual  Antarctic hole, would be caused
by chlorofluourocarbons (CFCs), a  refrigerant. After widespread media coverage
on the threat of CFCs,  the White House moved a production ban, scheduled for
the  year 2000, up to 1996, raising the cost of the ban by tens of billions  of
dollars. Unfortunately, NASA held its press conference before  it had finished
the study or subjected it to even cursory peer  review. The hypothesized ozone
hole over North America never  materialized. Nor could it have. According to
Patrick Michaels of the  Climatology Department at the University of Virginia, &quot;The
only  way you could produce an ozone hole in the high latitudes of the  Northern
Hemisphere that resembles what occurs in the Southern  Hemi
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 18 -->  sphere (where the ozone hole
occurs) would be to flatten  our mountains and submerge our continents. Then you
would  have airflow patterns similar to those that occur in the Southern 
Hemisphere, and are the ones that are required to create an  ozone hole.&quot;
<TT><B><A HREF="ftnt4.htm#26">26</A></B></TT>  One would
think NASA would know this as well.  Now, although no information other than a
thoroughly discredited  hypothesis justifies dramatically stepping up the
phaseout, the  country is redirecting its limited economic resources  at an
extra  cost of hundreds of dollars per household  because of the ban,  which is
now in place.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>Instead of merely responding to tabloid claims or politically  motivated
studies by federal agencies and environmental  organizations trying to justify
their budgets, regulations should be based on  credible scientific findings open
to public scrutiny. For instance,  agencies should use consistent methodologies
to determine risks.  Currently, they use different methods. Thus, for example,
risk  assessments by different agencies may turn up different answers as  to
whether a chemical at a particular dose level causes cancer.  Theoretically,
exposure to some level of a chemical could be found  to be both deadly and
perfectly safe. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Government assessments also should reveal the assumptions  and uncertainties
in their analyses. Typically, because of missing  data, most studies use certain
assumptions to estimate these  uncertainties. These assumptions, sometimes
unreasonably gloomy,  usually determine the conclusion reached. For instance,
sometimes an  estimate of the likely risk from some chemical is multiplied 
thousands, or even millions, of times just to be &quot;conservative.&quot;  Yet 
the analyses used to justify these enormously expensive  regulations often are
obscure as to their assumptions. Moreover, the  reports 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 19 -->  rarely reveal the level of
uncertainty involved in arriving at  their conclusions. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Whenever regulations that address risks are considered,  each agency should
be required to conduct risk assessments  if only  to aid in intelligent
decision-making  that are consistent, that  are transparent to public scrutiny,
and that fully detail their  assumptions and levels of uncertainty. Moreover,
each study should  be reviewed before a regulation is pub-lished to ensure that 
scientific guidelines are strictly followed. If federal agencies cannot  meet
even this very limited standard, it is unconscionable for them  to impose costly
standards on others.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE>     The Need To Set Priorities.</B> The economy has a
limited capacity  to absorb environmental regulations. Simply put, the country 
cannot afford to eliminate every risk. Thus, there is a trade-off:  Attempting
to regulate one risk out of existence may mean that  another risk (or other
risks) will have to be tolerated. In most cases,  the cure is worse than the
disease. Misguided and excessive  regulation can cost lives, so it is critical
that regulators recognize the costs  of their actions. Spending enormous amounts
of money to  eradicate small or even hypothetical risks means that those dollars
cannot  be used in other productive ways  public or private  that might  be of
greater benefit to the nation.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>It also makes no sense to impose burdensome costs on  consumers to regulate
chemicals that are much less dangerous than other  risks Americans accept
knowingly every day. Yet that is exactly  what the government does. For
instance, it routinely bans or  regulates chemicals  sometimes at the cost of
billions of dollars   whenever they pose a one-in-a-million chance of cancer
while  simulta
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 20 -->  neously ignoring risks hundreds
of times greater that would be  far less costly to regulate. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     The chances of dying from cancer
due to the aflotoxin in 4  tablespoons of peanut butter per day are
approximately 1 in 1,800. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     The chances of dying in a commercial aircraft
accident, for  those taking three trips annually, are approximately 1 in 6,500.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     The chances of being struck by an aircraft
suddenly falling  from the sky are 4 in a million  greater than the average 
person's chances of contracting cancer from asbestos.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>The idea of regulating peanut butter consumption and limiting  frequent
flying is ludicrous. But it demonstrates just how  unreasonable it is to
regulate risks that are thousands of times safer  simply because they are less
familiar to the public or because they  involve chemicals that are man-made
instead of naturally occurring,  such as those found naturally in peanut butter.
Regulating these  less serious risks costs the economy enormous sums while 
providing little or no benefit to those supposedly being protected.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>This is why it is essential that policymakers develop a priority  list of
environmental problems, based on the extent of the possible  risk each appears
to pose and the cost of reducing that risk to  acceptable levels. With such a
list, policymakers can know just  how much protection is being bought for every
dollar spent.  Americans finally will get the maximum environmental &quot;bang
for the buck.&quot;   Conversely, the federal government will be able to achieve
 environmental objectives at the lowest cost, and thus with the  fewest &quot;pink
slips&quot; for American workers.
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 21 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Is There an Environmental Crisis?</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Is there an environmental crisis?  The answer is a  resounding &quot;No.&quot;
 Certainly the country and planet have environmental  problems that need to be
addressed. But overall, the environment  has been improving. Unfortunately, the
public is subjected only to  the &quot;Chicken Little&quot; version of the
situation, and reports of  environmental progress and refutations of
environmental alarmists  are rarely covered in the press. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>In his 1995 book <I>A Moment on the Earth</I>, which details many  of the
improvements that have taken place in the last three  decades, <I>Newsweek</I>
editor Gregg Easterbrook notes that reports of  positive environmental
developments, such as significantly lower air  pollution in major U.S. cities,
are buried inside the  newspapers. <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt4.htm#27">27</A></B></TT>  Negative news,
meanwhile, gets front-page attention, and the  news that is reported often
contains numerous misleading &quot;facts.&quot; 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The truth is that threats to the environment have lessened  considerably.
Lead has been almost eliminated. Even in Los Angeles,  the most polluted city in
the country, levels of Volatile Organic  Compounds (VOCs) have fallen by more
than half since 1970. In  other formerly polluted cities, such as Atlanta, the
air is now  considered relatively clean as VOCs are down by almost two-thirds
and  Nitrous Oxide is down 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>In area after area  so-called global warming, endangered  species, wetlands,
pesticides, hazardous waste, and automotive  fuel economy, for example  the
problem is the same: Only rarely  are the facts heard by the American people.
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 22 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Global Warming. </B>One persistent source of controversy is  the claim
that the Earth is subject to a steady and potentially  damaging rise in
temperature  a phenomenon known as &quot;global  warming&quot;  and that this
condition is in large part a byproduct of  Western industrial growth. <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt4.htm#28">28</A></B></TT>  The suspected culprits, &quot;greenhouse
 gases,&quot; occur in nature but also are caused by human activity, such  as
burning fossil fuels. They are responsible for making Earth  sufficiently warm
to permit the existence of life, and are thus essential. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The concern is that the buildup of these gases in the  atmosphere could warm
the planet more than otherwise would be the case,  and that this change could
lead to adverse changes in the world's  ecology. Some environmentalists even say
that rising sea levels  caused by melting polar caps could lead to flooding and
tidal waves  and that drought-induced crop failures could trigger global famine.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>While this scenario is taken almost as gospel in some quarters,  the
accumulated scientific data simply do not support it.  Moreover, there is
enormous uncertainty associated with the scientific  methodology used to predict
future climate changes. Among the  difficulties:
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>Climate-change computer models that predict warming often 
rely on assumptions and simplifications that raise questions about  their
reliability.</B> For example, one model, for purposes of  estimating future
temperature, compensated for discrepancies by  increasing the Sun's output by
six percent, which amounted to moving  the Earth's orbit 2 million miles closer
to the Sun. Obviously, if  it moves the Earth's orbit closer to the Sun, which
is the source  of warmth on the planet's surface, the model will predict 
warming, 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 23 -->  just as it will show cooling if
it moves the Earth further from  the Sun. <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt4.htm#29">29</A></B></TT>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>There are shortcomings in the data.</B> For example,  temperature
records over the last century may suggest warming because  many weather stations
are close to growing cities. But cities show  higher temperatures than the
surrounding countryside because of the  increased amount of concrete, which
retains heat. Thus, even if  the temperature in the surrounding country remained
constant,  weather stations close to growing cities would show warming  because
more concrete was laid down around them. <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt4.htm#30">30</A></B></TT>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Temperature observations over the last century are  inconsistent with
the predictions of global warming theories.</B> For example,  if weather data
from 50 years ago are plugged into the models  for global warming, they predict
today's temperatures as being  much higher than they are. &quot;In place of the
[models'] expected  warming trend of 0.3 Celsius/decade, the satellite data show
a slight  cooling trend of -0.06 Celsius/decade.&quot; <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt4.htm#31">31</A></B></TT>  This clearly shows that
the  models being used are biased in favor of warming.
</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>Given these and other uncertainties, it is far from clear that  a warming
trend is occurring. Yet decisions made by  policymakers within our own country,
at the United Nations, and elsewhere  and based on the assumption that warming
is an established fact  could have enormous implications for the Earth's
inhabitants.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The economic costs could be especially dramatic. Consider  one proposal  a &quot;carbon
tax&quot; of $100 per ton, designed to  reduce industry's carbon emissions to
1990 levels by the year 2000.  The Congressional Budget Office estimates this
tax would  reduce 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 24 -->  America's gross national product
by two percent. Put another  way, the loss would be $100 billion per year, or
more than $1,000  per family. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Global warming may pose a huge danger. Or it may turn out to  be just as
much a false alarm as the &quot;Ice Age&quot; panic 20 years  ago, when
environmentalists and the media were claiming that:
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     &quot;The facts have emerged, in
recent years and recent months,  from research into past ice ages. They imply
that the threat of a new  ice age must now stand alongside nuclear war as a
likely source  of wholesale death and misery for mankind.&quot;
<A HREF="ftnt4.htm#32">32
</A></P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     &quot;The cooling since 1940 has been large
enough and  consistent enough that it will not soon be reversed, and we are
unlikely  to quickly regain the `very extraordinary period of warmth' that 
preceded it. Even this mild diagnosis can have `fantastic  implications' for
present-day humanity, [C.C.] Wallen [then of the World  Meteorological
Organization] says.&quot; <TT><B><A HREF="ftnt4.htm#33">33</A></B></TT>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     &quot;A model of future climate based on the
observed  orbital-climate relationships... predicts that the long-term trend
over the next  several thousand years is toward extensive Northern Hemisphere 
glaciation.&quot; <TT><B><A HREF="ftnt4.htm#34">34</A></B></TT>
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>The Endangered Species Act</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Thousands of landowners have been forced to surrender their  property rights
to the U.S. Department of the Interior, whose  enforcement of the Endangered
Species Act (ESA) has led to an  angry backlash. What most Americans do not know
is that the  Act, passed in the late 1960s to protect species from decline, has 
failed 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 25 -->  to recover a single species from
extinction. Although some  species on the list are not now considered
endangered, none (contrary  to the claims of environmentalists) was saved by the
ESA. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B><CITE>-</CITE>     The bald eagle</B>  the symbol of
America  was brought back by  a combination of things unrelated to the ESA: the
banning of  DDT, which caused the precipitous decline in the eagle population in
 the first place by weakening eggshells; a culture change among  hunters who no
longer shoot predatory birds that competed for  prey; the existence of a
separate law solely for the protection of the  bald eagle; and a captive
breeding program that helped boost  populations more quickly. <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt4.htm#35">35</A></B></TT> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE>     American alligators,</B> which environmentalists
claim as one  of ESA's great achievements, should never have been placed on  the
endangered species list. Alligators were plentiful, numbering  between 750,000
and 1,000,000 in the United States at the time  they were listed on March 11,
1967. <TT><B><A HREF="ftnt4.htm#36">36</A></B></TT>
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>The reason the Act does not work is simple. As U.S. Fish  and Wildlife
official Sam Hamilton says, &quot;The incentives are all  wrong here. If I have
a rare metal on my property, its value goes up.  But if a rare bird occupies the
land, its value disappears. We've got  to turn it around to make the landowner
want to have the bird on  his property.&quot; <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt4.htm#37">37</A></B></TT>  Hamilton's words
illustrate why environmental  laws that do not take individual rights into
account are  counterproductive. A serious problem has developed, known as &quot;shoot,
 shovel, and shut up.&quot; <TT><B><A HREF="ftnt4.htm#38">38</A></B></TT>
 Landowners that find, say, a listed plant on  their property sometimes pull the
plant rather than lose their life  savings. Even when landowners take no hostile
move against  species, few have any incentive to provide what endangered species
 need 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 26 -->  most: habitat. As Larry McKinney,
Director of Resource  Protection for the Texas Parks and Wildlife Department,
says, &quot;While  I have no hard evidence to prove it, I am convinced that more
 habitat for the black-capped vireo, and especially the  gold-cheeked warbler,
has been lost in those areas of Texas since the listing  of these birds than
would have been lost without the ESA at  all.&quot; <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt4.htm#39">39</A></B></TT>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>In contrast to the harmful effects from confiscatory  regulations,
encouraging the willing cooperation of landowners has led to  some striking
successes.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>&quot;Perhaps the most notable success story was the recovery of  the wood
duck which was rapidly headed for extinction early in  the century due to a loss
of nesting habitat and over-hunting.  Friends of the wood duck, in the best
tradition of voluntary association  and private conservation, spent the rest of
the century asking  the nation's private landowners to allow them to erect
artificial  nest boxes for the birds,&quot; says R.J. Smith, Senior 
Environmental Scholar at the Competitive Enterprise Institute. &quot;Most 
landowners were more than willing to help. There was no downside. If  the ducks
utilized the nest boxes, the landowners would not be  prevented from using their
lands. If we had had an ESA in 1920,  the wood duck would likely be extinct
today  instead of the  second most common duck in the eastern flyway. Similar
efforts  have worked for... bluebirds, screech owls, barn owl kestrels  (sparrow
hawks), purple martins, and even prothonotary warblers [as  well as] wild
turkeys, ruffed grouse, prairie chickens, and many  species of quail.&quot;
<TT><B><A HREF="ftnt4.htm#40">40</A></B></TT>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Numerous controversies surround ESA, such as whether it is  appropriate or
worthwhile to protect endangered sub-species that  are 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 27 -->  almost identical genetically to
other non-endangered  sub-species. But these are side issues. As currently
enforced, ESA forces  landowners  without compensation  to surrender many of 
their property rights if listed species are found. If the incentive  problem
that pits landowners against species instead of aligning their  interests was
eliminated, the threat to species would likely become  a thing of the past. But
this would occur only if the fear of  punishment for having habitat was replaced
with the promise of  reward for providing habitat. Issues such as which species
need the  most protection could be debated dispassionately with a view to 
getting the maximum return for public funds spent to preserve these  species.
Since federal wildlife managers would be forced to  implement the most efficient
and beneficial uses of those funds,  species most needing protection would be
the most likely to benefit.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Wetlands</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Wetlands, traditionally known as swamps or bogs, have been  disappearing at
a rapid rate during this century, primarily  because they are unique ecosystems.
They are valued by many  Americans for the very practical reason that they can
act as a buffer  against flooding and can purify streams and rivers. Others
despise  wetlands as &quot;mosquito-infested swamps,&quot; and they typically 
are breeding grounds for disease-carrying mosquitoes. While  most Americans
historically have fallen into the latter group,  increased public recognition of
the positive qualities of some wetlands  in recent decades has led to demands
for preservation. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Unfortunately, the confusing and onerous nature of wetland  policy has made
wetland protection a politically contentious issue.  In practice, the Clean
Water Act has been used as the legislative  ve
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 28 -->  hicle to restrict any disturbance
of wetlands even though  wetlands are not mentioned in the legislation. The EPA
and Army Corps  of Engineers rely on Section 404 of the Clean Water Act to 
regulate landowners that wish to disturb wetland on their  property. <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt4.htm#41">41</A></B></TT>  There are four principal
problems with current wetland policies:
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>First,</B> the statutory authority itself is questionable.
Indeed, for  isolated wetland, known as &quot;non-adjacent&quot; wetland,
federal  authority seems clearly lacking. Obviously, federal agencies should not
 pursue policies that neither the Constitution nor any statute  allows them to
pursue.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Second,</B> the definition of what constitutes a wetland is 
unnecessarily broad. According to the 1987 Delineation Manual now in  force, a
wetland is any land that meets each of the following criteria:  It must be
inundated or saturated to 12 inches deep for at least 7  consecutive days and 5
percent of the growing season, and more  than 50 percent of the dominant plant
species found are found  in marshes and swamps regardless of whether they are
found  elsewhere as well. This language is so unnecessarily inclusive  that land
which is bone dry for almost the entire year can be deemed  a wetland.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Third,</B> the nation already has achieved the Bush-Clinton  wetland
goal of &quot;no net loss&quot; in a given year. In recent years, the nation 
has been increasing its wetland stock. In 1994, the likely net gain  was more
than 100,000 acres; the expected loss rate was 102,000  acres, while the
expected &quot;creation&quot; rate due to federal programs  was 195,000 acres.
Additionally, wetland restoration is taking place  on public land and through
strictly private initiatives. In 1994,  for example, Ducks Unlimited alone
restored or enhanced  51,260 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 29 -->  acres.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Fourth,</B> the financial resources of many Americans are being 
destroyed as owners are forced to surrender, without  compensation, their right
to use their property. Because many affected  individuals make their living or
pay their mortgages from income  derived from the land, their savings can be
wiped out.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>In short, this legislation has led to often absurd results. Based  on
questionable legal authority, federal agencies can force  landowners to
sacrifice their life's savings to protect land with little  ecological value
against the now-obsolete threat of net loss of wetlands.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Pesticides and the Delaney Clause </B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>One of the onerous aspects of pesticide regulation is Section  409 of the
Federal Food, Drug, and Cosmetic Act, known as  the Delaney Clause, enacted in
1958 to ban any additive in  pro-cessed food that has been shown to cause cancer
in humans or  laboratory animals. The Delaney Clause seemed reasonable at the
time  because scientists could test for traces of chemicals only in  quantities
of about one in a million. Today, however, with improvements  in technology,
they can test for many of these chemicals in  quantities of less than one in a
quadrillion (a billion million). Some  chemicals can be detected almost down to
the level of a molecule. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>This means that extremely small trace quantities that were  undetectable 37
years ago  and thus allowable  now form the  basis for a court order requiring
EPA to eliminate dozens of  pesticides. Many of these same pesticides are
completely safe up to  certain levels, according to EPA's own findings, but the
law requires  that 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 30 -->  they be banned. Under Section 408
of the same Act, which  relates to raw foods, EPA has issued regulations setting
the tolerance  level deemed safe for consumption. Thus, under Section 409   the
Delaney Clause  EPA will ban pesticide residues in  processed foods that it
allows and proclaims safe in raw foods. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Even EPA Administrator Carol Browner has called for a change  in the law: &quot;We
have gotten to a point where we have to say  we know a lot more about these
chemicals than we did 35 years  ago when the law was passed.&quot;  <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt4.htm#42">42</A></B></TT>  Unfortunately, the 
environmental lobby applied severe pressure on the Clinton Administration,  and
Browner backpedaled from her position. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The issue is not simply cutting costs. Pesticides are responsible  for an
explosion of food production in this country and around  the world while the
land use has remained relatively constant. As  the <a href="envir_4.gif">chart</a> below shows, if
pesticides were eliminated, the amount  of land used for agriculture to produce
the same amount of  food would triple. Moreover, pesticides are directly related
to  lower world food prices. This increases food consumption, including  the
consumption of fruits and vegetables, which in turn lowers  cancer rates. In the
words of Bruce Ames, Professor of Biochemistry  and Molecular Biology at the
University of California at Berkeley  and perhaps the world's foremost expert on
cancer risk, the best  known way to prevent cancer is to &quot;eat your 
veggies.&quot; <TT><B><A HREF="ftnt4.htm#43">43</A></B></TT>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Moreover, the fact that some chemical pesticides test positive  for cancer
when huge doses are fed to test animals is not  necessarily cause for alarm.
After all, says Ames, of the 22 chemicals found  in coffee that have been tested
in animal cancer tests, &quot;17 are  carcinogens. There are 10 milligrams of
known carcinogens in a  cup 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 31 -->  of coffee and that's more
carcinogens than you're likely to  get from pesticide residues in a year....
We're eating natural  pesticides, which are chemicals that plants use to try to
kill off insects that  try to eat them. And we eat roughly 1,500 milligrams of
them per  day. We eat 0.09 milligrams of synthetic pesticide residues. So  we're
talking about incredibly tiny amounts of synthetic pesticides,  and yet the same
percentage [roughly half] of natural chemicals  come out positive&quot; when
tested for cancer. <TT><B><A HREF="ftnt4.htm#44">44</A></B></TT>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Superfund </B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The Comprehensive Environmental Response, Compensation,  and Liability Act
(CERCLA), the program for cleaning up  hazardous waste sites, is up for
reauthorization. Superfund, as CERCLA  is known, not only is one of the most
complex laws now in force,  but also is widely regarded as the most wasteful and
ineffective.  Even the Clinton Administration admits the program does not  work.
Despite expenditures of between $20 billion and $30  billion, Superfund has
cleaned up only a small fraction of the  nation's worst hazardous waste sites.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Superfund was enacted after widespread press attention to the  exposure of
residents to high levels of dangerous chemicals at  Love Canal near Niagara
Falls, New York. <TT><B><A HREF="ftnt4.htm#45">45</A></B></TT>
 Unfortunately, the  law was hurried through Congress in the final days of the
Carter  Administration, so many provisions are ill-considered. Much of  the
money has been spent not on cleanup, but on legal fees and  other &quot;transaction
costs,&quot; and while program costs have  ballooned, cleanups have proceeded
slowly. Only 291, or 24 percent, of  the 1,238 &quot;worst&quot; hazardous waste
sites  sites placed on the  National Priorities List (NPL)  have been cleaned
up. To clean up the  re
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 32 -->  maining sites now on the NPL will
cost an estimated $40  billion. <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt4.htm#46">46</A></B></TT>  If the cost of cleaning
up federal facilities is added to the  equation, the total could exceed $750
billion, or $7,800 per U.S.  household. <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt4.htm#47">47</A></B></TT>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>There are four basic flaws in the Superfund program:
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>1. The law as written is designed to reduce the level of 
chemicals in the ground, not to reduce risks to people.</B> Yet fully one-third 
of the sites pose only hypothetical future risks based primarily on  the
assumption that residential housing will be built, thus  exposing future
residents to these chemicals. It is utterly unrealistic to  assume any
residential housing will be built on any  untreated Superfund site; no developer
would attempt it, or get permits if  he did.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>2. The program's unreasonable standards require that  hazardous waste
sites be cleaned up to a pristine level no matter what  the location, resulting
in a poor return on the investment.</B> For  instance, polluted soil at
industrial park sites must be cleaned up to a  level that makes it essentially
clean enough to eat.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>3. Hazardous wastes by their very nature are local problems,  but
listings, cleanup decisions, and program authority are run by a  federal
bureaucracy.</B> If there is any federal environmental law  for which a
legitimate case can be made for devolving authority  back to the states, it is
CERCLA.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>4. The law's retroactive, strict joint and several liability  scheme
results in endless legal battles as potentially responsible  parties (PRPs)
fight EPA, then each other, and then their insurers to  shoul
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 33 -->  der the costs of cleanup.</B> It
is little wonder that the program is  derisively called the &quot;Super
scholarship fund for lawyers' children.&quot;   The liability scheme is designed
to find someone with &quot;deep  pockets&quot; to pay the cost of cleanup
regardless of how much  or  how little  that individual may have contributed to
the waste  problem. This forces individuals and small businesses to pay 
enormous sums for what most people would consider innocent acts, some  of them
committed generations ago.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>All of these characteristics drive up costs while blunting  the program's
effectiveness. Moreover, all have led to numerous  horror stories of people
caught in the Superfund liability web.  For instance:
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     Russ Zimmer was named a PRP for a
Superfund site at a car  battery cracking plant in Torrington, Wyoming. His
contribution  to the problem?  He sold a bag of dog food in 1977 and a bag of 
seed in 1984, and took a third-party check as payment for the  items. Since the
checks had been issued by the now-bankrupt  company that had owned the battery
cracking plant, Zimmer was sued as  a PRP by another company caught in the
Superfund liability  scheme. Zimmer decided, on advice of counsel, that he
should settle  to avoid even more in legal costs. He agreed to pay $3,500  even
though he had nothing to do with the matter.  <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt4.htm#48">48</A></B></TT>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     The entire town of Triumph, Idaho, located just
a few miles  away from the famous ski resort town of Sun Valley, has suffered 
terribly under EPA's administration of the Superfund law. The  town, which had a
silver mine until 1957, has plenty of lead in  the ground. So the EPA put the
mine on the Superfund list, with  the highest &quot;worst&quot; Superfund score
ever  almost half again as  high 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 34 -->  as the nuclear production site at
Hanford, Washington. As a  result, banks red-lined the town, and homeowners
cannot sell their  homes because banks refuse to lend on them. EPA officials
summoned  an emergency meeting at which they told the 50 families their 
children might have extremely high levels of lead in their blood.  EPA conducted
tests for lead contamination but refused to disclose  the results, so the town
did its own tests. It turns out that lead  poisoning was not a problem because
the well water in Triumph was  not contaminated. In fact, lead levels in
Triumph's water are below  the national average, well within safety limits. Now
the  townspeople are unified against the federal government's treatment of 
their community. In March 1995, a resident, Donna Rose, testified to  a House
Commerce subcommittee that EPA &quot;terrified us. They  committed atrocious
acts on our community.&quot; <TT><B><A HREF="ftnt4.htm#49">49</A></B></TT>
 Unfortunately for  Triumph, however, the suffering caused under Superfund 
continues. Rose, who like many of her townsfolk believes Triumph was  chosen for
designation as the worst of the worst sites because  EPA needed a trophy as
Superfund came under attack, testified  that &quot;We can't sell our houses.
We're trapped there forever until this  is resolved.&quot; <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt4.htm#50">50</A></B></TT>
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>CAFE Standards </B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The Corporate Average Fuel Economy (CAFE) standards  were enacted in
response to the oil crisis in 1973 and were designed  to stabilize oil prices at
lower levels. Today, support for the  program comes primarily from the
environmental lobby, which sees  the standards as a way to preserve fuel, and
perhaps to drive up  the cost of autos. The program currently requires that cars
 average 27.5 mpg (miles per gallon) and that light trucks average  20.7 mpg.
Now the Clinton Administration is considering tightening  the 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 35 -->  standards. The problem is that
this law costs both lives and jobs. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The most serious problem with CAFE standards, to put it  bluntly, is that
they kill people. According to economists Robert  Crandall of the Brookings
Institution and John Graham of the  Harvard School of Public Health, 1989 model
cars are about 500  pounds lighter than they would have been without the 27.5
mpg  economy standard. <TT><B><A HREF="ftnt4.htm#51">51</A></B></TT>
 They estimate that this weight reduction is  responsible for 2,500 additional
deaths and 25,000 additional serious  injuries per model fleet year. This is too
high a price to pay for any  government program. Raising the standard would only
increase  the death toll. Raising standards to 40 mpg, for example, would 
likely mean another 4,800 to 8,600 deaths per  year. <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt4.htm#52">52</A></B></TT>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The other problem with CAFE, especially with raising the  standard, is that
it makes little economic sense. A study by  Charles Rivers Associates has found
that increasing standards would  raise the average price of cars by $1,500 and
the average price of  trucks by $2,100. <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt4.htm#53">53</A></B></TT>  This would lead
consumers to retain their older  autos longer, thus minimizing the very
decreases in fuel  consumption regulators hope to see and increasing pollution
by an estimated  4 percent by the year 2010 (assuming a 30 percent increase in 
the mileage standard). <TT><B><A HREF="ftnt4.htm#54">54</A></B></TT>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Finally, raising CAFE standards would be devastating to  average families.
The reason the traditional full-size family station  wagon no longer is made is
that car manufacturers found it difficult  to meet the 27.5 mpg standard with
these gas-guzzlers in their  fleets. Thus, the market for even less
fuel-efficient minivans  exploded, since they only had to meet the light truck
standard of less than  21 mpg. If standards for light trucks were raised, then 
manufacturers 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 36 -->  would be forced to raise prices
dramatically to cut sales of  the minivan so their fleet average could remain in
compliance.  Thus, most families no longer could afford the only vehicle
designed  for families.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><A NAME="RECORD">THE RECORD</A></B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>THE CLINTON ADMINISTRATION
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Slowly, methodically, and steadily, the Clinton Administration  has been
pushing a consistently liberal environmental agenda.  The most prominent aspect
of this agenda is its high-flown  rhetoric, especially since the advent of the
104th Congress. While much  of this rhetoric has little to do with reality, the
attack has been  quite effective against a Congress that seems to lack  the
Administration's unified sense of purpose. Vice President Al  Gore, EPA
Administrator Carol Browner, and Interior Secretary  Bruce Babbitt all have been
heavily engaged in criticizing the new  Congress, with Gore dismissing
Congress's attempts at  environmental reform as a &quot;jihad.&quot; <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt4.htm#55">55</A></B></TT>  President Clinton also
has turned up  the rhetorical volume. In his weekly radio address on November 
4, 1995, he charged that:
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>Under cover of balancing the budget, the Republican Congress 
is going after the essential environmental protections that have  guaranteed the
health and safety of all Americans for a long time  now, and I am determined to
stop them.... This budget will mean  dirtier water, more smog, more illness and
a diminished quality of life.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>When making its own proposals for high-visibility issues, the 
Administration has taken great care to appear reasonable while  still 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 37 -->  pursing a liberal agenda. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The Superfund reform advocated by the Administration in  1994 and 1995, for
example, partially addressed some of the most  egregious aspects of this law,
but created perhaps as many problems  as it solved. Thus, the Administration was
able to claim that it  wanted to eliminate some of the worst aspects of the law,
such as joint  and several liability, while attempting to substitute provisions 
that were not much better, such as the allocation scheme it  devised. Meanwhile,
it insisted on seemingly innocuous provisions  that would have created an
environmental welfare program by  diverting up to 4 percent of Superfund's money
to environmental  activists. <TT><B><A HREF="ftnt4.htm#56">56</A></B></TT>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The Administration's environmental agenda is one of  increased government
control and production mandates. Steered by  Vice President Gore, author of <I>Earth
in the  Balance</I>, the Administration has fought for numerous regulations,
executive orders, and  international agreements that are anti-business,
anti-growth, and  ultimately anti-consumer. One common theme among these 
regulations is the seeming lack of any serious consideration of their  relative
costs and benefits. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     The Clinton Department of
Transportation in 1993 considered  promulgating hazardous material regulations
for the shipping of  butter and salad oil. The plan, aborted after tremendous
criticism,  would have required 24 hours of hazardous materials classroom and 
field training for workers who responded to butter or salad oil  spill
emergencies. <TT><B><A HREF="ftnt4.htm#57">57</A></B></TT> 
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>Perhaps most insidious has been the effort to include  environmen
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 38 -->  tal objectives in international
agreements. The principal effect  of this scheme would be to make it harder to
reform  this Administration's misguided policies.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     To combat the potential threat of
global warming, a  worldwide effort is under way to reduce greenhouse gases such
as carbon  dioxide that contribute to climate change. The Bush  Administration
spent months negotiating the language of the Framework  Convention on Climate
Change in preparation for the June 1992  Earth Summit in Rio de Janeiro, Brazil,
so that it would not require  that greenhouse gas production be scaled back to
1990 levels by  the year 2000. Yet Clinton, soon after taking office, decided 
to reconstrue the language of the treaty to mean exactly that,  and later
proposed costly actions to achieve this end. Even  though most countries will
not meet their present commitments, the  Administration is considering signing a
legally binding  convention protocol proposed at a Berlin conference to target
greenhouse  gas emission levels after the year 2000. <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt4.htm#58">58</A></B></TT>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     After the Bush Administration refused to sign
the Biological  Diversity Treaty, Clinton signed it. The treaty calls for a 
national biological survey to inventory existing species. It also provides  for
technology transfers from developed nations to lesser  developed nations, as
well as for the &quot;equitable sharing&quot; of technology  derived from
biodiversity with the country in which the plant  that developed the technology
(typically, a plant owned by a U.S.  company) was located.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>The Administration has not been as successful in implementing  the
far-reaching goals of its global agreements here in the  United States. When
faced with the daunting task of reaching  consensus 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 39 -->  on policies naturally resulting
from these global agreements,  the Administration seems to falter despite
enormous efforts to  impose its leftist agenda. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     Administration efforts to survey
private property (without  permission) for animals and plants under the
Biodiversity Treaty  were defeated in the 103rd Congress when conservative
Democrat  (now Republican) Representative Billy Tauzin (LA) put forward  an
amendment that required the property owners' permission to  come onto their
property. The amendment passed overwhelmingly.  The Administration nevertheless
is putting enormous staff  resources into cataloging species.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     The White House Car Talks Committee, known more
formally  as the Policy Dialogue Advisory Committee to Develop Options  for
Reducing Greenhouse Gas Emissions from Personal Motor  Vehicles, seriously
considered truly draconian measures to further  the reduction of greenhouse
emissions under the U.N.  Framework Convention on Climate Change. Perhaps most
troublesome  were its recommendations that fuel economy (CAFE) standards  be
raised so that cars would average 45 mpg (and light trucks  34 mpg) by the year
2007 and 75 mpg and 56 mpg by the year  2025. These recommendations, if
implemented, would have  increased the death toll on the road by many thousands
every year, since  cars meeting these standards necessarily would have to be
lighter to  be more fuel efficient, and thus would be less crashworthy. 
Fortunately, the committee was unable to issue a consensus report  because the
auto and oil industries refused to support its  recommendations, which wound up
being presented as the so-called  Majority Report by other members of the
advisory committee on  December 13, 1995.
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 40 --> 
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>But the Clinton Administration has not been altogether  ineffective in
imposing its environmental vision on the country. In addition  to laying the
groundwork for more regulations, it has taken  limited action in some areas.
While its plan to stop global  warming stopped short of a carbon tax, for
example, it does include a  Climate Change Action Plan that will impose a $60
billion burden  on the economy  a burden that may well be wholly unnecessary. 
The plan is widely thought to be an inadequate response to the  problem of
greenhouse gas emissions; thus, even if one assumes  global warming to be a real
threat, the Administration has embarked  on an effort that will waste over $600
per  household. <TT><B><A HREF="ftnt4.htm#59">59</A></B></TT>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>THE 104TH CONGRESS</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The 103rd Congress, which left office in 1994, accomplished  very little
with respect to the environment. The House and Senate  leadership failed either
to reauthorize any of the major  environmental laws up for reauthorization or to
pass any new ones (with the  exception of the California Desert Protection Act).
 Environmental lobbyists worked successfully to block any reauthorization  that
included one or more of three reforms: compensating  property owners for losses
caused by environmental rulings, giving  states relief from unfunded federal
environmental mandates, or  requiring that risk assessments be conducted before
expensive  regulations designed to alleviate some hypothetical risk are put into
place.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Environmentalists so feared passage of these reforms (which  they called the
&quot;unholy trinity&quot;) that they decided it was better to  have no
environmental legislation adopted at all. But conservatives  kept offering the
amendments, which also were supported by  many 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 41 -->  moderates, so the Democratic
leadership refused to let the  reauthorization bills come up for a vote  even a
bill that would  have raised EPA to Cabinet level as the Department of the 
Environment.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Unfortunately, the 104th Congress accomplished little more in  the
environmental area during its first session, although it did pass  the Unfunded
Mandates Reform Act of 1995 (UMRA), one part of  the &quot;unholy trinity.&quot;
 While this Act covers regulation generally,  the most burdensome mandates on
local governments typically  have been environmental regulations. For instance,
prior to the  Unfunded Mandates Reform Act, regulators continued to issue  new
prescriptive regulations under the Safe Drinking Water Act  that imposed
enormous costs on local communities by requiring  what some local officials
called gold-plated solutions. After passage  of UMRA, the Senate voted
unanimously for a bill that would  allow smaller communities to develop and use
less costly  alternative standards on condition that they protect the public 
health. <TT><B><A HREF="ftnt4.htm#60">60</A></B></TT>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>While property-rights and risk-assessment bills have been  debated
thoroughly by both chambers and passed by the House, the  Senate has yet to vote
on them, and President Clinton has threatened  to veto them if they reach his
desk. <TT><B><A HREF="ftnt4.htm#61">61</A></B></TT> 
Congress also has failed  to reauthorize the major environmental laws. The
reason: Few  reforms of the current laws could avoid a veto by the President, 
and the leadership does not have the votes to override a veto.  Moreover, as of
publication, Members so far have failed to embrace  an environmental vision of
their own.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>As of publication, EPA appropriations for FY 1996 have not  become law.
Congress passed the EPA appropriations bill as part  of 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 42 -->  the Veterans Affairs, Housing and
Urban Development, and  Independent Agencies appropriations bill on December 14,
1995,  but President Clinton vetoed the bill four days later. His main 
objection was that EPA's funding level of $5.7 billion was too low,  especially
in the enforcement area. While EPA's funding under  the bill would have been
reduced by 21 percent as a necessary  incident to balancing the budget, it is
unlikely this would interfere  seriously with EPA's mandate. Although no new
major environmental  laws have passed  and only one has been amended since  1989
<TT><B><A HREF="ftnt4.htm#62">62</A></B></TT>  the level of
funding that Clinton vetoed as too deep a cut is almost  10 percent higher than
when President Bush took  office. <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt4.htm#63">63</A></B></TT>  In reality, EPA's growth
has far outstripped growth of both the economy  and the federal government; the
funding of $5.7 billion merely  reflects an attempt to rectify this imbalance.
<TT><B><A HREF="ftnt4.htm#64">64</A></B></TT>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>WHAT TO DO IN 1997</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>Emphasize research on climate change rather than costly, 
questionable controls. </B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>If the science of climate change were more precise than it is,  and the
evidence more consistent with the dire predictions of  some proponents of the
global-warming theory, it could make sense  for the United States and other
countries to take urgent,  expensive action to deal with the potential threat.
But the science is far  from certain. Rather than rush to &quot;do something&quot;
at huge cost, the  wiser and more mature course would be to try to find out more
 precisely what actually is happening to the Earth's atmosphere. Yet 
environmentalists are trying to redirect funding from research on  climate
change to research on its effects  on the assumption that  global warming
definitely will happen. As noted by Jeffrey Salmon,  Ex
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 43 -->  ecutive Director of the George C.
Marshall Institute, which  focuses on science issues, &quot;obviously, the
environmental lobby has  not been happy with the data that science has been
coming up with  the last few years.&quot; <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt4.htm#65">65</A></B></TT> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Congress should resist attempts to redirect climate change  research. While
cutting unnecessary duplication of research  may allow for some budget savings,
the basic research should  continue as insurance against unwise actions in the
future.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Change the Endangered Species Act to give landowners the  incentive to
conserve species.
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P>ESA should be reformed to eliminate the adversarial  relationship between
landowners and species fostered by the current Act.  If landowners, who are
closest to the species needing protection,  had an incentive to provide habitat
or encourage reproduction on  their property, there is little doubt these
species would flourish. Just  as the country pays auto makers to produce Jeeps
for the Army,  it should pay landowners to produce members of endangered 
species that need protection. Not only would this reform allow the Act  to work
for the first time, but Americans also would not be forced  to surrender their
freedoms.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Reform America's wetlands &quot;legislation.&quot;
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P>It is time to decide whether wetlands should be protected for  their own
sake. If the answer is &quot;No,&quot; the Clean Water Act  reauthorization
should specify that protection is limited to water pollution.  If the answer is
&quot;Yes,&quot; a Wetlands Protection Act should be passed.
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 44 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Require the government to pay fair market value if it  confiscates
property through regulation.
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The executive branch should be required to define different  categories of
wetlands according to ecological structure and  value. Additionally, it should
establish differing levels of protection.  This categorization should include
the economic value of the land as  a component of the decision-making process so
that decisions  to regulate take into account the relative cost of protecting
each  parcel. By including this factor, the money spent on acquiring  wetlands
would be stretched to obtain the maximum protection  for every dollar spent.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Repeal the Delaney Clause.
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Spending billions of dollars to ban useful, safe pesticides to  avoid
negligible risks is simply bad public policy. The Delaney Clause  is obsolete
and should be discarded.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Reform Superfund.
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Superfund is broken. If it is to be repaired, it must be  completely
overhauled. Federal agencies, state governments,  municipalities, and the
private sector must be relieved of the ill-conceived,  unnecessary, and
expensive burdens of this program. Specifically,  the reformed CERCLA should at
least:
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE>     Turn</B> authority for current NPL sites over to the
states  with  the necessary funding. To qualify for funds, states should be 
required to meet two conditions:
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 45 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>      <B>1.</B> That they prioritize sites and expenditures based on real 
risks, and
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>      <B>2.</B> That they eliminate joint and several liability and end 
retroactive liability for wastes disposed of before 1987 for sites  cleaned with
federal funds.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE>     Allow</B> states to use funds for any of their most
serious  hazardous waste sites, not just NPL sites transferred from the federal 
government. These conditions would have to apply, or states would  be tempted
simply to spend the money on sites for which they  were responsible rather than
on those that are most dangerous.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE>     Create</B> a revolving loan fund for cleaning up old
industrial sites.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE>     Allow</B> EPA to retain its emergency cleanup 
capacity. <TT><B><A HREF="ftnt4.htm#66">66</A></B></TT>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>If substantive reforms of this nature are not enacted,  Superfund will
continue to be an ineffective and expensive drain on  the American economy. But
if proper reforms are instituted,  Congress can achieve its original goal of
protecting Americans from  hazardous wastes at reasonable cost.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Save lives by ending the CAFE program.
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Not only should CAFE standards not be raised further, but the  program
should be eliminated. It costs lives and jobs and  provides only questionable
benefits. Reducing oil consumption may  help lower oil prices and reduce
pollution, but it also costs 2,500  lives. The trade-off simply is not worth it.
<TT><B><A HREF="ftnt4.htm#67">67</A></B></TT> 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 46 --> 
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><A NAME="Q&A">Q &amp; A</A></B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Q. Doesn't regulatory reform mean rolling back regulations  that protect
our environment?
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>A.</B> No. Regulatory reform means introducing common sense  into the
equation when decisions are made about whether, for  instance, a chemical should
be banned or regulated. At its most basic,  regulatory reform means making sure
the government knows what it  is doing before it does it by requiring agencies
to analyze  realistically the risks and compare the costs and benefits of their
actions.  It means making sure the process is open to scrutiny by making  it &quot;transparent&quot;
so that shoddy procedures or wildly unrealistic  assumptions used in risk
analysis, and thus in making decisions,  do not go unchallenged. Also, by
requiring these agencies to  estimate the likely risks  not just the most
extreme conceivable risks   the country can have a better idea of what it is
buying with its  scarce economic resources. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Currently, federal agencies typically use only worst-case  assumptions
multiplied by other worst-case assumptions. The likely  risk of chemicals, for
example, is multiplied millions of times.  Thus, the risk is artificially
inflated to seem unacceptable. By that  mathematical logic, leaving your house
in the suburbs to pick up a  carton of milk from a convenience store would be
deemed an  unjustifiable risk because of your chance of dying from a falling 
airplane. Without accurate risk assessments, federal agencies such as  EPA
promulgate costly regulations which yield few or no benefits,  and many of which
probably would not be seen as desirable if  the agency were adequately
self-informed about the likely risks  and benefits of its actions.
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 47 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Q. Why should the federal government compensate property  owners for the
loss of property rights? 
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>A.</B> There are plenty of good reasons. For one, the Fifth  Amendment
states, &quot;nor shall private property be taken for public  use, without just
compensation.&quot;  Unfortunately, the Supreme  Court has interpreted this to
apply primarily only when the  government physically takes your land.
Bureaucrats exploit this legal fine  print by allowing people to retain title to
their property  and pay  taxes on it  even as they take away the owner's right
to decide how  his property should be used. Nor are property owners reimbursed 
for their losses. This is both unfair and economically devastating.  For
instance, if an elderly husband and wife spend a large portion  of their
retirement savings to buy property on which to build  their dream home and that
property then is designated a &quot;wetland,&quot;  the value of their property 
and their savings  is destroyed.  Unfortunately, tales of financial hardship
caused by government  designation of land as wetland or endangered-species
habitat have  become common. This is unconscionable. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>If the public benefits, then the public  not some hapless  landowner  should
pay to provide that benefit. Thus, if the  government takes away your right to
determine for yourself how to  use your $100,000 property, it should compensate
you for the loss  in value it created by taking away that right. The fundamental
 question is whether they took away your right to use your  property; how much
they should pay is merely a function of how much  that right was worth.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Q. Conservatives often fight regulations that encourage  energy 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 48 -->  conservation. Why? 
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>A.</B> Conservatives are not against conserving energy when it  makes
sense to do so, but responsible adults who must weigh the pros  and cons of
their actions  and who must pay for the energy  are  the best judges of when it
makes sense to conserve or expend  energy in their daily lives. The fact is that
federally mandated energy  conservation is costly in terms of money, human
suffering, and  increased deaths, and sometimes is even counterproductive. For 
instance, Corporate Average Fuel Economy (CAFE) standards  are now supported
primarily by the Clinton Administration and  environmentalists as a way to
preserve fuel. The most serious  problem with CAFE standards is that the weight
reductions necessary  to meet them make cars less safe because lighter cars are
less  crashworthy. In fact, about 2,500 additional deaths and 25,000  additional
serious injuries occur per model year. Although raising  the standard would
raise the death toll even more, that is exactly  what Clinton wants to do. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Energy conservation mandates also cause other unintended  consequences.
Increasing CAFE standards would raise the average  price of cars by as much as
$1,500. And with higher priced autos,  many people would keep their autos on the
road longer, thus  minimizing the very decreases in fuel consumption regulators
are hoping  to achieve. On top of that, older autos kept on the road longer 
would mean increased pollution, not lower pollution. Saving some  oil hardly
justifies the death and suffering imposed by  ill-considered command-and-control
federal regulations such as CAFE.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Q. Isn't cutting EPA's funding just a backdoor attempt by  conservatives
to gut the enforcement of environmental laws they  don't 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 49 -->  like? 
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B> A.</B> No. The simple truth is that our country cannot afford  ever
more expensive government if we are to eliminate the budget  deficit that
threatens the economic future of our children.  Balancing the budget requires
tough choices, and all federal agencies   even the IRS  will be forced to
streamline their operations.  EPA should not be an exception. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The administration of environmental laws will not be affected  adversely by
the budget. EPA still will have a bigger budget than  it had when President Bush
took office, so charges of gutting  EPA's ability to enforce the law are
specious. The fact is that EPA,  instead of concentrating on how we can protect
our  environment under the law, has pushed for ever more paperwork and  control
over the private sector. It uses these new costly programs to  justify its
requests for ever greater funding. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>What these cuts do is require EPA, just like any business  in America, to
evaluate its procedures to cut the fat from its  programs while simultaneously
improving the environment. For  instance, EPA currently does an expensive but
very poor job of  sporadically monitoring factory air and water emissions. It
should allow  companies to hire independent certified contractors to certify
that  they have met certain compliance requirements, much as  accountants
certify tax law compliance. With EPA maintaining a  spot-checking function,
independent contractors would be motivated to  provide honest reports, and &quot;cheating&quot;
and pollution would likely be  reduced considerably. The government also would
save  enormous sums.
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 50 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Q. Conservatives talk about reducing costs and saving jobs,  but what
about saving lives by controlling toxic chemicals? 
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>A.</B> How many dollars or jobs is a child's life worth?  Who can  put a
price tag on human life?  These are impossible questions,  but they are not
really the issue. The issue is how to structure our  laws so that we get the
highest quality of life, which includes a long  and healthy life, but at
reasonable cost. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Reducing costs and saving jobs actually saves far more lives  than many
federal &quot;risk reduction&quot; regulations. Money wasted on  ineffective
programs is not available for more beneficial  purposes, including saving more
lives. Recent studies have made this  point crystal clear. Scholars have
recently discovered that, for every  year of life extended, the average cost for
federal toxin regulations   the kind for which EPA is renowned  is $2.8 million;
by  contrast, the average cost for medical treatments is $19,000, and the 
average cost for injury reduction efforts is $48,000. Thus, the average  toxin
control program costs roughly 58 times more for every year of  life extended
than the average injury prevention program and  146 times more than the average
medical program. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The question thus is not whether $2.8 million is too little or  too great.
The question is whether we want to save the most lives  possible with our
economic resources or squander those scarce  resources in an attempt to
eliminate what are often hypothetical  risks while ignoring that real people
still will die from some other  cause. If lawmakers seriously considered which
environmental  policies actually save the most lives, they would scrap many
costly  rules and use the freed-up resources in other ways that save more 
lives. This commonsense approach would lead to levels and types  of 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 51 -->  regulation that are radically
different from those that  burden America today. In many cases, if the private
resources used  to comply with federal mandates simply were left in the 
industries concerned, or used in other ways in the local economy,  Americans
would benefit far more  and far more lives could be saved.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Q. Experts and governments from all over the world have  concluded in
the last year or so   that industrial activity adds to  global warming. When
will conservatives take their heads out of the  sand and admit it?
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>A.</B> Actually, scientists and experts all over the world have  been
coming to a very different conclusion. Fears of global  warming have been
reduced as knowledge has increased, and the dire  predictions of global warming
are beginning to resemble the dire  predictions of the coming Ice Age  also
supposedly man-caused   that was supposed to turn the planet into a frozen
wasteland.  President Bush jump-started serious scientific research on  climate
change a few years ago, increasing the annual budget 25  percent annually. The
results of these billions of dollars are that we  have consistently  vastly 
overstated the risk. Now that we are  armed with much more information, it is
clear the models predicting  global warming were fatally flawed and biased to
show  warming when in reality the planet is cooling. The truth is that despite 
the hysterical language often associated with this issue, we know  the planet
has not warmed at all since we started keeping highly  accurate satellite data
in the late 1970s. Yet environmentalists  now claim even the blizzard of '96 is
an example of global  warming. While it might be nice to dismiss the climate
change theory  altogether since environmentalists are so inconsistent about 
whether the temperature will soar or plummet  although it will be  man's 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 52 -->  fault either way  this would be
unwise. The wise thing to  do would be to continue funding so that we know what
is really  happening. What gives the environmentalists away is that many  of
them are now calling for elimination of research on whether  and how climate
change is occurring in favor of research on what  effects global warming will
have, based on the assumption it  will happen.
</P>
