<h2>Issues '96: The Candidate's Briefing Book</h2>
<b><A HREF="/heritage">The Heritage Foundation</a></b>
</center><p>
<h3>Chapter 6</h3>
<center>
<h2>SOCIAL BREAKDOWN IN AMERICA</H2>

<CITE><B>By <a href="/heritage/staff/fagan.htm">Patrick F. Fagan</a>
</B></CITE>
<P><A HREF="chpt6.html#ISSUES">The Issues</A> | <A HREF="chpt6.html#FACTS">The Facts</A> |  <A HREF="chpt6.html#RECORD">The Record</A> | <A HREF="chpt6.html#Q&A">Q&amp;A</A> | <A HREF="chpt6.html#SELECTED">Selected Heritage Foundation Studies</A> | <a href="chpt6.html#EXP">Experts</a> 
</CENTER>
<p>
<a href="soc_1.gif">Chart 1</a>: Growth of Illegitimacy<br>
<a href="soc_2.gif">Chart 2</a>: Births to Married and Unmarried Women, Percent of Total Births<br>
<a href="soc_3.gif">Chart 3</a>: Marriage and Divorce Rates<br>
<a href="soc_4.gif">Chart 4</a>: Annual Number of Children Whose Parents Divorce: 1950-1993<br>
<a href="soc_5.gif">Chart 5</a>: Proportion of Children Entering Broken Families<br>
<a href="soc_6.gif">Chart 6</a>: Out-of-Wedlock Births, Welfare Dependency<br>
<a href="soc_7.gif">Chart 7</a>: Proportions of Married Families, Female-Headed Households Under Poverty Level<br>
<a href="soc_8.gif">Chart 8</a>: For Each 10% Increase in Single-Parent Families, 17% Increase in Violent Teen Crime<br>
<a href="soc_9.gif">Chart 9</a>: Percent of High School Students Who Ever Used Alcohol, Marijuana<br>
<a href="soc_10.gif">Chart 10</a>: Income Taxes For Family With Two Children, Before, After $500 Per-Child Tax Cut<br>
<a href="soc_11.gif">Chart 11</a>: Working Mothers Absent<br>
<a href="soc_12.gif">Chart 12</a>: Adoptions Decreasing, Especially for Women Under 20<br>   
<a href="soc_t1.gif">Table 1</a>: What the $500 Per-Child Tax Credit Means to a Family with Two Children<br>
<a href="soc_t2.gif">Table 2</a>: Income At Which Family Becomes Eligible for Tax Cut<br>
 
<p><a href="chpt6text.html">Additional Text</a><p>

<P><B><A NAME="ISSUES">THE ISSUES</A></B>

</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Americans are increasingly anxious about the breakdown of the basic social
institutions of society.  Nowhere is this more visible than in the breakdown and
disappearance of neighborhoods. Many once-friendly  and peaceful neighborhoods
are now threatening and dangerous. Particularly alarming is the breakdown  of
marriage and the family. Marriage and the stable two-parent family form the
centerbeam of society,  but soaring rates of divorce and out-of-wedlock births
are destroying this crucial institution and weakening  the development of the
next generation. This means more welfare dependence, more crime, more health 
and behavioral problems, lower educational achievement, and the prospect of
daunting obstacles in later life  for millions of young Americans. Some 92
percent of children on welfare today are from broken  families. <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt6.htm">1</A></B></TT>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>To a significant extent, government programs and policies have contributed
to this collapse. The  incentives within welfare programs over the last 30 years
have discouraged two-parent families among the poor.  These programs also have
discouraged work and responsible behavior.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Families also have come under assault from the tax system. Today the federal
income tax takes  one-fourth of the income of the average married family with
children  and state and local taxes increase the  total government take to 38
percent. <TT><B><A HREF="ftnt6.htm">2</A></B></TT>  This
compares with just two percent in federal taxes paid by a  similar family just
after World War II. The rise in taxation is due in large part to the erosion,
through inflation, of  the personal exemption and the sharp rise in payroll
taxes.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The next generation is already under assault from the present government's
spending habits. The  national debt is a $70,000 mortgage on the back of every
child under 18. Instead of allowing Americans to pass  a patrimony of wealth on
to their children, entitlement programs are eating their future earnings.
Children  have become not dependents, but providers.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The collapse  almost extinction  of two-parent families in many
neighborhoods has contributed heavily  to the collapse of those neighborhoods.
The absence of fathers means there is no adult male financial  support, guiding
hand, or protection for children. The result: gangs of young men driven by a
destructive credo  in place of paternal guidance, young girls vulnerable to
abuse, children having children, and mindless,  violent crime.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>In addition, institutions in poor neighborhoods that once provided help and
guidance to those lacking it  at home have been crowded out by the burgeoning
welfare state. Caring and knowing local people have  been replaced by armies of
professional social workers and bureaucrats who emphasize rights and rules,  not
freedom and responsibility. Effective faith-based solutions to educational and
social deficiencies are  barred from receiving government funds to carry out
their work  and if they are able to receive support, it is  often only by giving
up their religious message.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Candidates need to explain these elements in the decline of American
society, declines already well  ad
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 2 -->  vanced in the inner cities and
growing in our suburbs, and they must warn electors that it will take  many
years to rebuild the social fabric because so much long-term damage has been
done. The key to  rebuilding society is rebuilding the family and unshackling
the institutions that complement the family. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><A NAME="FACTS">THE FACTS</A></B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Rebuilding society by rebuilding the family, however, requires reversing the
harmful effects of decades  of government social engineering. Among them: 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     The increase in illegitimacy.
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Historically, illegitimate births hovered at low rates. In recent decades,
however, this pattern has  changed radically. According to the most recent
statistics released by the Center for Health Statistics at the  U.S. Department
of Health and Human Services, illegitimacy continues to rise rapidly and
marriage continues  to decline across the United States. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Recently released HHS data show that out-of-wedlock births represented 31.0
percent of all births  in 1993, up from 30.1 percent just a year earlier. For
certain groups and parts of the country, the rates  are alarmingly high  as high
as 82 percent in one state. For all groups in all parts of the country, the
trend is  the same: steadily upwards at similar rates of increase. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Among whites in 1993, 23.6 percent of births were out of wedlock, up from 11
percent in 1980.  Among blacks, 68.7 percent of births were out of wedlock in
1993, up from 58 percent in 1980.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The most useful tool in measuring the decline in marriage and the growth in
illegitimacy is the illegitimacy  rate (more formally called the illegitimacy
ratio). The illegitimacy rate or ratio measures the number of  out-of-wedlock
births in a given year as a percent of all births in that year. Thus, if there
were 100 births, and 30  of those births were out of wedlock, the illegitimacy
rate or ratio would be 30 percent. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The illegitimacy rate is important because it measures the extent to which
illegitimacy is displacing  marriage in our society. Moreover, it is widely
recognized that illegitimacy is a profound underlying factor  contributing to
most other social problems. The illegitimacy rate is the best possible tool for
indicating the  potential magnitude of a wide array of future social problems.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>As <a href="soc_1.gif">Chart 1</a> shows, the illegitimacy rate in the U.S. has increased rapidly
over the last 30 years.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The continuing rise in the illegitimacy rate is propelled by three factors:
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     A decline in the portion of women
of childbearing age who are married;
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     An increase in the birth or fertility rate among
non-married women; and
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     A decline in the birth or fertility rate among
married women.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>While the breakdown in family is occurring across the whole age spectrum, it
is most graphic in what  has happened among teenagers over the last 35 years, in
illegitimate births, in the flight from marriage, and in  the practice of
abortion.
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 3 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     Abortion and sex outside of marriage.</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>In terms of family breakdown and the threat to children not growing up in a
family once conceived,  the different rates of abortion within and outside of
marriage contribute to the severing of society's  former linking of children,
marriage, and sexual intercourse. There is only one large sample survey,
reported in  1989 by the Alan Guttmacher Institute, which gives a snapshot of
the rates of abortion within and outside  of marriage. <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt6.htm">3</A></B></TT>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<CENTER><P><B>Abortion Rates      1988
</B></P></CENTER>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>Married, living with husband present 
																																18.5 percent
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Separated 
																																																																														6.4
percent
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Divorced 
																																																																													11.2
percent
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Never married 
																																																																							63.3
percent</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>If this ratio is applied (as the best approximation we have from research)
to the incidence of abortion  since 1973, then the following picture emerges:
The vast proportion of abortions occur among those  committed neither to the
child nor to a spouse  in other words, among the unattached. The best way to 
reduce abortion is to reduce sexual intercourse outside of marriage. This means
a cultural change that  depends primarily on the effectiveness of the family,
the church, and schools at their tasks; such a change is  not possible through
government action alone. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>- </CITE>     The high rate of divorce. 
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Divorce reached its highest rate in 1978 and has dropped only slightly since
then. Americans divorce at  the highest rate among all nations in the  world.<TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt6.htm"> 4</A></B></TT>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Since 1972, over a million children per year have suffered the pains and
effects of the breakup of  their parents' marriages.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE>     Proportion of children entering broken families. 
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P>If one adds the number of children entering broken families, either through
out-of-wedlock births or  through divorce, every year and plots them as a
proportion of the total entering life that year, one gets a fair  picture of the
proportion being affected by broken family life. This proportion has grown from
12 percent in  1950 to over 60 percent in 1992.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>The Effects of Family Breakdown
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Illegitimacy and divorce result in a disastrous emotional injury rate for
children, which means a  massively weakened future America. Even if the
illegitimacy rate declined sharply and permanently next year,  the effects on
children now being raised in broken families would be felt for generations to
come. Children  born out of wedlock or raised in a broken family suffer from:
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 4 --> 
</P>
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE>     Poorer health as newborns and, if the mother is very
young, an increased chance of dying.
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>&quot;So substantial are the differentials associated with
illegitimacy,&quot; says Nicholas Eberstadt of Harvard  University and the
American Enterprise Institute, &quot;that an American baby born to a teenage
mother is less  likely to register low birth-weight if the mother is married and
black than if she is unmarried and white....  [I]nfant mortality rates for white
mothers over age twenty were higher for unmarried but college-educated  women
than for married high-school  or even grade school  dropouts. The same pattern
holds true among  black mothers.&quot; <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt6.htm#5">5</A></B></TT>  Similar findings were
enumerated again in a 1992 National Institute of Child Health and  Development
summary, 
</P>
<P><I>Outcomes of Early Childbearing</I>.<B><CITE><A
HREF="ftnt6.htm#6"> 6
</A></CITE></B></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE>     Retarded cognitive development, especially verbal
development.</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>Illegitimate children tend to have lower verbal cognitive 
development;
<TT><B><A HREF="ftnt6.htm#7">7</A></B></TT> their early
problems in control of activity levels are precursors of later intellectual 
problems. <TT><B><A HREF="ftnt6.htm#8">8</A></B></TT>  The
effect on boys is greater, at least in  the early years.<TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt6.htm#9">9</A></B></TT>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Such findings are not new. They were well known in 1981 from Project TALENT,
a federal survey  of 375,000 commissioned in 1960, which found that children
born outside of marriage were likely to  have lower cognitive scores, lower
educational aspirations, and a greater likelihood of becoming teenage  parents
themselves. All of these effects were greater for  boys. <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt6.htm#10">10</A></B></TT> 
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>- </CITE>    Lower educational achievement.</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>A 1988 University of Illinois study of adults born outside of
marriage found that the longer the child  spends in a single-parent family, the
less education the child attains. Children who have lived in single-parent 
homes as preschoolers (which includes all those born outside of wedlock) are
most affected, and boys are  more affected than girls. <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt6.htm#11">11</A></B></TT> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>In sharp contrast with parents of illegitimate children, married parents
have higher expectations of  their children, even when the children have the
same intelligence and performance  abilities. <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt6.htm#12">12</A></B></TT>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>These findings are confirmed again and again in studies, conducted both in
the United States and  abroad, which also demonstrate that illegitimacy is
associated with lower job and salary  attainment. <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt6.htm#13">13</A></B></TT>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>With these burdens upon them, boys from such families are less likely to be
breadwinners and less likely  to attract young women seeking competent husbands
for themselves and capable fathers for their children.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE>     Lower job and income attainment. 
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>The average difference in annual salaries between adults in
their early thirties raised in intact families  and those raised in broken
families is $11,500. <TT><B><A HREF="ftnt6.htm#14">14</A></B></TT>
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE>      Increased behavior and emotional problems, and
lessened impulse control.
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>In 1990, a major analysis of national survey data confirmed
that children from intact families have far  fewer mental health and
developmental health problems. Children from mother-only families have about
twice  as 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 5 -->  many problems. <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt6.htm#15">15</A></B></TT>  They have less ability
to delay gratification, poorer impulse control (over anger  and sensual
gratification), and weaker moral  norms. <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt6.htm#16">16</A></B></TT> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>About one-third of children born to unmarried mothers, or whose parents
separate, become part of a  two-parent family within five years.
<TT><B><A HREF="ftnt6.htm#17">17</A></B></TT>  However,
this is not an unmixed blessing. Children from these  &quot;blended&quot;
families (families with step siblings) have even more difficulties than children
raised in either single-parent  or intact families. <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt6.htm#18">18</A></B></TT>  The sad fact is that the
incidence of child abuse and neglect is higher among  single-parent families.
<TT><B><A HREF="ftnt6.htm#19">19</A></B></TT>
</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE>     An increased risk for:
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>*</B>     Out-of-wedlock births. The illegitimacy rate is
highest among those who themselves were born out  of wedlock.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     Welfare dependency. Fifty percent of girls who have a baby out
of wedlock before age 18 will be  long-term welfare recipients, and 80 percent
of them will go on welfare at some  time. <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt6.htm#20">20</A></B></TT>
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>The Effects of Divorce on Adults</B><TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt6.htm#21">21</A></B></TT><B> </B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>A broken family has damaging impacts on adults, too. Life expectancy,
physical health, psychological  health, and the economic well-being of the
adults involved are all reduced. In the case of divorced adults,  they exhibit:
</P>
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE>     Shorter life expectancy.
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>Married people have consistently lower death rates from
disease, suicide, and accident  mortality. <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt6.htm#22">22</A></B></TT>  The death rate among
nonsmoking divorced men is almost the same as it is for men who smoke at least 
one pack of cigarettes a day. Overall, the premature death rate is four times
higher among divorced white  men than among their married counterparts. <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt6.htm#23">23</A></B></TT> 
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>- </CITE>    Poorer physical health. </B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>Divorced and separated people experience acute conditions such
as infectious and parasitic  diseases, respiratory illnesses, digestive system
illnesses, and severe injuries in greater numbers than other  marital status
groups. <TT><B><A HREF="ftnt6.htm#24">24</A></B></TT>
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>- </CITE>    Poorer psychological health. </B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>The divorced have higher levels of stress and psychiatric
disorders (depression, for example), which in  turn also have a profound impact
on their physical well-being, including depressed immunological  capacities.<TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt6.htm#25">25</A></B></TT> 
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE>     Lower economic well-being. </B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>Women who experience an increase in income after divorce are
either those who are very poor, and who  go on AFDC, or those who work much
longer hours after divorce than they did before  divorce. <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt6.htm#26">26</A></B></TT> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>While married black Americans have been moving steadily out of poverty (the
poverty rate among  this group, in 1994 figures, is now 11.4 percent) and are
closing in on the white married poverty rate  (8.3 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 6 -->  percent), the rate is still 53.9
percent for black American female-headed families  five times the rate  for
married black Americans. <TT><B><A HREF="ftnt6.htm#27">27</A></B></TT>

</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>How Family Breakdown Leads to Crime</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Of all the social indicators, the one which is tied most closely to serious
violent crime is illegitimacy.  The most recent figures indicate that the
illegitimate birth rate in some states for some sub-groups is a  staggering 80
percent. <TT><B><A HREF="ftnt6.htm#28">28</A></B></TT> 
With the continuing increase in illegitimacy, we can be assured of a continuing
rise in  serious violent crime.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     From 1985 to 1993, the number of
juveniles 13 and 14 years old who were arrested for murder  increased 162
percent. The murder arrest rate also increased 207 percent for 15-year-olds, 197
percent for  16-year-olds, 146 percent for 17-year-olds, and 119 percent for
juveniles ages 18 to  20. <TT><B><A HREF="ftnt6.htm#29">29</A></B></TT>

</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>      The numbers of juveniles involved in aggravated
assaults, rapes, and robberies also are rising dramatically.  If trends
continue, according to the Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI), the arrest
rates for violent  juvenile crime will double by the year 2010.<TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt6.htm#30"></A></B></TT> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     State-by-state analysis indicates that, in
general, a 10 percent increase in the percentage of children living  in
single-parent homes (including divorces) accompanies a 17 percent increase in
juvenile  crime. <TT><B><A HREF="ftnt6.htm#31">31</A></B></TT>
</P>
<P>
</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>High-crime neighborhoods tend to be single-parent neighborhoods. Researchers
long ago observed  that violent crime, among both teenagers and adults, is
concentrated most heavily in urban  neighborhoods characterized by a very high
proportion of single-parent  families. <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt6.htm#32">32</A></B></TT>  Today's researchers,
like those  before them, find that a neighborhood composed mainly of
single-parent families invariably is a chaotic,  crime-ridden community <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt6.htm#33">33</A></B></TT> where gangs assume 
control.
<TT><B><A HREF="ftnt6.htm#34">34</A></B></TT>  In these
chaotic conditions, parental supervision  of adolescent and pre-adolescent
children is almost  impossible. <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt6.htm#35">35</A></B></TT>  In turn, children living
in these  neighborhoods are more likely to learn, accept, and use physical
violence to satisfy their wants and  needs. <TT><B><A
HREF="chpt6.htm#36">36</A></B></TT>  For example:
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>-     The last 15 years have seen an extraordinary increase in
community violence in most major American  cities which, despite recent
moderately good news, has not been rolled back nearly enough. In 1990, the 
homicide rates increased in Boston by over 40 percent over the previous year; in
Denver, by 29 percent;  in Chicago, Dallas, and New Orleans, by more than 20
percent; in Los Angeles, by 16 percent; and in  New York, by 11 percent.<TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt6.htm#37">37</A></B></TT> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>-     In 1988, nationwide firearm death rates for all teenagers for the
first time exceeded the total for all  other natural causes of death combined,
and black male teens were 11 times more likely than their white  counterparts to
be killed by guns. <TT><B><A HREF="ftnt6.htm#38">38</A></B></TT>
 Thus, despite the good news of a recent drop in crime, the decrease has  to
continue for a long time for the nation to return to past levels of safety and
peace.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>-     Crime has risen sharply within inner-city schools, making places of
education &quot;no-go&quot; areas for  many children. &quot;Twenty percent of
high school students now carry a firearm, knife, razor, club, or some  other
weapon on a regular basis.&quot; <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt6.htm#39">39</A></B></TT>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>-     According to the National League of Cities, school violence during the
past year resulted in student  death and injury in 41 percent of American cities
with a population of 100,000 or  more. <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt6.htm#40">40</A></B></TT>
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 7 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>-      &quot;In 1991, 134,000 teenagers used cocaine once a week or more and
580,000 teenagers used  marijuana once a week or more. In addition, 454,000
junior and senior high school students were weekly  binge drinkers.&quot; <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt6.htm#41">41</A></B></TT>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>-      Approximately 900 teachers throughout the nation are threatened with
bodily harm, and nearly 40  are physically attacked, each hour of the school
day. Some 160,000 students miss school daily because  of intimidation or fear of
bodily harm. <TT><B><A HREF="ftnt6.htm#42">42</A></B></TT>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>-     A 1993 <I>USA Weekend</I> survey on school disruption revealed that
nearly 40 percent of students  nationwide think schools are unsafe. <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt6.htm#43">43</A></B></TT>
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>If one looks for the single biggest contributor to the rise in crime, two
factors stand out in the  research literature: the breakdown of the family and
the rise in illegitimacy.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Five Stages in the Development of a Serious Criminal </B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The five stages in the development of most serious criminals most frequently
have their beginnings in  the abandonment of the child by the father. Add abuse
and neglect in early childhood, and the child is on  his way to a serious life
of crime.
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>Stage One: Parental neglect and abandonment in early home
life</B> are characterized by different  combinations of the following:
fatherlessness, absence of a mother's love, parental fighting and domestic
violence, lack  of parental supervision and discipline, rejection of the child,
parental abuse and neglect, or criminal parents.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Stage Two: The embryonic gang</B> emerges as young, unsocialized,
aggressive children, rejected by their  more normal peers, seek and find other
alienated children, fail at school, lose interest in education, and begin  to
run wild.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Stage Three: The embryonic gang of grade school changes into a gang</B>
of tough, exploitative teenagers  who gradually become more and more expert in
crime.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Stage Four: Violence emerges as a way of life</B> within the gang as the
more expert learn to do their  crime without getting caught.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Stage Five: A new baby is born</B> to the now-criminal young father, who
stays with the child's mother for  a while before abandoning her and her child.
The mother comes from a background similar to the  young criminal father's.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>The more single-parent families we put in place, the more likely it is that
increasing numbers of children  will experience this pathway to crime. Overall,
a 10 percent increase in illegitimacy leads to a 17  percent increase in serious
violent crime (see <a href="soc_8.gif">Chart 8</a>). With the continued rise in illegitimacy, we will
see more  and more violent criminals coming onto our streets as they reach their
mid-teenage years. And with the  appearance of these criminals, we will lose
more and more of our everyday freedoms, and will be forced to  pay other huge
social and economic costs.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Drug Use on the Rise Again
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 8 --> 
</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Teenage drug use, particularly among 8th graders, is rising again as a
direct result of a change in  Administration policy.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Dr. Lloyd Johnson, program director for the University of Michigan survey of
high school drug use,  &quot;Monitoring the Future,&quot; in recent testimony
before the Senate Judiciary Committee stated that:
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>There has been a sharp increase in the proportion of young
people using marijuana. These [increases]  are specific to American adolescence.
We are seeing a rate now that is two and a half times what it was  among the
eighth graders just four years ago; two times as high among the tenth graders
and half again as  high among the twelfth graders.... Certain attitudes and
beliefs and norms among our young people are critical  to the containment of use
of these drugs. And those are in erosion.... And the fact that a much larger
pool  of youngsters are now marijuana experienced creates a greater danger that
they will go on to use other drugs.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>This is a problem which we can deal with. We have been vastly more
successful at dealing with drug  use than we have with crime, for example....
This is a labile kind of behavior.... We can influence  it. <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt6.htm#44">44</A></B></TT></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>Senator Orrin Hatch (R-UT), chairman of the committee, summed up the
findings: 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>The number of Americans using illicit drugs plunged from a peak
of 24.7 million in 1979 to 11.4 million  in 1992. The so-called casual use of
cocaine fell by 79 percent between 1985 and 1992, while  monthly cocaine use
fell 55 percent between 1988 and 1992 alone, from 2.9 million to 1.3 million
users. Now  these reductions were dramatic and unprecedented and represented
nothing less than a cultural revolution  in attitudes towards drug use. Now
we're in danger of giving back all the ground we have won.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>This is deadly serious business, since 12-17 year olds who use marijuana are
85 more times more likely  to graduate to cocaine than those who abstain from 
marijuana. <TT><B><A HREF="ftnt6.htm#45">45</A></B></TT>
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>Jim Burke, chairman of Partnership for a Drug-Free America, stated that
roughly one in thirteen of  those who take drugs become addicts: &quot;In 1962
less than 4 million Americans had ever tried an illegal drug in  their lifetime.
In 1992, one generation later, 80 million had tried illegal drugs.... Of the 80
million we now have  6 million addicts.... If you go back to 1962 we only had
300,000 addicts. The numbers are very clear:  twenty times more triers, twenty
times more addicts.... We know what works. Children are just as rational  as
adults. If they believe that the risk goes up in using drugs, their usage goes
down. Social disapproval  and perception of risk are the two drivers.&quot;
<TT><B><A HREF="ftnt6.htm#46">46</A></B></TT>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The drug situation is getting worse on all three major indicators among
teenagers:
</P>
<P></P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>-     Perception</B> of harm or risk has decreased;
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>-     Disapproval</B> of drugs among teenage peers has decreased; and
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>-     Availability</B> of drugs has increased.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>Coupled with this increase in the use of drugs is the &quot;baby-boomerang&quot;
increase in teenagers coming of  age. Dr. James Allen Fox, Dean of the College
of Criminal Justice at Northeastern University in Boston, stated  at the same
hearing: 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>Over the next ten years we will have a 23% increase in the
number of teenagers in this country.... We'll  have 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 9 -->  a 29% increase in the number of
black teenagers, a 50% percent increase in the number of Latino  teenagers. I'm
really concerned. I think this is the calm before the storm.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>I think it's a matter of supervision...one of the important elements that we
are not talking about....  For example at this point 57% of the children in this
country do not have full time parental supervision....  Almost 45% of the
juvenile violent crimes occur between 3:00 in the afternoon and dinnertime.
[They] are  unsupervised in the neighborhood. <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt6.htm#47">47</A></B></TT>
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>Jim Burke also stated: &quot;If you go back to the epidemic before [1978]
when we normalized drugs,  the average age of trial [first use] in that period
was around 16. The average age of trial today is 13....  The current marijuana
is three to five times stronger.&quot;
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The inevitable result to be expected from this worsening situation is a
sharp rise in addicts, in crime,  in AIDS, in health care costs, and in
unmeasurable family suffering.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>How the Tax System Hurts Families</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>In addition to the cultural onslaught on family life, the tax burden on
families with children has raised the  cost of having children and forced many
couples to endure a trade-off between time at home and time spent  at work
earning money to support the family. More and more couples function like a tag
team, with one  at home with the children while the other works, or work
concurrent shifts while the children are at school or  in day care.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Over the last few decades, the tax system has removed much of the help it
once gave to parents  raising young children. Rather than defend the family and
encourage marriage, the tax code now does almost  the opposite.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>In 1950, the median-income family of four paid 2 percent of its gross annual
earnings to the federal  government in income and payroll taxes. Today, it pays
24 percent. In addition, state and local taxes on  average take another 14
percent from the family's gross  income. <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt6.htm#48">48</A></B></TT>  The main reasons this
burden has risen  so sharply, other than the general increase in taxes, are that
the personal exemption has been eroded  by inflation and payroll taxes have
risen. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<CENTER><P><B>VALUE OF THE TAX EXEMPTION</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>1948                                                     42.1 percent of
median family income
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>1957.....................................28.8 percent
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>1966....................................19.6 percent
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>1975.....................................12.4 percent
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>1984.......................................7.5 percent
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>1993......................................11.4 percent
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 10 --> 
</P>
</CENTER>
<P>
</P>
<P>Families with children are overtaxed. In 1948, the average American family
with children paid only  3 percent of its income to Uncle Sam. Today, the same
family pays 24.5 percent. The average family  now loses $10,060 of income due to
the 45-year increase in federal taxes as a share of family  income.<TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt6.htm#49">49</A></B></TT> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The tax code is riddled with other anti-family, or anti-marriage, or
anti-mother-at-home inequities.  For example, there is a child care allowance
for parents who work but not for those who stay at home with  their children. If
two fathers both earn $20,000, for example, and the mother in one family goes
out to work,  that family not only has her extra income, but also can deduct up
to $1,600 for child care expenses. But if  the mother in the other family
sacrifices the extra income to stay home to look after her children, that 
family receives no tax break. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P> Moreover, the spouse who stays at home to look after the children is
penalized by the tax code in  her savings for old age. While a working mother is
allowed to invest $2,000 a year in a tax-deferred IRA,  a stay-at-home mother is
allowed to invest only $250 per year. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>The 1995 Congressional Tax Credit Proposal of $500 per Child </B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>During the budget process of 1995, Congress passed a tax credit of $500 per
child to help alleviate  the financial stress on families with children.
President Clinton, by contrast, offered a $300 tax credit that  is phased in at
higher income levels, phased out at lower income levels, and does not apply to
children  over the age of 12.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>The $500-per-child tax credit eliminates the entire income
tax burden for 3.5 million taxpayers caring  for 8.7 million children.</B> These
3.5 million families would receive over $2.2 billion per year in tax relief. 
Families with two children earning up to $24,000 per year would see their entire
income tax burden eliminated by  a $500-per-child tax credit, and families with
three children earning up to $26,000 also would have  their income tax bill
eliminated.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Cutting taxes for all families regardless of income is fair.</B>
Congress's plan will cut the income tax burden of  a family of four earning
$30,000 per year by 51 percent and the income tax burden of a family  earning
$40,000 per year by 30 percent. Meanwhile, a family of four earning $75,000
would see its tax  burden reduced by 12 percent, and a family earning $100,000
per year would receive a tax cut of just 7.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Giving a family of four a $500-per-child tax credit is equivalent to
giving them one month's  mortgage payment.</B> The average family now loses
$10,060 per year of its income due to the 45-year increase  in federal taxes as
a share of family income. This tax loss exceeds the annual mortgage payment on
the  average family home. The $1,000 in tax relief the congressional tax-cut
plan would give to a family with two  children would help this family meet one
month's mortgage payment.
</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>The Effect of Debt on America's Children</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The welfare state, with its ever-expanding appetite for taxes and
expenditures, has misdirected and  wasted a huge portion of the money in the
nation's economy. The deficit has soared as a direct result of this  unbridled
appetite, jeopardizing not only present income, but also the future incomes of
many generations.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>At present, America has 70,020,000 children under 18 and a deficit burden of
$4.887 trillion, or  $70,000 per child under 18. <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt6.htm#50">50</A></B></TT>  This means that even if
Congress balanced all future budgets and kept up with  the 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 11 -->  interest payments, every child
under 18 still faces a future mortgage of $70,000. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P> To appreciate the effect this has on the economy, consider the opposite:
Rather than a mortgage  of $70,000 on each child, assume an investment of
$70,000 in each child at birth. This investment would  yield huge benefits.
Indeed, $70,000 invested at birth would grow to over $11,000,000 (in future 
dollars) <TT><B><A HREF="ftnt6.htm#51">51</A></B></TT> by
retirement age and also do all of the following (in future dollars):
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>-     Pay $5,000 a year for grade school education;
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>-     Pay $7,000 a year for high school education;
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>-     Pay $12,000 a year for college education for six years;
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>-     Pay $7,000 a year for medical and unemployment insurance from age 25;
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>-     Pay for a $50,000 downpayment on a house at age 30; and
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>-     Pay $30,000 a year for the education of the children and increase
their insurance to $8,000 per year,  all starting at age 35.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>The national debt, however, will have the opposite effects on our children:
correspondingly less money  for their education, less money for their insurance,
less money for their college education, and  instead  of capital to draw on to
build their families and futures  heavy taxes to pay off the debt.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>In solid families with good traditions, parents strive to add to the
patrimony (inheritance) they leave  their children, expecting them to do
likewise for the grandchildren. Parents who not only would leave nothing,  but
also would go so far as to mortgage the lives of their children by their own
profligate spending incur  appropriate scorn and are seen as economic pariahs.
The welfare state is doing this to our children.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>A Further Result of Federal Taxes: Family Time Famine. Getting adequate
after-tax family income  has become more difficult for married parents with
children. Consequently, family time suffers as work  outside the home becomes
more common for mothers of school-age children.
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>*     On average, parents are available 10 hours less per week
to their children than they were a decade  ago, and a full 40 percent less today
than in  1965.
<TT><B><A HREF="ftnt6.htm#52">52</A></B></TT>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>*     Adequate time with parents is critical for the development of every
child, especially for their self-esteem  and confidence. As Harvard University
child psychiatrist Robert Coles puts it, &quot;The frenzied need of children  to
have possessions isn't only a function of the ads they see on TV. It's a
function of their hunger for what  they aren't getting  their parents' time.&quot;
<TT><B><A HREF="ftnt6.htm#53">53</A></B></TT>
</P>
<P>*     As <a href="soc_11.gif">Chart 11</a> shows, more and more children do not have their mothers
available to them after school hours. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>*     A Massachusetts Mutual 1993 poll found that 33 percent of parents say
they do not spend enough  time with preschool children, and 46 percent say do
not spend enough time with  teenagers. <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt6.htm#54">54</A></B></TT>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>*     A 1990 <I>Los Angeles Times</I> poll found that 57 percent of all
fathers and 55 percent of all mothers felt  guilty about spending too little
time with their children. The poll also found that 73 percent of all married 
couples would have one parent stay home full-time with the children &quot;if
money were not an  issue.&quot; <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt6.htm#55">55</A></B></TT>
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 12 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>*     Reflecting the growing concern about the time famine, a Yankelovich
poll found a big jump (from 39  percent to 57 percent) between 1989 and 1990 in
mothers who would give up work indefinitely if they no  longer needed the money.<TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt6.htm#56">56</A></B></TT>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>*     Reflecting the concern about mother absence, a 1993 poll by the Family
Research Council found that  89 percent of parents believe their children would
do better if cared for by their mothers rather than by  day care providers.
Similarly, an increasing number of parents think too many children are being
raised in  child care. <TT><B><A HREF="ftnt6.htm#57">57</A></B></TT>
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Themes for Reform</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>America's often disparaged, traditional two-parent family is the principal
social institution by which the  work ethic, self-discipline, intellectual
motivation, and moral character are passed on to the next generation.  The
traditional family is the foundation of American society, and when it is
weakened, the nation is weakened.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>For decades, the government has pursued policies which help assure the
collapse of the family. To  change course, fundamental changes are required in a
wide range of policies. These changes embody five themes.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>THEME 1: Reducing the government financial burden on working families. 
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>The traditional family is the original department of health,
education, and welfare, but government  for decades has engaged in punitive
policies which discourage marriage and make it difficult for the  traditional
family to carry out its functions. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>In 1950, the median family of four paid just 3 percent of its income to the
federal government in  taxes. Today, that figure has risen to 24 percent; when
state and local taxes are thrown in, the typical family of  four now pays 38
percent of its income in taxes to the government.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The extraordinary cost of financing the Great Society and the War on Poverty
has been borne in  large measure by the middle class, especially by parents with
children. In response to this crushing tax  burden, many in the middle class
have delayed marriage and, when they have married, have put off having  children
and reduced the number of children they raise.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Ironically, even as its punitive tax policy discourages child rearing by
traditional middle-class families,  the government continues to subsidize child
rearing by never-married women who generally are ill-prepared  to act as
parents. The results of this disastrous policy are only too apparent. Current
government policy,  which places punitive and crippling financial burdens on
traditional two-parent families while subsidizing  illegitimacy, is a recipe for
eventual social collapse. 
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>THEME 2: Reforming welfare to control costs and require work to improve
the lot of the &quot;welfare family.&quot;  
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>Today's welfare system crushes low-income families by placing
anti-family requirements on mothers as  the price of receiving welfare, as well
as by discouraging employment. The steps needed to change this  destructive
incentive system are outlined in the accompanying chapter on welfare reform.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>THEME 3: Reducing illegitimacy. 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 13 --> 
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>Societies through the ages have recognized that it takes the
efforts of at least two persons, a father and  a mother, to provide the economic
and psychological support needed to raise children. Women who  have children out
of wedlock invariably impose a heavy financial burden on the society around
them. A  father's absence also threatens the psychological well-being of his
children. Thus, societies historically have gone  to great lengths to encourage
marriage and, conversely, to discourage illegitimacy. In the recent past,  the
United States has experimented with reversing this common wisdom by aggressively
subsidizing  single parenthood and penalizing marriage. The results of this
experiment have been disastrous.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>For the well-being of American children and the safety of society, a moral
sense of responsible  parenthood must be restored, based on the commonsense
principle that it is immoral to have children unless one is  fully prepared to
raise those children. To be fully prepared to raise children means three simple
things. First,  the mother and father must be married and committed to a life
together. Second, they must be mature  and psychologically ready for the
difficult task of raising the young. Third, they should be economically 
productive and self-sufficient, able to sustain a family without large amounts
of ongoing financial support from  the larger community.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>THEME 4: Reforming divorce law and strengthening marriage. 
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>Over the past 40 years, government policy has made divorce
easily available, and welfare has  subsidized family breakup. The principal
victims have been children. These trends should be reversed.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>While divorce and marriage law should remain under the control of state
legislatures, it is clear that levels  of divorce and marital instability have
direct repercussions on the federal welfare system and on the  overall
well-being of America's children. Thus, the federal government should use the &quot;bully
pulpit&quot; to urge  reforms at the state level.
</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>THEME 5: Revitalizing civil society. <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt6.htm#58">58</A></B></TT></B> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>While reforms in taxes, divorce law, and welfare are necessary
steps in dealing with the problems of  family disintegration and the underclass,
they are not sufficient in themselves. Welfare programs in particular,  by
subsidizing self-destructive behavior, have played a huge role in promoting
underclass problems. But  welfare is not the sole cause of these burgeoning
problems: Changing cultural values and norms concerning  sexual behavior,
marriage, work, respect for others, and self-control have played a heavy  role.
<TT><B><A HREF="ftnt6.htm#59">59</A></B></TT>  Members of
Congress and others seeking a comprehensive solution must look beyond reforming
welfare programs  and into the broader culture. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Government leaders seeking to reestablish sound norms and virtuous behavior
within vulnerable  groups would do well to look to the past. Few people realize
that 19th century America fought several wars  on poverty which, in contrast to
the 20th century version, were quite successful. These historic  anti-poverty
efforts were headed by non-governmental institutions, primarily churches, which
saw poverty as  emanating from behavior and individual  character. <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt6.htm#60">60</A></B></TT>  They took as their
central task the molding of character and  self-discipline within vulnerable
low-income communities. For example:
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><P>-     The Young Men's Christian Association (YMCA)
was established to combat urban crime. Seeing  its mission as molding the moral
character of the young, the YMCA successfully undertook a struggle to  win the
hearts and minds of inner-city youth, leading to a major drop in juvenile crime.
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 14 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>-     Catholic parochial education is a dramatic instance of long-lasting
private voluntary endeavor. In  founding Georgetown University in 1792, Bishop
John Carroll argued for the necessity of a &quot;pious and  Catholic education
for the young.&quot;  Carroll hoped that Georgetown's graduates would supply a
pool of teachers  for the Catholic schools of local parishes. Today those
schools provide superior education, open to children  of all faiths, and of
tremendous importance to poor inner-city parents seeking an alternative to
public  education.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>-     The Young Women's Christian Association (YWCA) gave a chaperoned place
to live to young  women migrating to the cities from rural areas. The stability
immediately available to them permitted them  gradually to find the community
life in which they felt comfortable, and safe fellowship after leaving their
families  and original communities.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>-     The Red Cross is a massive private-sector organization which runs the
world's largest blood collection  and distribution system as just one of its
projects.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>-     The temperance movement of the mid-1800s, a response to the growing
alcohol addiction of the  time, resulted in massive reductions in alcohol
consumption and a change of attitude toward the abuse of alcohol. 
</P></BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>Dealing with social problems by placing greater reliance on non-governmental
social institutions is  therefore nothing new. It is a return to the fundamental
political philosophy upon which the American Republic  was established. The
Founders, because they understood the dangers inherent in looking to government
as  a cure for social ills, relied instead on civil institutions such as the
family and church.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>This wisdom is reflected in the writings of one of the most astute observers
of American politics and  society, Alexis de Tocqueville. De Tocqueville
emphasized the crucial role in American society of such  &quot;private
associations&quot; as religious institutions, private philanthropies, clubs,
fellowships, voluntary civic  associations, and private moral and educational
institutions. According to de Tocqueville, these private associations  or civil
institutions were more important than America's political and economic
institutions. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>One of the functions of private civil associations was to affirm, renew, and
sustain social virtues. It was  their task to inculcate into Americans the basic
virtues and norms which make civilized life possible.  Without these
value-affirming and renewing institutions, Americans would soon lose their
capacity to maintain  healthy families, to work honestly and diligently, to
educate and govern themselves, and even to live next to  one another without
murder and mayhem. In other words, civil institutions provided the moral
foundation  which made the political and economic superstructure possible, and
their ability to shape individual character  and to inculcate individuals with
the virtues and norms necessary for social life was essential to the 
continuance of society. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Over the last hundred years, however, government has usurped much of the
role of civil associations.  One social function after another  education,
charity, and, increasingly, child-rearing  has passed from  civil institutions
into the hands of government bureaucrats. By arrogating to itself more and more
of those  functions, and by monopolizing an ever-larger share of the financial
resources needed for operation of  civil institutions, government decisively
undermines private civil associations. By diminishing and  shouldering aside
value-affirming institutions, government wages war on society's natural immune
system. The  growing underclass and the collapse of the family are only two of
the many problems which stem from this assault.
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 15 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>The Crucial Role of Religion.</B> In grappling with the burgeoning
problems of family disintegration, crime,  and dependence, Americans must
utilize all the vital resources within society. History, common sense,  and
research all show that there is one neglected institution ideally suited to lead
this struggle of moral renewal  in low-income communities and across the nation:
the church. Efforts to tackle underclass problems in the  19th century succeeded
largely because they were spearheaded by value-laden religious institutions. By 
contrast, efforts to fight urban poverty in the 20th century frequently have
failed because of their reliance on  value-free government programs.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>-     Research by Dr. Richard Freeman of Harvard University
shows that black inner-city youth with  religious values are 47 percent less
likely to drop out of school, 54 percent less likely to use drugs, and 50 
percent less likely to engage in criminal activities than those without
religious  values. <TT><B><A HREF="ftnt6.htm#61">61</A></B></TT>

</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>-      Religious practices can play a large role in reducing illegitimacy.
Religious belief and practice have  been shown to reduce significantly the level
of pre-marital sexual activity among adolescent  girls, <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt6.htm#62">62</A></B></TT> and regular church
attendance has been shown to cut the probability of out-of-wedlock births
roughly in half. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>-     Studies also show that young people who attend church have a positive
effect on the behavior of  other youngsters in their immediate neighborhoods.
The effect of young people motivated by religious values is  the exact opposite
of the heavily publicized negative peer pressure exerted by street gangs who
suck the  young into lives of aimless violence and  alienation. <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt6.htm#63">63</A></B></TT>
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>Echoing this research, criminologist John DiIulio sees moral decay at the
heart of America's terrifying  crime problem. He explains that crime is driven
not, as old-fashioned liberals believe, by material deprivation,  but by moral
deprivation  not by material poverty, but by &quot;moral poverty.&quot;
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>Moral poverty is the poverty of being without loving, capable,
responsible adults who teach you right  from wrong. It is the poverty of being
without parents and other authorities who habituate you to feel joy  at others'
joy, pain at others' pain, happiness when you do right, remorse when you do
wrong. It is the  poverty of growing up in the virtual absence of people who
teach morality by their own everyday example  and who insist that you follow
suit.... In the extreme, moral poverty is the poverty of growing up surrounded 
by deviant, delinquent, and criminal adults in abusive, violence-ridden,
fatherless, Godless, and jobless  settings. In sum, whatever their material
circumstances, kids of whatever their race, creed, or color are most likely  to
become criminally depraved when they are morally  deprived. <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt6.htm#64">64</A></B></TT>
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>DiIulio sees help for these morally deprived children not in bigger
government, but in a revitalization of  civil society: of De Toqueville's
private associations. In particular, DiIulio views the church as society's last 
hope, the final dam which separates us from the onrushing tidal wave of violent
&quot;super-predators.&quot;
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>My one big idea is borrowed from three well-known
child-development experts  Moses, Jesus  Christ, and Mohammed. It's called
religion. If we are to have a prayer of stopping any significant fraction of 
the super-predators short of the prison gates, then we had better say &quot;Amen,&quot;
and fast.... So let our  guiding principle be, &quot;Build churches, not jails&quot;
 or we will reap the whirlwind of our own moral  bankruptcy. <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt6.htm#65">65</A></B></TT>  
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><A NAME="RECORD">THE RECORD</A></B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>THE CLINTON ADMINISTRATION
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 16 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>President Clinton has said some very good things on the family and on the
breakdown of family and  marriage. However, he frequently contradicts himself,
and his actions have been very different from his  rhetoric. For instance, in
addressing the National Governors' Association, the President said that &quot;There
are  almost no poor children in families with two parents in the home.&quot; 
And on abstinence, he has said that &quot;we need  to send a strong signal that
it is essential for young people to delay sexual activity, as well as having 
children, until they are ready to accept the responsibilities and consequences
of these actions. It is critical that we  help all youth understand the rewards
of...deferring childbearing until they are  married.&quot; <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt6.htm#66">66</A></B></TT>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>However, Secretary of Health and Human Services Donna Shalala has been
vehement in her opposition  to such programs. Commenting on her elimination of
Title XX (abstinence) funds from the Clinton budget  in 1994, she said that &quot;abstinence
only messages provide no hope of protection at all against the risks  of
pregnancy and disease.&quot; <TT><B><A HREF="ftnt6.htm#67">67</A></B></TT>

</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The President has never reinstated Title XX in his budget, not even since
announcing his Teen  Pregnancy Initiative in January 1996. Instead of standing
for marriage as the traditional place for sexual  expression, President Clinton
has pushed for the enshrinement in public policy of homosexual sex as equal to
sex  in heterosexual marriage.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>On abortion the President has repeatedly said: &quot;I believe abortion
should be safe, legal and  rare.&quot; <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt6.htm#68">68</A></B></TT>  However, on January 22,
1993, two days after his inauguration, his first four executive orders were all
directed  at liberalizing American abortion regulations: To make foreign aid
money available for use in providing  abortions in other countries; <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt6.htm#69">69</A></B></TT> to speed up the granting
of FDA approval to RU-486, a drug designed to  make abortion a very easy form of
birth control; <TT><B><A HREF="ftnt6.htm#70">70</A></B></TT>
to permit the spending of Title X monies for abortion  counseling; <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt6.htm#71"></A></B></TT> and to reinstate the
practice of abortions at military  hospitals.
<TT><B><A HREF="ftnt6.htm#72">72</A></B></TT>  While the
views of the President  were well known and an open part of the debate, even he,
aware of the need for delicate handling of this  issue, has stated: &quot;If
people in Washington spent less time in using abortion to divide the country for
their  own political ends....&quot; <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt6.htm#73">73</A></B></TT>Despite this, he made
known he was signing these memoranda as the annual  pro-life march was being
held near the White House.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Taxes and the Family</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>During his presidential campaign, candidate Bill Clinton promised a tax
credit of $800 per  child. <TT><B><A HREF="ftnt6.htm#74">74</A></B></TT>
 But in 1993, he gave families the biggest tax hike in history, which also means
he has taken more money  and parental time away from the family than anyone in
U.S. history.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>When Congress included a $500-per-child tax credit in the Budget
Reconciliation Act of 1996,  President Clinton opposed it as giving money to the
rich even though almost 90 percent of the monies went to  middle-class and
poorer families. However, as Table 2 shows, the relief to the poor was higher at
every stage in  the congressional plan than in the Clinton proposal.
</P>
<P><B>THE 104TH CONGRESS</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>On Illegitimacy:</B> In the welfare reform package which passed the
House and Senate and which was part  of the budget reconciliation package sent
to the President in November 1993, Congress moved to reduce  the welfare rewards
and reinforcements for increased numbers of children out of wedlock. Congress 
forbade states to spend federal monies for increased welfare payments for new
children born out of wedlock  while the mother was on welfare. (States could
spend their own money for these increased payments.)  The President vetoed the
bill.
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 17 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>On Abortion:</B> Congress outlawed the use of partial birth abortions, a
procedure involving cranial collapse  of the seven to nine month old fetus
followed by dismemberment and suction removal. The President  has promised to
veto it.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Fatherlessness:</B> Congress toughened the child support provisions in
the welfare bill which was part of  the reconciliation package vetoed by the
President in November 1995.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Pro-family tax changes:</B> Historically mothers who stay at home to
care for young children have been  penalized in the regulations covering
individual retirement accounts (IRAs). Congress, in the budget  reconciliation
bill, removed the discrimination against these mothers. President Clinton vetoed
the bill.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>WHAT TO DO IN 1997</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The key to arresting America's moral decay is to restore the historic
balance between the state and  civil society  to revitalize those private
institutions which are society's natural immune system.  Destructive policy
influences must be reversed, and the beneficial effects of non-governmental
institutions must  be allowed once again to play their full role in rebuilding
civil society.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>These themes translate into the following policy prescriptions:
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Cut taxes on middle-class families with children at both the federal and
state levels. 
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>Healthy families are the foundation of a successful society,
and government must seek to strengthen  marriage as the crucial institution
within which future generations of Americans will be raised. The most obvious 
step is to reduce sharply the crippling tax burden it now places on young
working and middle-class parents  with children.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The $500-per-child tax credit passed by the present Congress but vetoed by
President Clinton is only a  first step in this regard. This tax credit should
be enacted now and followed by larger tax cuts for families  with children in
the near future.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Create a pro-marriage tax credit at the federal and state levels. 
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>The current welfare system heavily penalizes marriage between a
mother and a working man. This  marriage penalty should be reduced through
creation of a tax credit for lower-income parents who are married  and working
rather than living on welfare. The pro-marriage tax credit should be available
to  low-income married couples who are living together and supporting dependent
children; the family should have  the equivalent of at least one adult working
full time. The credit should be refundable and should have a  maximum value of
$1,000.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Avoid false solutions.
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>One simplistic solution to the anti-marriage and anti-work
effects of welfare would be to allow a  welfare mother to retain all or most of
her benefits after she has taken a job or married a fully employed male.  But
this approach would be unfair to working single mothers and to low-income,
working married couples  who never went on welfare in the first place. Moreover,
it would give low- and moderate-income parents a  huge 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 18 -->  incentive to enroll in welfare,
at least briefly, to become eligible for the long-term continuing benefits. Such
 a system would degenerate inevitably into one in which the majority of low- and
moderate-income single-  and two-parent families received substantial welfare
payments, raising the overall cost of welfare by hundreds  of billions of
dollars per year. Realistic reformers must seek to alter welfare incentives in a
more  practical manner.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Promote abstinence at the federal and state levels.
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>Scientific experiments have shown that strong sexual abstinence
curricula substantially change  teenagers' attitudes toward early sexual
activity. Among girls taking abstinence courses, pregnancy rates have  been
reduced by over 40 percent when compared to girls who have not taken the 
classes. <TT><B><A HREF="ftnt6.htm#75">75</A></B></TT>  By
contrast, programs promoting contraception often increase pregnancy rates. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Teen sexual abstinence is a logical developmental step in the life of a good
citizen and future strong  parent and marriage partner. Joseph Piccione and
Robert  Scholle, <TT><B><A HREF="ftnt6.htm#76">76</A></B></TT>
former policy analysts at the Office of  Population Affairs in the Department of
Health and Human Services, explain:
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><P>While no one can dispute the health advantages of
abstinence, and while most people would admit that it  is the socially,
developmentally, and psychologically appropriate course for an adolescent, there
are many  who assert that abstinence is impossible for an adolescent. This
assertion is groundless. For decades, if  not centuries, sexual abstinence was
expected of unmarried individuals in Western society. According to  the National
Survey of Family Growth (NSFG), abstinence was the norm among unmarried American
 teenage girls at least until 1982. <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt6.htm#77">77</A></B></TT>  The best of the recent
surveys of high school age youth (young people  14-17 years old) was conducted
as part of the National Health Interview Survey of 1992. This survey showed 
that 56.6 percent of adolescents were virgins. <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt6.htm#78">78</A></B></TT>  A series of surveys
conducted over the last 25 years by 
<I>Who's Who Among American High School  Students</I> shows that only one in
four top students is sexually  active. This suggests that abstinence is not only
possible, but associated with high levels of personal  achievement. <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt6.htm#79">79</A></B></TT>
</P></BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>Contrary to the expectations of many adults, the majority of teens seem
interested in what  abstinence-based programs might have to offer. A survey of
1,000 girls conducted by Emory University found that of a  dozen possible sex
education topics, the most popular (chosen by 84 percent of the respondents) was
 more information on how to say &quot;no&quot; to a boyfriend's requests for sex
without losing the  boyfriend. <TT><B><A HREF="ftnt6.htm#80">80</A></B></TT>
 It is also evident from a February 1994 Roper Starch poll that 12-17-year-olds
regard the pressure to have sex  as the prime threat to their well-being. <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt6.htm#81">81</A></B></TT>  It seems obvious that
adolescents have been calling on adults  to protect them with reasonable
behavioral limits. For many years, however, the vogue in child-rearing was  to
ignore such calls.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Promote adoption at the federal and state levels.
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Congress should pass a $5,000 tax credit for couples who adopt a child,
fundable (that is, those who  do not pay $5,000 in federal taxes still should
receive $5,000 support) so that poorer families will be  encouraged to adopt and
not be left out of the pool of adopting parents.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>While the numbers of children born out of wedlock have been increasing
massively, the practice of  adoption has been decreasing.
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 19 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The benefits of growing up in a two-parent family are illustrated again
among adopted children.  Adopted children do as well as or better than their
non-adopted  counterparts. <TT><B><A HREF="ftnt6.htm#82">82</A></B></TT>
 Adopted children score higher  than their middle-class two-parent counterparts
on indicators of school performance, social competency,  optimism, and
volunteerism.<TT><B><A HREF="ftnt6.htm#83">83</A></B></TT>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Adopted adolescents generally are less depressed than children of single
parents and less involved in  alcohol abuse, vandalism, group fighting, police
trouble, weapon use, and  theft; <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt6.htm#84">84</A></B></TT> they score higher on
self-esteem, confidence in their own judgment, self-directness, positive view of
others, and feelings of security within  their families. <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt6.htm#85">85</A></B></TT>  On health measures,
adopted children and children of intact families share similarly high  scores,
and both groups score significantly higher on these measures than children
raised by single  parents. <TT><B><A HREF="ftnt6.htm#86">86</A></B></TT>
 Adopted children do well at school. In 1988, only 7 percent of children adopted
in infancy repeated  a grade. <TT><B><A HREF="ftnt6.htm#87">87</A></B></TT>
 By contrast, 33 percent of children whose mothers had never married repeated a
grade.  Adoptive parents also are less likely to divorce. <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt6.htm#88">88</A></B></TT>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Significantly, teenage mothers who choose adoption also do better then
unmarried teen mothers who  choose to become single parents. Unmarried teen
mothers who choose adoption have higher educational  aspirations and are more
likely to finish school than mothers who keep their children; are less likely to
live in  poverty and receive public assistance; are more likely to marry
eventually; are more likely to be employed  12 months after the birth and less
likely to repeat out-of-wedlock pregnancy; and are no more likely to  suffer
depression or other negative psychological consequences than mothers who rear
children as single  parents. <TT><B><A HREF="ftnt6.htm#89">89</A></B></TT>
 Thus, all goals of liberal government programs such as job training,
supplemental education,  and family planning services are attained with greater
ease, and a lower cost, through adoption.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Although adoption meets the interests of the needy child better than any
other option, Elizabeth Bartholet  of Harvard Law School concludes that
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>[O]ur adoption system has failed to live up to even its own
limited vision....Laws and policies that  are supposed to protect children have
created barriers to adoption that function effectively to prevent  these
children from getting the kind of protection they most need: &quot;a loving,
nurturing and permanent home.&quot;
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>Several barriers make it very difficult for many families to adopt children.
These barriers include  anti-adoption bias in pregnancy counseling, with most
counselors not even raising the option of adoption;  misuse of the family
preservation principle in social work, which prolongs the danger to severely
abused  children instead of rescuing them and placing them for adoption sooner;
overload and confusion of social  service roles, with the work of preserving
families sometimes in seeming conflict with that of rescuing children  in danger
(most social service agencies do not resolve this dilemma and leave the burden
to the child);  unsatisfactory protections of confidentiality, which inhibit the
adoption option; unknown, uninvolved, or  unmarried fathers who increasingly, at
local court levels are permitted to block adoption processes; and the race of 
the child and the adoptive parents, with many social workers against transracial
adoptions even if parents of  the same race as the child are not readily
available to adopt (which puts the burden on the child rather than  on the
community).
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Enforce statutory rape laws at the state level.
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Male accountability is needed. In many inner-city communities, when 16- or
17-year-old girls  become pregnant, the father is often four or five years older
than the girl. Such cases often involve statutory rape,  a 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 20 -->  serious criminal offense.
Congress should hold hearings to emphasize the role of statutory rape in 
contributing to pregnancy among young girls, and the states should act
vigorously and visibly to enforce their  statutory rape laws in such cases as a
way to deter such predatory male behavior in the future.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>End &quot;no-fault&quot; divorce at the state level and require waiting
periods, mediation, and counseling.
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P>In most states today, it is easier to terminate a marriage contract than a
contract to purchase a new  washing machine. Marriage is America's most
important social institution; steps must be taken to restore its  sanctity and
the seriousness of marital commitment. State governments immediately should
eliminate no-fault  divorce for couples with children. In the future, the major
share of the costs of divorce, as well as the future costs  of raising the
children, should be borne by the parent who is at fault (or by the party who
initiated the divorce  if no fault is found). Couples seeking a divorce who have
children should be required to undertake  counseling, and states should
establish a six-month waiting period for completion of any divorce action.
During  divorce proceedings, children should be represented by a separate
attorney tasked with representing their  interests (which often may be for the
parents to remain together).
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Encourage pre-marriage counseling.
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Marriage is a legal and social institution designed to enforce the binding
commitments of a man and  a woman to one another, and to provide the best
environment for the raising of children within society.  Society has an interest
and obligation (to children not yet born) to seek to ensure that marriages which
are  formed will have a good chance of not only enduring, but flourishing.
States should insist that individuals  receive some form of pre-marital
counseling as a condition of receiving a marriage license.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Part of counseling should be an evaluation to inform prospective spouses of
the probability that their  marriage will end in divorce. Modern evaluation
devices such as the PREPARE (Premarital Personal  and Relationship Evaluation)
questionnaire can predict with an accuracy of over 80 percent whether a 
marriage will end in divorce. PREPARE already is offered by thousands of
churches across the nation. It is in the  best interest of all concerned
(especially the children yet unborn) that the fiancees be informed of their 
prospects for marital success before they have embarked on what should be a
lifelong  commitment. <TT><B><A HREF="ftnt6.htm#90">90</A></B></TT></P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Fight moral decay through school choice at the federal and state levels.
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The plight of the underclass is rooted in behavior; behavior in turn is
molded by the cultural values  and norms of low-income communities and the
larger society. For the problems of the underclass to be  solved, there must be
a dramatic change in behavior, which in turn will require an enormous shift in
underlying  norms and values. Policymakers must seek to reanimate within
low-income communities the ethical  principles which are the foundation of a
successful society. To combat the growing problem of the underclass,  Americans
need a multi-dimensional policy which harnesses all the vital forces in our
society. But in the war  against poverty and violence, the most effective social
weapon  the church  lies dormant.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The key to harnessing the church's untapped social strength is another
crucial public policy issue:  school choice. Poor parents should be given
vouchers equivalent to the sum which is spent educating their  children in the
public schools. These parents would be free to use the voucher to place their
children into a school  of their own choice, including private religious
schools. If voucher plans were put in place in large cities,  dozens of
high-quality private religious schools would spring up immediately in each city,
operating as adjuncts  of urban churches. Many low-income parents, struggling to
save their sons and daughters from the social  tide 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 21 -->  of violence, drugs, and sexual
promiscuity, would be overjoyed to place their children under the firm  moral
tutelage of such church-related schools, each one of which would function as a
focal point of moral  renewal emanating into the surrounding community. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Unlike Bill Clinton, Al Gore, and Jesse Jackson (and many Members of 
Congress), <TT><B><A HREF="ftnt6.htm#91">91</A></B></TT>
who are wealthy enough to send their children to private schools, poor parents
are left with the inert monopoly of the  public schools, institutions which no
longer can adequately teach simple reading, let alone serve as the focal  point
for moral transformation within underclass communities. In grappling with the
problems of dependence  and the underclass, education voucher programs for
low-income parents are an indispensable complement  to welfare reform.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Liberals will argue that providing parents with vouchers which can be used
in religious schools violates  the First Amendment prohibition on establishment
of religion. This is untrue. The Supreme Court has  clearly ruled, in <I>Mueller
v. Allen</I> and <I>Witters v. Washington State Department of Services for the 
Blind</I>, that vouchers or tax credits can be spent for religious education
without creating constitutional problems. Just  as a widow can place her Social
Security check in the collection plate of a church or synagogue, or a  veteran
can use funds from the GI Bill to go to seminary without violating the
constitutional provisions against  state-established religion, a poor parent may
use education vouchers to place a child in a religious school. As  long as the
parent, not the government, decides where the voucher funds will be spent, the
government  has neither advanced nor hindered a particular religion, and there
is no violation of the religious  establishment clause of the First Amendment.
<TT><B><A HREF="ftnt6.htm#92">92</A></B></TT>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The church is thus America's strongest weapon in the war against family
disintegration, crime, drugs,  and despair in low-income communities. Churches
can succeed in tackling these problems where  government has failed. Instead of
relegating the churches to the social periphery, policymakers must unleash their
 energy, permitting them to play a much greater role in molding the character of
youth and adults.  Specifically, Congress should redirect a substantial portion
of federal aid to primary and secondary education into  model voucher programs
for poor parents in inner cities.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><A NAME="Q&A">Q &amp; A</A></B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Q. What right does government have to tell people what their moral
values should be? 
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>A.</B> Government is not the fundamental moral teacher; that is the duty
of the church or synagogue and  the family itself, the first and most intimate
source of moral instruction. But government does have a  profound responsibility
to inform American taxpayers about the costs and consequences of personal 
behaviors, including violations of the marriage contract, child abuse, or the
dramatic growth in out-of-wedlock  birth, precisely because of their profoundly
negative social impact on the character and quality of American  life:
increasing numbers of psychologically damaged children, rising crime and
juvenile delinquency,  substance abuse and welfare dependency. Americans are
free to live by any moral code they wish, or none at all.  But they should not
expect taxpayers to pick up the tab, without imposing any conditions, for what 
traditionally has been understood to be immoral behavior. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Q. What right does government have to tell people what form of family
they are to have?
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>A.</B> From time immemorial, government in every civilized society has
recognized marriage and the family  as the basic and most venerable institutions
of the social order. Indeed, government has always had a  direct 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 22 -->  interest in both the
establishment and maintenance of the traditional marriage contract and the
family,  the mutual obligations of a husband and wife and of parents to their
children. To that end, an entire body  of domestic law has been established,
governing everything from the state's issuance of marriage licenses to  the
preservation of family property and inheritance and the protection of children.

</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Of course, Americans are free to experiment and to have any &quot;alternative
family arrangements&quot; they  wish. But the empirical evidence is overwhelming
that the intact, two-parent family is superior to any other  arrangement.
Children thrive and do better in stable married families than anywhere else.
Their health,  their learning, their income, their mental and emotional
well-being, and their avoidance of drugs, crime,  welfare dependency, and
illegitimacy are much lower than those of children in single-parent families.
America  is stronger because of married families and weaker when families are
broken or unformed. As a matter  of public policy, therefore, it is perfectly
reasonable to promote and preserve the traditional family. As a  matter of
public policy, it is perfectly unreasonable to do anything else. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Q. What has been the record of federal drug treatment (as opposed to
enforcement) programs?
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>A.</B> Poor. Federal drug treatment spending almost tripled between 1988
and 1994, but the number  of persons treated actually declined from 1.5 million
in 1989 to 1.4 million in  1994. <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt6.htm#93">93</A></B></TT>  Most addicts have been
through treatment more than once. As summed up by John Walters, deputy director
of the White  House Office of National Drug Control Policy during the Bush
Administration, &quot;The harsh fact is that drug  addicts like taking drugs,
even though most of them also dislike some aspects and consequences of their
drug  use. They sometimes admit themselves to treatment programs, not to stop
using their drugs, but to regain  greater control over their drug use; but the
overwhelming majority of addicts entering treatment with the goal  of ending
their drug use are coerced to do so by the courts, family members, or employers.
That is why  the liberals who discuss treatment as if it were the opposite of
enforcement show a profound ignorance of  the reality of drug treatment.&quot;
<TT><B><A HREF="ftnt6.htm#94">94</A></B></TT>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Q. How would conservatives fashion a policy on drug treatment?
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>A.</B> Congress should combine federal anti-drug support to states and
localities (estimated at $3.5 billion  in FY 1994) into anti-drug block grants
for states and local communities. In this way, states and local  communities can
use these funds for anti-drug treatment and rehabilitation programs that work
best. At the  same time, it is essential that Congress establish performance
standards so that organizations receiving  funds demonstrate that they are
effective in treating addicts. Interestingly, some of the best drug and  alcohol
treatment and rehabilitation programs in the nation are those that are connected
with religious or  faith-based institutions. They are successful precisely
because they are able to effect a deep internal or spiritual  commitment on the
part of addicts to resist the use of illegal drugs or the abuse of alcohol. 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 23 --> 
</P>
