<TITLE>Immigration - Issues '96 - Heritage</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<center>
<h2>Issues '96: The Candidate's Briefing Book</h2>
<b><A HREF="/heritage">The Heritage Foundation</a></b>
</center><p>
<h3>Chapter 11</h3>
<center>
<h2>IMMIGRATION</h2>

<B><CITE>By Joe Cobb</CITE></B>
<P>
<A HREF="chpt11.html#ISSUES">The Issues</A> | <A HREF="chpt11.html#FACTS">The Facts</A> |  <A HREF="chpt11.html#RECORD">The Record</A> | <A HREF="chpt11.html#Q&A">Q&amp;A</A> | <a href="chpt11.html#EXP">Experts</a>  
</center>
<p>
<a href="immig_1.gif">Chart 1</a>: Foreign-Born Population, by Country of Origin<br>
<a href="immig_2.gif">Chart 2</a>: Number of Immigrant Arrivals by Decade, 1820-1990<br>
<a href="immig_3.gif">Chart 3</a>: Immigrants as Percentage of U.S. Population by Decade, 1850-1990<br>
<a href="immig_4.gif">Chart 4</a>: Origins of Immigrants<br>
<a href="immig_5.gif">Chart 5</a>: Demographic Composition of U.S. in 1995<br>
<a href="immig_6.gif">Chart 6</a>: Immigration Destination by State, 1982-1993<br> 
<a href="immig_7.gif">Chart 7</a>: Apprehensions at the Mexican Border<br>
<a href="immig_8.gif">Chart 8</a>: Illegal Immigrants, 1992
<P>
<a href="chpt11text.html">Additional Text</a><p>
<a name="ISSUES">

<P><b>THE ISSUES</b>
<P>
<P>Immigration has re-emerged as one of the nation's more 
controversial political issues. In 1994, California's Proposition 187, 
designed to deny welfare benefits to illegal immigrants, received 
a resounding 59 percent of the vote, and a special Commission 
on Immigration Reform issued a report supporting a national 
computerized registration system for all workers to help enforce 
laws against the employment of illegal aliens. Legislation to 
strengthen law enforcement against illegal immigration and restrict the 
quota of legal immigrants is being considered in Congress. 
Candidates for public office in 1996 are very likely to be asked to take a 
position on immigration issues.
<P>
<P>One reason for this concern is the widespread impression that 
immigrants who come to America to take advantage of welfare 
contribute to the urban crime rate. Immigration has been 
increasing, and many people worry that recent immigrants are changing 
the face of America ethnically, culturally, and politically. 
Immigration from European countries is much smaller than in earlier 
years, while Hispanic and Asian immigration is much greater.
<P>
<P>Not only is the number of new immigrants under current law at 
an all-time high, but the concentration of these new Americans in 
five 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 2 -->

states -- California, Florida, Illinois, Texas, and New York --  
significantly magnifies their impact on local government 
services, including schools, emergency medical care, and welfare.
<P>
<P>The changing skills of immigrants also raise concerns. The 
proportion of highly skilled immigrants has declined in the past decade 
as the proportion of immigrants sponsored by close family 
members has increased. Refugees from political repression or ethnic 
persecution often arrive in this country without skills or other 
 resources and automatically are placed on welfare.
<P>
<P>Illegal immigration is a particularly sensitive issue for 
many Americans, one that prompts them to worry about the price 
society pays for an &quot;open door&quot; policy. Illegal immigration involves 
not only people who sneak across the U.S. border, but also those 
who come as tourists or students and decide to stay. In 1986, legal 
sanctions were imposed on employers who hire unlawful 
immigrants, but they have been difficult to enforce because identification 
documents are easily forged. Legislation pending in Congress 
would create a national identification card for every 
American,<A HREF="ftnt11.htm#1">1</a> but this worries many who feel that a national identification card would 
be a dangerous intrusion by government.
<P>
<P>Opinions about the merits of America's current immigration 
policy are sharply divided. Those who believe immigrants should be 
welcomed argue that the cultural and economic contributions of 
immigrants are part of America's historical tradition and that the 
economic benefits from more workers and people who start 
businesses and pay taxes far exceed any social 
costs.<A HREF="ftnt11.htm#2">2</a>  Those who think the demographic change is too great, on the other hand, note that 
current levels of immigration will cause Americans from the 
Euro
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 3 -->

pean ethnic groups that dominated this country for most of its 
history to become a minority of the population the middle of the 
21st century.<A HREF="ftnt11.htm#3">3</a>
<P>
<P>But this is not just a political numbers game. It is an intensely 
personal issue for millions of Americans whose close family ties 
or business interests are regulated by the immigration law. 
Reuniting families is a primary goal of U.S. immigration law, and 
businesses in the rapidly growing high technology sectors of the 
U.S. economy, as well as American corporations with a 
multinational workforce, want the freedom to bring foreign-born employees 
and their families into the United States without excessive red tape.
<P>
<P>Most current immigration to the United States cannot be 
justified as bringing some general economic benefit to other Americans, 
but neither can it be attacked as an economic drain. Though 
national statistics do not clearly show any particular economic costs or 
benefits to the country as a whole,<A HREF="ftnt11.htm#4">4</a> the family members and 
employers who sponsor immigrants believe very strongly in the 
economic contributions of the individuals they 
know.<A HREF="ftnt11.htm#5">5</a>
<P>
<P>The abstract question  whether there is too much 
immigration today  tends to dominate the debate (along with the problem 
of illegal immigration). But the issue is hard to resolve. For 
those people directly affected, the concern is whether the 
government will permit a particular, valuable<A HREF="ftnt11.htm#6">6</a> person to live and work in 
the United States. For other Americans, the issues are less 
clear-cut. Candidates must be prepared to help their constituents 
resolve them.
<a name="FACTS"><P>
<P><B>THE FACTS

<P>
<P>Immigrants and Welfare</B>
<P>
<P>The generous welfare benefits provided by most states and 
the federal government are intended to help individuals and families 
in need. Many people take advantage of the this system to avoid 
assuming their family responsibilities and performing work. It 
certainly seems plausible that people from impoverished 
countries would want to come to the United States because of the 
higher standard of living, as well as to assume that many would come 
to be on welfare, since welfare benefits in the United States 
are higher than the incomes of most people in less developed 
countries. But there is no evidence that large numbers of working 
age immigrants come to America to go on the dole. 
<ul><P>
<li><P>The labor force participation rate among male immigrants is 
77 percent -- slightly higher than among native-born Americans 
(74 percent), according to the 1990 census. The highest labor 
force participation rate, 83 percent, is among Hispanic immigrants. 
<P>
<li>The median age for legal immigrants in 1993 was 28, 
slightly younger than the average American's age of 33. More than 80 
percent of immigrants arrive before age 45, and only about 
5 percent arrive after retirement age to join family 
members.<A HREF="ftnt11.htm#7">7</a>
</ul><P>
<P>Newly arrived immigrants, &quot;legal permanent residents,&quot; 
generally are prevented from receiving welfare. They cannot receive 
most direct aid during their first three years<A HREF="ftnt11.htm#8">8</a> in the country 
because their sponsors' income is counted as their own during this 
period in determining eligibility. They also can be deported as a 
public 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 5 -->

charge if they use public benefits during their first five years in 
the country. Elderly immigrants, however, who typically are 
sponsored by their children, are able to take advantage of the 
Supplemental Security Income (SSI) program after five years. 
Their sponsors' financial responsibility ends, and SSI is an 
entitlement for those with a low income after age 65.
<P>
<P>The Immigration Reform Act of 1986, which established 
procedures to legalize immigrants, barred those taking advantage of 
the amnesty from receiving public benefits for five years. After 
that, they can receive welfare. Undocumented aliens are not eligible 
for most public assistance, except for emergency medical 
treatment under Medicaid and nutrition benefits under the Women, 
Infants, and Children (WIC) program. The states were mandated by 
the 1986 immigration law to establish a computerized system, the 
Systematic Alien Verification for Entitlements (SAVE), to screen 
the immigration status of non-citizen applicants for Aid to 
Families with Dependent Children (AFDC) and other federal benefit 
programs.<A HREF="ftnt11.htm#9">9</a>
<P>
<P>A recent study of welfare participation over a whole lifetime 
by immigrant families, based on the years they arrived in the 
United States, shows a trend toward increasing use of welfare among 
immigrants in recent decades.<A HREF="ftnt11.htm#10">10</a>
<P>
<P>
<center><table border=0>
<tr align=center>
<th>Expected Welfare Costs over the Life Cycle for a 
Typical Household<br>
Lifetime Costs (1979 Dollars)</th>
</tr><tr>
<td>Natives</td><td>                         $4,624</td>
</tr><tr>
<td>Immigrants arriving before 1950</td> <td>    $2,683</td></tr>
<tr>
<td>Immigrants arriving 1950-54</td><td>          $4,197</td></tr>
<tr>
<td>1960</td><td>                         $646,312</td></tr>
<tr>
<td>1965</td><td>                         $697,109</td></tr>
<tr>
<td>1970</td><td>                         $747,016</td></tr>
<tr>
<td>1975</td><td>                         $807,925</td></tr>
</table></center>
<P>This trend in lifetime welfare outlays for the foreign born is 
explained by the demographic pattern of recent immigration 
rather than by a growing tendency among immigrants in general, most 
of whom are young men, to go on welfare. More elderly 
immigrants have a higher lifetime dependence on welfare benefits for 
elderly people than the native born because they have fewer resources 
in the form of Social Security, private pensions, and 
accumulated savings. In addition, the number of refugees and political 
asylum seekers coming to the United States has increased since the 
1960s, and this category of immigrants is eligible for welfare 
immediately upon arrival.
<P>
<P>Still, it is important to keep this in proportion:
<P>
<P><B>Elderly Immigrants </B>
<ul><P>
<li><P>Elderly immigrants show up on the welfare rolls in greater 
numbers than younger immigrants, or the native born. But 
immigrants over age 65 who have lived in the U.S. for at least 20 years 
are only slightly more likely to receive welfare than elderly 
natives 

(8.7 percent versus 6.9 percent). 
<P>
<li><P>Most native born recipients receive other retirement income, 
including Social Security, that is not counted as welfare. But 
Supplemental Security Income (SSI) is available when other sources 
of income are small. For most of the elderly immigrants on SSI, 
their monthly check is their only source of 
income.<A HREF="ftnt11.htm#11">11</a> 
<P>
<li><P>In 1982, there were 127,900 non-citizens receiving SSI. In 
1992, this number had increased to 601,000, equal to about 11 percent 
of the total elderly poor. It continues to increase rapidly: By 1994, 
it had climbed to 738,000.<A HREF="ftnt11.htm#12">12</a>  SSI recipients also qualify for 
Medicaid, food stamps, and local welfare services.
<P></ul>
<P>Most non-citizens on SSI have relatives able to support them. 
Support is a condition of sponsorship for immigration, but after 
five years is no longer mandatory. After five years as a legal 
permanent resident, an immigrant can become a naturalized citizen, and 
no restrictions on welfare eligibility apply. Significant changes in 
the federal means-tested welfare standards were included in the 
Balanced Budget Act of 1995.<A HREF="ftnt11.htm#13">13</a>  Welfare benefits for refugees 
and other &quot;qualified aliens&quot; would have ended after five years. 
The income of a sponsor would have been used to calculate 
eligibility for SSI and other means-tested entitlements, without a three- 
or five-year limit. The legislation also would have required all 
non-citizens to reapply for benefits, with the incomes of their 
sponsors to be used in the recalculation of eligibility. But even this 
regulation ends if the elderly immigrant qualifies for citizenship.
<P>
<P><B>Immigrants and Crime
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 8 -->

</B>
<P>
<P>Ethnic communities with a high proportion of immigrants 
typically are located in the inner city, where higher crime rates are 
common. The issue: Do immigrants cause crime, or do they simply tend 
to live in high crime-areas?  The notion that higher immigration 
rates and higher crime rates are causally related cannot be dismissed 
out of hand. In every ethnic group, young males commit most of 
the crime, and immigrants are predominantly young males  
particularly illegal immigrants. In the United States, moreover, 
economic opportunity often depends on education and cultural 
advantages that immigrants from poor countries do not possess. 
<P>
<P>Many Americans assume this makes immigrants more inclined 
to commit crimes. But it is wrong to assume that educational 
disadvantages and other factors mean that immigrants are more likely 
to be involved in crime than native born Americans.
<P>
<ul>
<P><li>For the nation as a whole, the number of non-citizens in prison 
is approximately the same proportion as the number from the 
general population.
<P>
<P><li>Of the five states with the largest proportion of alien prisoners 
in 1992  California, New York, Florida, Illinois, and Texas  
only New York had a greater share of non-citizens in its prisons than 
in the general population.
<P></ul>
<center><table border=0 cellpadding="6">
<tr align=center><th>Survey of State Prison Inmates, 1991
</th></tr>
<tr>
<td></td><td>Non-citizen Prison Inmates</td><td>General Population Rate</td></tr>
<tr>
<td><B>All States </B>
</td>
<td>  4.0%
</td><td>
4.7%
</td></tr><tr>
<td><B>Illinois</B></td>
<td>  1.0%
</td><td>
4.6%
</td></tr>
<tr><td><B>Texas</B>
</td><td>
 4.3%
</td><td>
5.9%</td></tr><tr>
<td><B>Florida  </B> </td>
<td>  7.0%
</td>
<td>7.3%</td></tr><tr>

<td><B>California</B>
</td>
<td>10.4%
</td><td>
14.9%
</td></tr><tr>
<td><B>New York</B>
</td>
<td>12.4%
</td><td>

8.6%
</td></tr><tr align="left">
<td>Source: National Institute of Corrections, 1992.
</td></tr></table></center><P>
<P>
<P>The federal prison system has a much greater proportion of 
non-citizens (not necessarily immigrants) in custody than the state 
prisons, with approximately 25 percent. One reason for this is 
that federal law enforcement tends to concentrate on different kinds 
of crime, such as drug smuggling, in which foreigners on tourist 
or business visas are caught entering and leaving the United 
States. Federal prison statistics tell us nothing about criminality 
among immigrants. Among the non-citizens in federal prison, 80 
percent were convicted for crimes related to the war on drugs, 
including former Panama dictator Manuel Noriega.<A HREF="ftnt11.htm#14">14</a> 
<P>
<P>The ethnic groups represented among non-citizen prisoners 
also have no significant correlation with the size of those 
immigrant groups in the general population. If immigration in general were 
a source of crime, we would expect to find a higher statistical 
correlation between members of specific ethnic groups in the 
prison population and their share of the general population.
<P>
<P><B>The Burden on State and Local Governments</B>
<P>
<P>Immigration policy, including the control of borders to halt 
illegal immigration, is a responsibility of the federal government. 
But state and local governments have to support public schools, 
hospitals, emergency rescue, police and fire departments, and other 
services for immigrant communities -- including many illegals 
who 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 11 -->

live and hide among the much larger legal foreign born 
population. Thus, if the federal government fails to secure America's 
borders, the states pick up the tab for illegals who receive services. 
The federal government clearly has failed to control the Mexican 
border. Moreover, the President and Congress annually set the 
quota for refugees, who are entitled to federal and local welfare 
benefits. The flood of political asylum seekers and foreign visitors 
who overstay their visa periods and melt into the population as 
illegal immigrants is entirely the result of Washington's failure to 
discharge its responsibility.
<P>
<P>Federal law requires state and local governments to provide 
public schooling<A HREF="ftnt11.htm#15">15</a> and emergency medical care for illegal 
immigrants. States have grown increasingly angry in recent years at what 
they see as an unfair financial burden placed on them by a federal 
government that is unwilling to enforce its immigration 
laws. California's Proposition 187 and other measures to deny state 
and local government services to illegal immigrants are prompted 
by the rising cost of services paid for by state 
taxpayers.<A HREF="ftnt11.htm#16">16</a> 
<P>
<P>The governors of the most heavily affected states have 
demanded federal reimbursement of the estimated costs imposed by 
illegal immigration on their state and local governments. In 
Washington, this argument is made in support of legislation to strengthen 
federal immigration controls, particularly at the Mexican border, 
to stop illegal crossing.
<P>
<P>In the Balanced Budget Act of 1995, Congress for the first 
time voted to eliminate one unfunded mandate (for emergency 
medical care, including childbirth, provided to illegal aliens) by 
authorizing a supplemental allotment of federal money to reimburse 
states. 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 12 -->

The Act also explicitly disqualified payments for 
non-emergency medical care for illegal aliens under the Medicaid program. 
To comply with the rules and obtain federal money, medical 
providers would have had to determine the immigration status of 
patients, which they do not now do.<A HREF="ftnt11.htm#17">17</a>  The legislation was vetoed by 
President Clinton.
<P>
<P><B>What is the cost of illegal immigration?</B> Illegal aliens are 
assumed to be a net cost to states. However, while they are 
among the poorest immigrants and pay fewer taxes than legal 
immigrants or the native born, many are employed and do not receive 
services paid for by taxpayers. Thus, figuring the costs that illegal 
immigrants impose on a community, and comparing this with 
benefits to that community from sales tax payments and other 
financial contributions, is no easy task. Illegal immigrants in general 
have more difficulty getting benefits from the welfare system than 
legal residents, and do not identify themselves as illegal if they do. 
As the RAND Corporation has observed, &quot;Congress, state, and 
local policymakers still have no reliable answers to basic 
questions about the costs and benefits of immigration for state and local 
governments, for the economy as a whole, and for the nature 
and speed of integration of new immigrants into U.S. 
society.&quot;<A HREF="ftnt11.htm#18">18</a>
<P>
<P>A review of the econometric studies of the fiscal burden on 
state and local governments from immigration by the RAND 
Corporation found that &quot;there is general agreement that currently 
illegal immigrants contribute less than those who received amnesty, 
who, in turn, contribute less than legal immigrants, who contribute 
less than the native born. However, this finding merely reflects 
differences in the average incomes of these various groups rather 
than their immigration status per se.&quot;<A HREF="ftnt11.htm#19">19</a>
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 13 -->

<P>
<P>In nine different studies<A HREF="ftnt11.htm#20">20</a> examined by the RAND 
Corporation, the available data about the costs of immigration are 
conflicting and inconclusive. &quot;Existing studies of the costs of immigration 
do not provide a reliable or accurate estimate of the net costs and 
benefits of immigration  even wcosts/benefits are defined 
narrowly. Moreover, without reaching consensus on a host of conceptual 
and accounting issues, we doubt that additional studies will shed 
light on these important policy questions.&quot;<A HREF="ftnt11.htm#21">21</a>  This is because they 
use different definitions for immigrants and public assistance, 
and even count tax revenues differently. Estimates of the per 
capita costs of providing federal, state, and local services to 
immigrants ranged from a low of $2,638 to a high of $4,476. The per 
capita revenue estimates varied from $1,051 to $3,644. When the 
costs and benefits were compared in each study, the conclusions were 
as widely apart as a surplus of $1,400 per immigrant to a net cost 
of $1,600.<A HREF="ftnt11.htm#22">22</a>
<P>
<P>RAND's analysis of the six state and local government studies 
of the cost of immigrants found that the methods used to 
calculate costs and benefits tended to include a full list of outlays for 
public services but only a partial list of revenues, including transfer 
payments from higher levels of government. The flawed 
accounting methods showed that neither immigrants nor the native born 
pay their way at the state and local levels. Where estimates were 
made separately for immigrants and the native born, the studies 
found that the &quot;deficit&quot; for immigrants is larger. What the studies 
actually seem to find is only the higher average income, and 
higher taxes paid, by the native born.<A HREF="ftnt11.htm#23">23</a>
<P>
<P>States and local communities with large immigrant 
populations 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 14 -->

probably have a disproportionate concentration among them 
of illegal aliens, who tend to be poorest. Mandates for social 
services and welfare, and lax enforcement by social workers of 
rules against aiding illegal aliens, probably impose a financial burden 
on those state and local governments. Because the federal 
government has failed to prevent the illegal immigration, the argument that 
the federal taxpayer should pay any imposed costs is sensible. But 
the size and nature of the costs of illegal immigration have not 
been clearly established. Moreover, the task of identifying the 
immigration status of almost all poor people in America's ethnic 
communities is one that state and local governments may not want to 
undertake.
<P>
<P><B>Are There Too Many Immigrants?</B>
<P>
<P>Many Americans are concerned that the higher rate of 
immigration to the United States in recent years may be too great for the 
cultural assimilation of so many people. Immigration has been 
increasing, and many commentators are concerned that this is 
changing the culture of America. 
<P>
<P>The assimilation of the foreign born could be a problem if 
their numbers were too great. The question is: Are they too great?
<ul><P>
<li><P>In 1993, more than 904,000 legal immigrants and as many 
as 300,000 illegal immigrants settled permanently in the 
United States. The decade 1981-1990 saw 7.4 million legal 
immigrants, which was almost double the 4.5 million who arrived in 
1971-1980. The decade of greatest immigration to the United States 
was 1901-1910, with 8.8 million new arrivals.

<P>
<li>In every decade between the Civil War and the Depression, 
e than 13 percent of the U.S. population; 
today, they are approximately 8 percent. 
</ul>
<P>The principal concern about legal immigration is that the rate 
is increasing every decade, and the current immigration rate plus 
the birth rate among the groups that are arriving in this country 
is higher than the birth rate for other Americans. 
<P>
<P>During the 1980s, immigration contributed 37.1 percent of 
the growth in the U.S. population. In the 1970s, it contributed 
32.6 percent.<A HREF="ftnt11.htm#24">24</a>  In 1990, immigrant women aged 35 to 44 had 
given birth to an average of 2.2 children, compared with 1.9 
children among native born women in that age group. The fertility 
concern is amplified by the fact that a greater percentage of 
immigrants than of native-born Americans are of reproductive 
age.<A HREF="ftnt11.htm#25">25</a>
<P>
<P>Although the proportion of immigrants in American society 
today is relatively low, and the numbers that come to the United 
States every year are well within historical levels, the demographic 
trend today will produce higher and higher proportions of immigrants 
in the general population. 
<P>
<P>By the year 2050, the proportion of immigrants in the 
general population will rise to approximately the same level as in the 
six decades following the Civil War (over 13 percent). But 
because the population of the United States has increased, and will 
continue to grow, the number of immigrants living in the 
United States by the middle of the next century will be about six 
times greater than in the earlier period.
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 16 -->

<P>
<P>Another important demographic trend that concerns opponents 
of more immigration is the very significant increase in 
immigration from Asia and Latin America.
<P><ul>
<li><P>In 1981-1990, 37.3 percent of immigrants were from Asia, 
22.6 percent were from Mexico, and 18 percent were from other 
Latin American countries. The great wave of immigration to the 
United States after the Civil War was mostly from Europe and 
essentially Caucasian. But a large proportion of the late 19th century 
immigrants were from the very poor regions of southern and 
eastern Europe and were very different culturally from those who 
originally settled the United States.
<P>
<li>The demographic projection of population growth represented 
by immigrants and the children of immigrants shows that by 
the middle of the next century, Asian or Hispanic immigrants and 
their immediate children will account for roughly a quarter of 
the American population.<A HREF="ftnt11.htm#26">26</a>  The population as a whole will 
change from today's proportions of 3 percent Asian, 9 percent 
Hispanic, 11 percent non-Hispanic black, and 77 percent non-Hispanic 
white to approximately 9 percent Asian, 13 percent non-Hispanic 
black, 19 percent Hispanic, and 59 percent non-Hispanic 
white.<A HREF="ftnt11.htm#27">27</a>  These estimates do not account for changes that would result from 
intermarriage among members of these groups.
<P></ul>
<P>The concern that opponents of current immigration policy 
feel about too many immigrants in the next century is exacerbated 
by the tendency of immigrants to move into their own ethnically 
homogeneous communities. More than 90 percent of 
immigrants move into cities and live in highly visible ethnic enclaves. 
The increased visibility of Hispanic and Asian communities 
reinforces 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 17 -->

the issue, just as the ghettos of Irish and Jewish immigrants in 
the last century and black Americans from the rural South after 
World War I aroused concern. The immigrant population is much 
more concentrated in Southern California, Texas, New York, and 
Miami than in the rest of the country. 
<P>
<P> Just 12 metropolitan areas received 55 percent of new 
immigrants in 1993. One in every three new immigrants now settles in 
California. Of these, 3 in 5 choose to live in the Los Angeles 
metropolitan area. Los Angeles is now 40 percent foreign 
born.<A HREF="ftnt11.htm#28">28</a>
<P>
<P>The question is whether the current U.S. trend is 
toward balkanization or a melting pot. Do large concentrations of 
immigrants living in their own communities, near others with 
similar backgrounds and cultural practices, resist Americanization 
and sustain a separate loyalty to a minority group?  It is easier for 
large ethnic community to use a non-English language outside the 
home, and public schools can be forced to offer bilingual education. 
Assimilation into a more uniform American culture would seem 
less likely to occur, but the evidence actually indicates that urban 
concentrations of immigrants, particularly from countries from 
which large numbers have come, are more likely to become 
naturalized citizens.<A HREF="ftnt11.htm#29">29</a>
<P>
<P>For example, in the mid-18th century, Benjamin Franklin 
complained: &quot;Why should Pennsylvania, founded by the English, 
become a colony of <I>aliens</I>, who will shortly be so numerous as 
to Germanize us instead of Anglifying them, and will never adopt 
our Language or Customs any more than they can acquire our 
complexion.&quot;<A HREF="ftnt11.htm#30">30</a>  But he was wrong. In New York and Chicago for 
example, the concentrations of Yiddish-speaking immigrants so 
char
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 18 -->

acteristic in the earlier period have disappeared.
<P>
<P>Opponents of current U.S. immigration policy maintain that 
assimilation of so many from the last great wave of 
immigration, which ended in the 1920s, was possible because (1) almost all 
immigrants came from Europe, and many from 
English-speaking countries; (2) the influx was stopped for a period of time to 
permit the assimilation of the immigrant minorities into the 
dominant American culture; and (3) the birth rate among the native 
born population was significantly higher than it is today. Only 27.8 
percent of the growth in the U.S. population came from 
immigration during the 1901-1910 peak period, compared with 37.1 percent 
in the 1980s.<A HREF="ftnt11.htm#31">31</a>
<P><ul>
<li><P>But the current rate of assimilation is very rapid. Research on 
immigrants to Southern California that looks at the age cohorts 
of recent immigrants has found very rapid increases in English 
language proficiency, naturalization rates, occupational mobility, 
self-employment, and income, in addition to significantly reduced 
poverty rates.<A HREF="ftnt11.htm#32">32</a>
<P>
<li>In Southern California, &quot;all immigrant children showed a 
tremendous rate of increase in English ability, though the trend was 
especially marked among Latinos.&quot;<A HREF="ftnt11.htm#33">33</a>
<P>
<li>By looking at age cohorts of Latino immigrants who arrived 
in California in the 1970s, demographers can see that poverty 
actually declined from 25.7 percent to 15.7 percent as the 
15-to-25-year-old arrivals matured and became 
assimilated.<A HREF="ftnt11.htm#34">34</a>
</ul><P>
<P><b>Should population patterns be changed?</b> Author Peter Brimelow, 
in 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 19 -->

his recent book<I> Alien Nation</I>, points out that the 1965 
immigration law, which opened the doors to higher rates of immigration 
from Asia and Latin America, was passed by Congress with the 
understanding that it would <I>not</I> change America's historical 
population patterns.<A HREF="ftnt11.htm#35">35</a>  Since the law has caused such a demographic 
change, however, particularly as the 1986 amnesty for illegal aliens 
has further shifted the family reunification preferences in favor of 
very recent immigrants from Asia and Latin America, he argues that 
the pattern of immigration must be corrected.
<P>
<P>This raises both political and non-political questions about 
what immigration policy the United States should adopt. From a 
political standpoint: 
<ul><P>
<li>The American people as a whole do not get to choose the 
nation's future demographic profile. But on their behalf, Congress does 
set immigration quotas, and these can be written to discriminate 
either for or against people. 
<P>
<li>The federal government has a constitutional responsibility to 
control the national borders, and the requirement that foreigners 
entering the country must have a visa and submit to customs 
inspection is important in maintaining that control. 
<P>
<li>The federal government sets requirements on individuals 
wishing to live permanently in the United States: extensive 
documentation of good character, sponsorship for immigration, and financial 
responsibility. Additional requirements involving financial 
responsibility, English language proficiency, or ethnicity could be 
added by Congress. 

<P>
<li>Both the size of immigration quotas and the categories of 
people who qualify were set in the 1990 Immigration Act and may 
be amended in 1996. But determining whether to increase or 
decrease immigration quotas will have a very small effect on the 
long-term demographic profile of the country.
</ul>
<P>The non-political considerations of immigration policy affect 
the nation's demographic patterns. Within the quota system, 
individual families and employers control the decisions over who 
can immigrate to America by virtue of their power to sponsor 
those individuals. Particular families or employers generally choose 
to sponsor immigrants for very personal or economic reasons, 
and there often is a long waiting period before an immigration visa 
is granted. The question is whether this choice should remain 
essentially personal or should be regarded as a significant public 
interest that requires more political control.
<P>
<P><B>The Immigration Law</B>
<P>
<P>The Immigration and Nationality Act establishes the rules 
and quotas for immigration to the United States.<A HREF="ftnt11.htm#36">36</a>  The visas issued 
to immigrants allow them to become permanent residents. The 
law provides that after five years, and after fulfilling a requirement 
to show some knowledge of American history, permanent 
residents may become naturalized citizens of the United States. Prior 
to 1965, specific quotas favoring predominantly European 
countries were enforced. In 1965, Congress repealed this system of 
quotas and established a worldwide quota for immigration, with a 
limit per country. This major change in U.S. immigration law put 
the priority on family unification  individual Americans 
sponsoring relatives to come here.<A HREF="ftnt11.htm#37">37</a>  The law fundamentally changed the 
em
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 21 -->

phasis from specific nationalities and opened the process 
much more widely to immigrants from Asia. Spouses and most 
children of American citizens are exempt from the quota system, 
while other relatives are given priority over foreigners with no 
American relatives.
<P>
<P>The quota system, with its &quot;preference categories,&quot; is an 
extremely complex area of immigration law. Combined with the limits 
on immigration from individual countries, the preference system 
requires some immigrants to wait many years after applying for 
U.S. permission before receiving it. Immigrants from other 
countries, however, are not subjected to such prolonged delays. The 
quota preference system also includes categories for occupations 
and skills, but these have much smaller quotas and are ranked lower 
in the preference categories.
<P>
<P>The quota system and its preferences were revised by the 
1990 immigration law, but the family unification priority was 
not changed. Current law provides for up to 675,000 immigrants 
annually. Of these, 480,000 (71 percent) are sponsored by relatives 
in the United States, and another 140,000 (21 percent) are 
&quot;economic&quot; immigrants whose acceptance is determined on the 
basis of skills, education, or willingness to invest and create jobs. A 
special preference category was created for &quot;diversity&quot; 
immigration, allowing 55,000, or 8 percent of the total, from countries 
where immigration was lowest in prior years. This provision is 
intended to ease immigration from Ireland and other European countries.
<P>
<P><b>Refugees.</b> The Refugee Act of 1980<A HREF="ftnt11.htm#38">38</a> provides general 
authority for the admission of refugees, who were removed as a 
category under the quota preference system. The number that will come 
to 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 22 -->

the United States annually is determined by the President in 
consultation with Congress, and there are procedures for 
admitting larger numbers in emergency situations, such as the Haitian 
and Cuban boatlifts. In 1993, 119,482 refugees were admitted.
<P>
<P>Political asylum is granted on a case-by-case basis to aliens 
who meet the definition of refugee but already are in the United 
States or at the border. The requirement for case-by-case 
determinations is a significant administrative burden for the Immigration 
and Naturalization Service (INS). In 1993, there were 150,386 
applications for asylum, and the backlog of cases had reached 
333,000. While waiting for the INS to schedule a hearing for political 
asylum, these individuals generally are allowed free movement 
within the country, and a large number disappear and become 
illegal aliens.
<P>
<P><b>Illegal Immigrants.</b> The Immigration Reform and Control Act 
of 1986 (IRCA)<A HREF="ftnt11.htm#39">39</a> was enacted to control illegal immigration. 
The intent of the law was to focus on the motives of illegal 
immigrants, who come to the United States and get jobs that offer better 
wages and working conditions than they can find in their native 
lands. The principal change in the law prohibiting employment of 
illegal immigrants, however, was to make the employer guilty of 
breaking the immigration law as well. To cut off the job 
opportunities being sought by illegal immigrants, employers were made 
responsible for enforcement. All job applicants must prove their 
citizenship or legal residence to their potential employers by 
completing an INS form (I-9) before they can begin work. The employer 
must verify this information and keep the documents with other 
personnel records. IRCA imposed both civil fines as high as $10,000 
on employers who hire illegal aliens and criminal penalties for a 
re
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 23 -->

peated pattern of violations.
<P>
<P>Because it was known that millions of illegal aliens already 
were living and working in this country, the Congress established 
procedures by which they could apply for legal resident status. By 
1988, more than 3 million people had applied for &quot;legalization&quot; 
under the 1986 law. These legalized immigrants in turn have provided 
a newly enlarged pool of families that are seeking to sponsor 
other relatives for immigration.
<P>
<P><b>Citizenship.</b> A legal permanent resident in the United States 
may apply for citizenship after five years. The Immigration and 
Nationality Act sets out a number of specific requirements for 
becoming a naturalized citizen: a test of the applicant's knowledge of 
U.S. history and the Constitution, proficiency in the English 
language, and an oath renouncing all allegiance to foreign governments 
and swearing loyalty to the United States and a willingness to 
defend it. Congress also could enact additional financial 
responsibility requirements.
<P>
<P><B>The Problem of Illegal Immigration</B>
<P>
<P>There were an estimated 3.2 million illegal aliens in the 
United States as of October 1992, according to the 
INS.<A HREF="ftnt11.htm#40">40</a>  The number of illegal residents is estimated to be growing by 300,000 per year.

<P>
<ul>
<li>Fifty-five percent of the illegal immigrants in the United States 

are estimated to be Mexican. Another 22 percent come from 
Central America. 
<P>
<li>Although Mexicans comprise about 90 percent of those 
apprehended at the southern U.S. border, one survey found they 
were joined by representatives of 70 other 
nationalities.<A HREF="ftnt11.htm#41">41</a>
</ul><P>In addition to crossing the border illegally, many violators of 
the law just stay in the United States after their non-immigrant 
visas expire. 
<P><UL>
<p><li>In 1993, there were 21 million visas issued to 
non-immigrants, including 17 million tourists and almost 3 million business 
visitors; 165,000 temporary foreign workers and 257,000 foreign 
students also were admitted. In addition, foreign journalists, 
foreign government officials, and the families of persons working for 
international organizations come to the United States freely. 
<P>
<li>During the 1986 fiscal year, the INS apprehended 1.8 million 
illegal entrants. Of these, 243,000 had overstayed their 
visas.<A HREF="ftnt11.htm#42">42</a> 
</UL><P>
<P>These statistics do not provide a good picture of the extent of 
the problem, however, because most illegal immigrants who enter 
the United States with a valid tourist or student visa are not 
identified unless stopped by the police for some reason.
<P>
<P>Illegal immigration is a serious problem that law enforcement 
has not been able to control. The shortage of border patrol officers 
and adequate physical barriers along the U.S.-Mexico border has 
been widely cited as a large factor in the problem, and improved 
enforcement at key locations in California, Texas, Arizona, and 
New Mexico certainly should be undertaken to curb illegal 
crossings. But the larger problem would not be solved by those 
measures alone, because illegal entry is only one source of illegal 
immigration. The problem of individuals misusing tourist visas also 
must be addressed. 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 25 -->

<P>
<P><B>Identification Cards</B>
<P>
<P>Employer sanctions under IRCA have failed to reduce illegal 
immigration and may have increased racial or ethnic 
discrimination in the workplace.<A HREF="ftnt11.htm#43">43</a>  Employers who suspect a job applicant 
may not possess legitimate credentials for legal residence or 
citizenship face a difficult problem. In an effort to solve this problem, 
legislation now before Congress would set up a pilot program 
covering approximately 47 million workers, or almost 40 percent of 
the workforce, to test a computerized national worker 
identification system.<A HREF="ftnt11.htm#44">44</a>  In theory, if an employer needed to verify the right of 
a job applicant to work, he could make a telephone call and obtain 
a verification number, just as businesses now do to verify 
credit cards and checks. This would be the employer's defense 
against any subsequent discovery that the new employee was in fact 
an illegal alien.
<P>
<P>Unfortunately, this idea is both impractical and potentially 
dangerous. It would solve a problem caused by less than 1.5 percent 
of the population that is here illegally by dramatically increasing 
government regulation of every American's life. Even the pilot 
program would require over 100 million names and numbers, 
since non-working spouses and children potentially are part of the 
labor force. What ought to be a private contractual arrangement 
between employers and job applicants would become an illegal 
relationship unless the employer first obtained government authorization. 
The danger that such a system would create an underground 
economy with crime and tax evasion is overwhelming. If the 
authorization were denied, for whatever reason  computer data errors, 
bureaucratic mistakes, or even sabotage by a criminal computer hacker 
 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 26 -->

the job applicant would be forcibly unemployed. As the 
logical implications of this system of legal sanctions against 
employers become clearer and more threatening to the civil rights of 
ordinary people, public opposition is likely to increase.
<P>
<P>Most advocates of a computer registry admit that it would 
work only with a secure national identification card. Without such 
positive identification, an employer would have no way to 
determine whether the Social Security number being used actually 
belonged to the job applicant. Senator Alan Simpson (R-WY), sponsor 
of the immigration reform legislation pending in the Senate, has 
described the two functions the worker identification system 
would have: &quot;It must verify that a name corresponds to someone who 
is authorized to work. And then verifying the identity, that the 
person claiming the name and the number is not an impostor. The use of 
a biometric identifier, such as a fingerprint, is needed if this 
function is to perform reliably.&quot;<A HREF="ftnt11.htm#45">45</a>
<P>
<P>Before a national computer system to identify every 
American could be installed, there would have to be significant 
improvement in the data stored in the federal government's computers. 
With approximately 6.5 million Americans changing jobs every year, 
an error rate of just one percent would cause 650,000 innocent 
victims to be denied a job until bureaucrats in Washington could 
be persuaded to correct their mistakes. The Social Security 
Administration has estimated that a national computer registry would 
cost between $3 billion and $6 billion  about 10 to 20 times more 
than its advocates have claimed.<A HREF="ftnt11.htm#46">46</a>
<P>
<P>The proposal for a national computerized worker registration 
system does not address the basic problem of illegal alien 
employ
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 27 -->

ment. Since employers are required to verify the right of job 
applicants to work in the United States today, violations of the law 
may occur because some employers simply ignore it. Advocates of 
the plan are enthusiastic about increasing the number of work site 
inspections for labor law and OSHA violations, along with 
the worker verification. The proposed computer system is an 
expensive, new invasion of every American worker's privacy and 
a threat to law-abiding employers who would have to deal with 
federal inspectors. Employers who violate the law today could 
continue to do so simply by going further underground and 
evading the new computer system.
<P>
<P>Employer sanctions is a misguided concept. The assumption is 
that because an illegal immigrant has broken the law, any 
employer who provides a job is a criminal accomplice. But employers 
are more likely to be the victims of document fraud. A solution to 
the criminal problem of illegal immigration ought to involve less 
government regulation of business, not more. Criminal 
penalties should focus on deterring illegal immigration by punishing 
the criminal, not the rest of the nation.
<a name="RECORD"><P>
<P><B>THE RECORD</B>
<P>
<P>THE CLINTON ADMINISTRATION
<P>
<P>The Clinton Administration has emphasized toughening the 
sanctions on employers who hire illegal aliens and increasing the 
number of inspections by the U.S. Department of 
Labor.<A HREF="ftnt11.htm#47">47</a>  In addition, INS funding and personnel increased significantly in FY 1995 
and FY 1996: Increases of 26 percent in budget (to $2.6 billion) 
and 3,200 new full-time employees (to approximately 25,000) 
are 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 28 -->

scheduled. This will include an increase of 1,000 Border 
Patrol agents &quot;on the front lines.&quot;  The budget for FY 1995 was 
increased by 25 percent over the prior year, mostly to finance 
improvements in the agency's computer technology. The INS will spend 
more this year on detention and removal of deportable aliens, 
including people who have been denied political asylum. A detention 
facility operated jointly with the U.S. Marshal Service is being built 
in Batavia, N.Y., and a &quot;triple fencing pilot project&quot; is being 
placed on the border south of San Diego.<A HREF="ftnt11.htm#48">48</a>
<P>
<P>The U.S. Commission on Immigration Reform<A HREF="ftnt11.htm#49">49</a> released its 
interim report to Congress, which addressed illegal immigration, 
in 1994, and a report on legal immigration in 1995. A final 
report covering issues related to immigration will appear in 1997. In 
general, the Commission has supported increased personnel 
and spending to enforce immigration laws at U.S. land borders 
and ports of entry.
<P>
<P>The Commission recommended &quot;development and 
implementation of a simpler, more fraud-resistant system for verifying work 
authorization.&quot;  It endorsed &quot;a computerized registry using data 
provided by the Social Security Administration (SSA) and the INS.&quot; 
 It also called for federal regulation of birth certificates and 
other documents issued by states that establish nationality, as well 
as increased penalties for fraud.
<P>
<P>The Commission supported &quot;in principle&quot; the authorization of 
impact aid to offset the fiscal burdens of unlawful immigration, but 
it wanted further investigation to determine the real costs 
imposed on state and local governments by being required to educate 
illegal immigrant children and provide emergency medical assistance.
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 29 -->

<P>
<P>The Commission's report on legal immigration generally 
supported changing the family visa priorities and eliminating them 
for adult children and siblings of American citizens. It proposed 
a change in the classifications of labor skills, the elimination of 
Department of Labor certifications, and the establishment of a 
&quot;labor market test&quot; for workers with college degrees. Employers 
would pay a fee to bring in skilled workers, and the money would be 
used for private-sector education and training of American workers.
<P>
<P><B>THE 104TH CONGRESS</B>
<P>
<P>During the 104th Congress, legislation to crack down on 
illegal immigration and further restrict legal immigration moved 
through committees in both the Senate and House of Representatives. 
At the end of the first session, nothing had been sent to the 
White House. The bills include:
<ul><P>
<li><b>S. 269</b>, the Immigrant Control and Financial Responsibility Act 
of 1995, sponsored by Senator Alan Simpson (R-WY).
<P>
<li><b>S. 1394</b>, the Immigration Reform Act of 1995, sponsored by 
Senator Simpson.
<P>
<li><b>S. 1535</b>, the Illegal Immigration Control and Enforcement 
Act, sponsored by Senator Spencer Abraham (R-MI).
<P>
<li><b>H.R. 2202</b>, the Immigration in the National Interest Act, 
sponsored by Representative Lamar Smith (R-TX).
<P>
<li><b>H.R. 2898</b>, the One Strike and You're Out Illegal 
Immigration 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 30 -->

Act, sponsored by Representative Randy Tate (R-WA).
</ul><P>
<P>Although illegal immigration and the legal immigration quota 
system are distinct issues, they have been combined. There is 
widespread agreement on many of the reforms proposed to control 
illegal immigration, but strong differences about the proposals to 
reduce legal immigration quotas.
<P>
<P>Both the House and Senate bills increase border enforcement 
patrols and authorize expedited hearings for deportation and 
tougher penalties for document fraud. The legislation begins 
implementation of the national computer identification system to enforce 
employer sanctions. Enforcement powers and penalties are 
increased for smuggling of aliens, as are punishment for repeated 
offenses, detention of illegal immigrants pending removal, and 
criminal penalties for failure to depart.
<P>
<P>Both the House and Senate bills contain new restrictions on 
the receipt of public benefits by illegal immigrants and impose 
new requirements for income support on the sponsors of legal 
immigrants. Sponsors will have to demonstrate greater financial 
ability in order to assure that immigrants are less likely to end up on 
welfare. Both the House and Senate bills reduce the number of 
legal immigrants and eliminate whole categories, such as adult 
children, brothers, and sisters. Immigration of parents of U.S. citizens 
would be restricted, and increased financial support requirements 
would be imposed.
<P>
<P>Legislation also has been introduced to make English the 
official language of the federal government. Proficiency in 
understanding simple English is already a requirement for naturalization as a 
U.S. 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 31 -->

citizen, except for elderly, long-time residents. There is a 
growing concern that the United States in danger of becoming a 
multilingual society, with all the social tensions and political problems 
that have occurred in some other officially multilingual nations. 
Bills include:
<P><ul>
<li><b>S. 356</b>, the Language of Government Act, sponsored by 
Senator Richard Shelby (R-AL).
<P>
<li><b>H.R. 739</b>, sponsored by Representative Toby Roth (R-WI), 
and H.R. 1005, sponsored by Representative Peter King 
(R-NY), which provide for English to be the official language of the 
U.S. government and require the INS to apply more strictly the 
English proficiency requirement for naturalization. These bills also 
repeal the Bilingual Education Act. No hearings have been held in 
the House of Representatives.
<P>
</ul>
<P><B>WHAT TO DO IN 1997</B>
<ul>
<P><li><b>Separate the specific issue of illegal immigration control from 
the more general issue of immigration quota reform.</b> 
<P>
<P>The legislation pending in Congress should be divided into 
separate bills dealing with each side of the question separately.
<P>
<li><b>Strengthen enforcement measures at the Mexican border and 
other entry points.</b>
<P>
More personnel, physical barriers, and detention facilities 
are needed, as is added enforcement authority to deter the 
smuggling and document fraud involved in illegal immigration. The 
INS 

should increase the scrutiny of applicants for political asylum 
and decide their cases more rapidly. Political asylees should be 
denied work permits until determined to be eligible for legal 
permanent residence. The political debate about immigration policy in 
the United States is inflamed primarily because of the highly 
publicized, inadequate enforcement along the Mexican border. But 
increased border enforcement may only shift the problem to 
other ports of entry. The equally serious problem of illegal 
immigration by aliens who arrive legally as tourists or on business and 
then decide to stay also has to be met with severe penalties. Other 
ports of entry also are heavily burdened by the abuse of political 
asylum by immigrants who have been advised on how to exploit it.
<P>
<li><B>Make illegal immigration a felony. </B>
<P>
<P>There should be brief but mandatory incarceration for the first 
offense after a deportation order has been granted. In addition, 
anyone convicted of illegal immigration should be denied all 
future admission to the United States after deportation, even as a 
tourist or on business. Illegal immigration to the United States is 
attempted because violators see the costs as low and the rewards 
as very attractive.
<P>
<li><B>Repeal employer sanctions. </B>
<P>
<P>Employers should not have to verify the citizenship or 
immigration status of a prospective employee. Instead, criminal 
penalties and deportation, along with an absolute prohibition against 
ever returning to the United States, should be imposed on those 
who break the U.S. immigration laws. The expensive and 
unworkable computer verification system that eventually would require 
all 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 33 -->

Americans to carry a national identification card and 
surrender personal privacy should not be started. The enforcement of 
laws against illegal immigration should focus on the law breakers, 
not on the entire American population and millions of innocent 
employers.
<P>
<P>The legitimate concern expressed by many business leaders 
that restrictions on legal immigration will seriously impair their 
ability to hire the people they want and maintain a worldwide labor 
force should be addressed with a uniform system of financial 
reassurance, which also could be used by immigrants who might come 
to the United States to establish new businesses or who seek 
employment without first obtaining a U.S. sponsor. The United 
States does not benefit from numerical quotas for the admission of 
immigrants who would come with the financial assets or skills that 
help guarantee their positive contributions to the national economy, 
to the tax base, and to the middle and upper strata of American 
society. 
<P>
<li><B>Place tough and real financial requirements on 
immigrants and their sponsors to reduce immigrant &quot;gaming&quot; of 
welfare, including a financial bond as security.</B>
<P>
<P>Sponsors of immigrants should be required to demonstrate 
sufficient financial ability to prevent any risk of welfare dependency 
by those who come to the United States. Sponsors' income or 
financial support should be deemed to apply to immigrants' 
income status for the entire term of their legal permanent residence in 
the United States. Posting a bond or purchasing other kinds of 
financial assurance to demonstrate that immigrants will not 
become dependent on welfare, particularly SSI and Medicaid, should 
be 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 34 -->

made a formal part of the visa approval process. Applicants 
for naturalized citizenship should be required to demonstrate by 
the same means that they will not become dependent on welfare, 
particularly SSI and Medicaid, in future years.
<P>
<P>The Supplemental Security Income (SSI) program is 
expanding rapidly, and elderly immigrants are a growing proportion of 
the total welfare burden. U.S. immigration policy always has 
included the provision that no one, including the immigrant parents of 
U.S. citizens should be allowed to become a public charge. The 
obligation of a sponsor to guarantee that an immigrant does not become 
a burden to other American taxpayers should be enforced for as 
long as the immigrant is not an American citizen. The opportunity 
to become an American citizen is a privilege extended to the 
legal permanent resident, but it requires the applicant to undertake 
a significant number of duties and obligations. One of these 
obligations should be to prove financial responsibility. A bond or 
insurance policy or other financial indemnity could eliminate the 
attraction of welfare programs to those who might think about 
immigrating to exploit them; it also could recover part of the costs of 
publicly provided welfare and medical benefits if genuine 
misfortune should befall the new citizen or his family.
<P>
<P>Within the framework set by Congress, the Immigration and 
Naturalization Service should be authorized to issue immigration 
visas to any person who meets stringent criteria of good character and 
is able to post a substantial bond or provide other financial 
assurance, subject to forfeiture if any welfare dependency should 
occur. Such a bond or other financial assurance could be remitted if 
the immigrant chose to depart permanently from the United States.
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 35 -->

<P>
<li><B>Require proficiency in the English language for all 
immigrants and naturalized citizens. </B>
<P>
<P>The standard for naturalized citizens should be raised to fluency 
in English. Immigrants who are not initially proficient in the 
language should be required to practice and study English, and 
their progress should be tested periodically.
<P>
<P>The concept of American nationality is inextricably linked 
with English as the national language. Every other nation in the world 
is identified with its language, and immigration, to say nothing 
of citizenship, often is simply prohibited to outsiders. 
Americans founded a unique republican form of government in the 18th 
century, based on ideal principles of human rights and limited 
government, and invited immigrants to come and join the new civil 
society. But in 200 years, America has become more than simply 
a republic. It has become a people, and English is its language. 
This in no way precludes the right of Americans to converse in 
another language; nor should it discourage the media from providing 
services in another language. But in the courts, the public 
schools, and the political system, the language should be English. 
Becoming proficient in the language of America is a price that any 
immigrant should want to pay.
</ul><P><a name="Q&A">
<P><B>Q&amp;A</B>
<P>
<P><b>Q. What is the difference between legal and illegal 
immigration, and how big a problem is the whole immigration issue?
<P>
<P>A.</b> Legal immigration is a big part of the American tradition, 
and even though there is almost as much legal immigration now 
as 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 36 -->

there was around the turn of the century, it is only a problem if 
you think there are too many new, legal immigrants. Most legal 
immigrants are family members of American families who want 
to sponsor them and bring them here. Family re-unification is a 
good thing. 
<P>
<P>Illegal immigration is a crime, and we must increase the 
penalties for committing this crime. No other remedy will work.
<P>
<P>People who come into the United States across the Mexican 
or Canadian border, or who come here as students or tourists and 
stay after their visas expire, are criminals. They should be 
tracked down, arrested, and put in jail for at least a year -- then 
deported. They should be forbidden ever to come back to the United 
States, even as tourists or businessmen. 
<P>
<P><b>Q. With generous welfare benefits in this country and 
poverty throughout the rest of the world, don't immigrants come 
to America primarily to go on the dole?
<P>
<P>A.</b> No. Statistics show that working-age immigrants actually 
use welfare benefits and food stamps less than native born 
Americans of working age. The real problem is the immigrant parents of 
U.S. citizens, who get Supplemental Security Income (SSI) if they 
are poor. The laws need to be changed so that if they are sponsored 
to come here by their children, who are U.S. citizens, their 
children will be financially responsible. We have to change the SSI law, 
not the immigration law, to do that.
<P>
<P><b>Q. If legal immigrants to the United States are prevented from 
getting welfare, will they not just take jobs away from native 
born 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 37 -->

Americans?
<P>
<P>A.</b> The only immigrant welfare problem is caused by 
elderly people who, after their children bring them to America, then go 
on Supplemental Security Income (SSI) if they are poor. Their 
children should support them, but they are not going to take any 
jobs away from anyone, because they are already retired.
<P>
<P>Working-age immigrants on average are harder working than 
native born Americans and tend to have a higher labor force 
participation rate than native born Americans.
<P>
<P>Immigrants don't take jobs away from American workers.  In 
addition to the dramatic increase in immigration we have seen in 
the past ten years, we have seen a tremendous increase in new 
jobs and a falling rate of unemployment.
<P>
<P>Everybody who gets a job or keeps a job does so as an 
individual, not as a member of some group. Employers hire individuals 
who can do the work. If an immigrant gets a job, it is because the 
employer has specific job needs that the immigrant is qualified to fill.
<P>
<P><b>Q. Would more Border Patrol officers and security fences 
across the Mexican border solve the problem of illegal immigration?
<P>
<P>A.</b> More Border Patrol officers and security fences are needed, 
and Congress is providing more money to do those things. But 
more than half of the illegal immigration problem comes from 
students and tourist visitors to the United States who simply decide to 
stay after their visas expire, and from people who falsely claim 
political asylum. Border patrols and fences won't keep them out.
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 38 -->

<P>
<P>The only way to stop illegal immigration is to impose stiffer 
criminal penalties on those who break our immigration laws. We 
need to put them in jail for at least a year after we catch them, and 
deport them after that. And we need to make sure they will 
never again even be able to visit the United States as a tourist or a 
businessman. The word will get out to those violators, and they 
will stop treating the violation of U.S. immigration laws like a game.
<P>
<P><b>Q. Would a national identification card, reinforced with a 
government computer system to verify identification, solve the 
problem of illegal immigration?
<P>
<P>A.</b> A national identification card, with a Big Brother 
computer system in Washington, D.C., would not stop illegal immigrants 
or even stop some employers from hiring them. What it would do 
is deprive all other Americans of some degree of privacy and create 
a monster information database that eventually could be used to 
violate our liberties.
<P>
<P>The law today makes it a crime for employers to hire illegal 
immigrants, but employers are victims, not criminals. We 
shouldn't create a system that punishes the victims and every other 
innocent American worker. Advocates of the giant computer system 
really are trying to increase government regulations on employers 
and create a justification for an army of Labor Department 
inspectors to invade every workplace in America.
<P>
<P><b>Q. How much should the federal government pay to states that 
are forced to carry the costs of illegal immigration?
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 39 -->

<P>
<P>A.</b> The federal government should be prepared to pay the 
entire costs of illegal immigration. Enforcing the immigration laws is 
a federal responsibility. If the federal government cannot do its 
job, it should pay the costs. The Balanced Budget Act Congress 
passed last year set up a way to pay the states for emergency 
medical treatment for illegal aliens.
<P>
<P>At the same time, the states should have to demonstrate the 
actual costs of illegal immigration. There have been a number of 
so-called studies of the costs of immigration, but none of them 
really proves that there is a significant cost or measures how great it 
may be. We need to get the real data and figure out how much the 
costs are; then the federal government should pay for the problem.
<P>
<P>But the most important things the federal government can do 
to stop illegal immigration are to hire more Border Patrol officers 
and stiffen the criminal penalties for breaking our immigration laws.
<P>
<P><b>Q. Should English be established officially as America's 
language and immigrants be required to read, write, and speak English?
<P>
<P>A.</b> Yes. Proficiency in the English language should be required 
of all immigrants and naturalized citizens. The standard for 
naturalized citizens should be raised to fluency in English. 
Immigrants not initially proficient in the language should be required to 
practice and study English, and their progress should be tested 
periodically.
<P>
<P>English as the national language is central to the concept 
of American nationality. Every other nation in the world is 
closely identified with its language. English is America's language.
<p>
<a name="EXP"><b>EXPERTS</b></a><p>

