<HEAD>
<TITLE>Congressional and Executive Branch Reform -- Issues '96 -- Heritage</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<center>
<h2>Issues '96: The Candidate's Briefing Book</h2>
<b><A HREF="/heritage">The Heritage Foundation</a></b>
</center><p>
<h3>Chapter 12</h3>
<center><h2> CONGRESSIONAL AND EXECUTIVE BRANCH REFORM
</H2></CENTER>
<P>

<CENTER><B><CITE>by Charles P. Griffin</CITE></B><sup><A
HREF="ftnt12.htm#1">1</A></sup>
<P><A HREF="chpt12.html#ISSUES">The Issues</A> | <A HREF="chpt12.html#FACTS">The Facts</A> |  <A HREF="chpt12.html#RECORD">The Record</A> | <A HREF="chpt12.html#Q&A">Q&amp;A</A> | <a href="chpt12.html#EXP">Experts</a>
<p></CENTER>
<a href="congr_1.gif">Chart 1</a>: 1994 Campaign Spending by House Challengers<br>
<p><a href="chpt12text.html">Additional Text</a><p>
<P><B><A NAME="ISSUES">THE ISSUES
</A></B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The 104th Congress has taken dramatic first steps to reform  itself. But
although the new majority  particularly the newly  elected freshmen  has made
great strides in achieving the  meaningful reform that the voters demanded
through the 1994  congressional election, much remains to be done. Congress now
must  complete the task of reforming its own operations and extend the process 
of reform to the executive branch.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Among its reform accomplishments, the 104th Congress:
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>*     Amended</B> its rules to make them fairer and open;
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*     Applied</B> the laws imposed on the private sector to itself;
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*      Cut</B> its budget and staff; 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*     Reduced</B> franking (free mail) and perks;
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*     Held</B> its first-ever vote on term limits and applied limits to 
committee chairmen;
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*     Curbed</B> pension excesses;
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 2 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*     Began</B> to address the issue of welfare for lobbyists;
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*     Repealed</B> the Ramspeck Act, a special law that favored  former
congressional staff in hiring for  career government jobs;
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*     Ordered</B> the first-ever comprehensive audit of the House of 
Representatives; and
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*     Reformed</B> the committee structure in the House of 
Representatives.
</P>
<P>
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>Building on this solid foundation, several problems still need to  be
addressed in the 105th Congress:
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>-     Term limits;
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>-     Welfare for lobbyists;
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>-     Incumbent advantages;
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>-     Budget process reform ;
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>-     Campaign finance reform;
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>-     Congressional perks and privileges;
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>-     The need for a comprehensive Senate audit; and
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 3 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>-     Senate committee reform.
</P>
<P>
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>Congress and the President must work together to reform the  executive
branch by:
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>*     Establishing</B> pay for performance as a principle
of  compensation for federal managers and staff; 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*     Reviewing</B> federal personnel rules to enhance managerial 
flexibility and accountability for performance while streamlining the  federal
process for appeals and grievances; 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*     Modernizing</B> federal benefits, allowing cafeteria plans, 
defined contribution retirement options for new employees, and  medical savings
accounts for federal employees; and 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*     Clearly</B> defining federal agency missions, eliminating 
duplication, privatizing government functions, and devolving certain  federal
functions to the states and local communities wherever  appropriate.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>Congress and the President must work together to complete  these reforms
both to demonstrate their commitment to the  American people and to make
government more accountable to the  voters and less focused on protecting
special interests and the careers  of politicians.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><A NAME="FACTS">THE FACTS</A></B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The 104th Congress made great strides in the effort to clean  up Washington,
enacting substantial reforms in its own processes  that changed the &quot;business-as-usual&quot;
mentality which frustrated  re
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 4 -->  sponsible government before the
1994 elections. But full  reform obviously takes time. The fact is that the new
Congress inherited  a federal government beset with fundamental problems in all 
three branches  executive, legislative, and judicial.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>To complete the reforms begun in 1995, therefore, Congress  and the
President must confront a series of problems, some old and some new.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*      The Supreme Court ruled state-imposed term limits 
unconstitutional.</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>In a 5-4 decision on May 22, 1995,<A HREF="ftnt12.htm#2">2</A>
the U.S. Supreme Court  held that states may not impose term limits on their own
Members  of Congress. At the same time, the Court indicated that Congress 
itself may not  by statute  impose term limits. The impact of  this decision was
to invalidate 23 existing term limits laws and  give greater force to the idea
of a constitutional amendment. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The best way to ensure that members of the House and Senate  stay in touch
with their constituents and truly represent their views is  to prevent
politicians from spending their entire careers in  Washington. If they knew that
Congress could not be a career,  legislators would be less interested in the
trappings of office and less  inclined to feather their own nests, mislead the
voters, legislate  irresponsibly, and abuse their offices as part of their
reelection efforts.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>There are at least four key arguments for a constitutional  amendment to
limit congressional terms:
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>1. Term limits are popular.</B> Support for limiting 
congressional 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 5 -->  terms reaches as high as 80
percent in some polls. The Gallup  poll shows that a 49 percent plurality of
Americans favored term  limits for Congress in 1964, with support swelling to 64
percent in  1990 and 73 percent in 1994.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>2. Term limits receive substantial support at the polls.</B> In 
addition to the fact that term limits were one of the most popular  components
of the Contract With America, voters have supported  them overwhelmingly when
faced with ballot initiatives. In the 22  states with term limits by referendum,
the average level of support in  the voting booth on election day was 66
percent.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>3. Term limits are a fundamentally democratic concept.</B> Since  as far
back as Aristotle, the concept of limiting the tenure of  politicians has been a
topic of public debate. One of America's  own Founding Fathers, James Madison,
argued 200 years ago that  term limits would reduce the influence of special
interests.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>4. Term limits ensure healthy change.</B> Increasing the turnover  in
Congress gives more citizens the opportunity to serve their  government and
their fellow Americans. The introduction of fresh  insights into the political
process increases the chances that  dramatic improvements in the role of
government can be effected.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>23 STATES HAVE IMPOSED TERM LIMITS ON THEIR STATE LEGISLATORS</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Alaska, Idaho, Montana, Oregon, Arizona, Louisiana,  Nebraska, South Dakota,
Arkansas, Maine, Nevada, Utah, California,  Massachusetts, North Dakota,
Washington, Colorado, Michigan,  Ohio, Wyoming, Florida, Missouri, and Oklahoma.
 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Audits have uncovered significant past abuses.</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>On January 4, 1995, the House of Representatives voted 430-1 
for an internal audit by an outside accounting firm, Price  Waterhouse. It was a
matter of bipartisan conventional wisdom that the  management of the House had
been permeated with &quot;abuses and  management inefficiencies,&quot; in the
words of former House  Majority Leader Richard A. Gephardt (D-MO) in 1992.
Although a  few House accounts had been audited by the General Accounting 
Office, it is likely that many had never been reviewed by an  independent
examiner. Since one such audit uncovered the House  Bank scandal, a full
accounting was long overdue. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The accounting practices of the 103rd Congress revealed by  the Price
Waterhouse audit demonstrate that the House's financial  and operational
controls were worse than even the harshest critics  had imagined. The 14
material weaknesses uncovered would be  troubling in a medium-sized business;
their presence in the  13,000-employee House of Representatives is a national
disgrace.  Most disturbing are the conclusions that the House was:
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>-     Wasting</B> millions of dollars on inefficient
purchasing practices  and superfluous staff; 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>-     Failing</B> to prevent employee fraud through multiple 
reimbursements for the same purchase; 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>-     Allowing</B> the use of official resources for campaign purposes;
and 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>-     Keeping</B> such careless records that the magnitude of the loss
to  the 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 7 -->  public probably will never be
known.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The good news is that the new Congress, under the leadership  of Speaker
Newt Gingrich (R-GA), House Oversight  Committee Chairman Bill Thomas (R-CA),
Representative Jim Nussle  (R-IA), its administrative officers, and the
management team they  brought in, has taken aggressive action to correct the
deficiencies  identified by the audit. Many of the 226 recommendations the
auditors  made already have been implemented, and the remainder are  being
implemented.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Members of Congress still benefit from a system of perks  and
privileges.</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Excessive pay, perks, and expenses focused citizen anger on  Congress and
helped trigger the 1994 electoral revolution. The  new Republican majorities in
the House and Senate moved quickly  to cut staff and expenses and to eliminate
many of Congress's  exemptions from the law. Further steps are necessary,
however,  to reduce perks, reform pensions, and further trim staff. 
Congressional committees currently are considering some of these  reforms, while
others will likely be debated in the course of the  appropriations process. But
problems remain, such as automatic pay  raises, excessive pensions, and high
expense accounts.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>These perks continue to insulate Congress from American  citizens, to
frustrate political fairness, and to promote legislative  careerism and
bureaucracy. Reforms in these areas will mean a more  efficient, representative,
and politically competitive Congress. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>-     Automatic Pay Hikes.</B>  These pay hikes are
scheduled each  year 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 8 -->  with no vote required, further
boosting lawmakers' salaries,  which already exceed $11,000 a month ($133,600
per year).  Because Members' salaries are funded by a permanent, indefinite 
appropriation rather than through the annual appropriations bill, they  are
nearly invulnerable to legislative change when the rest  of Congress's budget is
under discussion. Congress should  make Members' salaries a legislative
appropriations line item and  eliminate the automatic salary cost-of-living
adjustments (COLAs)  that, unless Congress acts, give each Member an automatic
pay  hike. Such an automatic pay raise violates the spirit of the 27th 
Amendment to the Constitution, which states that Members must stand  for
reelection before any pay raise they vote on takes effect.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>-     Excessive Pensions.</B> Congressional pensions far exceed most 
private-sector plans. Congress's pension system is up to twice as  generous as
those of most Fortune 500 corporations. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Not only do these generous pensions burden the taxpayers,  but they also
promote political careerism by providing incentives  for lawmakers to extend
their tenure. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Over 250 Members of the 103rd Congress will become  &quot;pension
millionaires,&quot; receiving pension income after their retirement  in excess
of $1 million. For instance, former Speaker of the  House Tom Foley (D-WA) is
eligible for nearly $124,000 per year in  addition to the pay he will receive
from his job at a  lobbying/law firm. The former Speaker could take in over $3
million in  pension checks over the course of his expected lifetime. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>COLAs are applied to congressional pensions as well as  congressional
salaries. Only one in ten private-sector pensions is  adjusted 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 9 -->  for inflation, and many of those
compensate for as little as a  third of the inflation rate. This feature makes
former Members of  Congress among the wealthiest of retired Americans.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>-     Members' office expense accounts are too high.</B> The 1996 
appropriation combined the three House Members' personal  allowance accounts
(staff salaries, office expenses, and official mail) into  one appropriation, a
positive step to increase flexibility and ease  administrative burdens. However,
the combined account was  increased by over 2 percent, to over $360 million, due
to increases  in staff salaries and mail funding. A House committee has 
approved an additional 2 percent increase for the coming year, to an  average of
$887,337 for each House member. Although increases in  postal rates and
population may justify some adjustment of mail  allowances, it is difficult to
make similar arguments for an increase  in the aggregate staff salary
appropriation.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>During the debate at the beginning of the 104th Congress over  the proposed
elimination of House Legislative Service  Organizations, advocates of abolition
intimated that a substantial portion of the  $5 million spent each year on LSOs
would be saved. In fact,  these funds were not cut, and even steeper staff cuts
are justified. 
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Incumbents retain a significant electoral advantage.</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Campaign finance law and congressional perquisites provide  huge electoral
advantages for incumbents, leading to House  reelection rates of well over 90
percent  even the dramatic 1994  elections produced a reelection rate of 90.2
percent. This remarkable  level of job security is the result of several
built-in advantages that  stack the election deck. There are several reasons why
incumbents  enjoy 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 10 -->  such success.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>-     Challengers have difficulty raising funds.</B> After
passage of  the 1974 law that first regulated contributions to congressional 
campaigns, incumbents' financial advantage over challengers  grew fivefold by
1992, approaching an advantage of four to one.  In 1994, this had fallen
somewhat, to just over two to one. Much  of this is due to political action
committee (PAC) donations   special-interest gifts five times larger than
individuals are allowed  to contribute   that flow to incumbents by a
disproportionate  margin of nine to one.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>-     Members use constituent services to build a voter base.</B> The 
greatest tax-funded advantage enjoyed by incumbents is the  routine operation of
congressional offices. Members of Congress  use about half their staffs for
constituent service or casework,  helping voters who have problems with the
government. The irony is  that these problems flow in large part from the very
laws and  government programs Congress makes possible. Says former  Minnesota
Representative Vin Weber, &quot;we create the government that  screws you, and
then you're supposed to thank us for protecting you  from it.&quot;  Studies
show that constituent service adds 5 percent to 10  percent to a typical
Member's vote total.<A HREF="ftnt12.htm#3">3</A>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>-     Members have free mailing privileges  though now in  smaller
amounts.</B> In March 1994, the House Oversight Committee  approved a one-third
cut in Members' franking allowances from  their 1994 authorizations. This will
save over $20 million in  postage-related spending yearly, bringing down the
average annual  spending ceiling per congressional office from $163,000 to 
$108,000. This is a healthy step on the road to eliminating abuses that  per
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 11 -->  petuate congressional careerism.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Many campaign finance &quot;reform&quot; schemes are overregulatory.</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Many of the reform plans to diminish the influence of money  in politics
create a regulatory system that actually protects  incumbents and punishes
challengers. The key elements of many  regulatory campaign finance reform plans
include spending limits,  advertising subsidies, and public financing. These
provisions  are likely to make elections even less competitive and less 
issue-oriented.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>There are four key problems involved in limiting  congressional campaign
spending:
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>1. Spending limits uniformly punish challengers.</B>
Studies  have demonstrated that challengers need to spend significant amounts 
of money to unseat sitting Members of Congress. In 1994, the  average challenger
who unseated an incumbent spent well  over $700,000.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>2. Spending limits ignore the advantages of incumbency.</B> In  addition
to contending with incumbents' natural advantage in  name identification and
media access, challengers must compete  with the enormous array of
taxpayer-funded resources that  incumbents have at their disposal.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>3. Spending limits violate the First Amendment.</B> Mandatory  limits
are clearly unconstitutional. To get around this problem, most  proposals call
the limits voluntary, but they place those who do  not accept the caps at such a
great disadvantage that the limits  argu
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 12 -->  ably are made compulsory.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>4. Spending limits encourage evasion, hiding, and cheating.</B> 
Citizens will always find ways to express their views. The  principal effect of
government regulation of political speech is to push  citizens away from
straightforward activities (such as direct  donations) into more circuitous
methods. Previous attempts at  regulating away political influence have led to
the development of  PACs, bundling, soft money, and independent expenditure 
campaigns.<A HREF="ftnt12.htm#4">4</A>
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Why Public Financing Is No Answer.</B> Another way to limit  the
influence of money on politics is through public subsidizing  of campaigns.
Already, presidential campaigns receive a limited  public subsidy that has
become increasingly unpopular with  the American taxpayers (as demonstrated by
the declining number  of taxpayers who elect to participate on their tax forms).
The  four most critical problems with public financing are:
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>1. The money is already committed.</B> Public financing of 
congressional candidates would require additional funds from the  federal budget
 an effort which the commitment to a balanced budget  by 2002 makes all the more
difficult.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>2. Public financing is expensive.</B> Taxpayer grants for  congressional
candidates could well total in the hundreds of millions of  dollars. The
possibility of nearly 1,000 subsidized candidates every  two years vividly
demonstrates the tremendous cost of  government involvement.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>3. The people oppose public financing.</B> Taxpayers have  abandoned the
presidential campaign fund checkoff, with participation  falling 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 13 -->  from 29 percent in 1980 to 17
percent in 1991. To find  sufficient funds for the 1996 presidential elections,
Congress was forced  to raise the value of the individual checkoff from $1 to $3
per year.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>4. Subsidizing political extremists is unattractive to most  Americans.</B>
Experience with the presidential fund shows that fringe  candidates are
attracted by government subsidies. Third-party  radical Lenora Fulani received
nearly $1 million in federal  matching funds in the 1988 presidential campaign
and over $2 million  in 1992.<A HREF="ftnt12.htm#5">5</A> 
Because there cannot be an ideological litmus test for  public financing, tax
dollars inevitably would go to dozens of  extremist candidates ranging from
Fulani to Lyndon La Rouche to  David Duke.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Why Broadcast Subsidies Also Are No Answer.</B> Postal and  broadcast
subsidies are nothing more than public funding in disguise.  By compelling
broadcasters or the postal service to provide no-cost  or low-cost political
communication services to candidates, the  government essentially is taxing
these entities and transferring  those funds to the candidates. All of the
problems that exist with  public subsidies necessarily carry over to this
heavy-handed,  big-government &quot;reform&quot; scheme.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*     Taxpayer-subsidized lobbying helps drive up the cost of 
government.</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The federal government currently subsidizes lobbying by  tax-exempt
organizations by supplying grants and contracts to  advocacy groups. Each year,
America's taxpayers provide these  organizations with billions of dollars which
they then use to advance  their own political agendas.
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 14 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Federal funding of private advocacy is not limited by  ideology.
Organizations to the left and right of the political center use  taxpayers'
funds to promote their ideas and positions. Almost  every interest in America 
from agriculture to zoology  has one  or more organizations tainted by
government funding. The  American Association of Retired Persons, for example,
received over  $73 million in a one-year period, while the American Bar 
Association received over $2 million.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Over the past 40 years, Congress has created a vast patronage  network of
organizations that enjoy preferred tax status, receive  federal funds, and
engage in legislative or political advocacy.  The days of big-city political
machines disbursing patronage may  be coming to an end, but the disbursement of
financial dividends  to political friends remains a prominent feature of the
federal budget.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>As James Bennett and Thomas DiLorenzo wrote in their  1985 book <I>Destroying
Democracy</I>: 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>      A large number of individuals with strong views can 
express their preferences by contributing funds to a group that  promotes that
issue. With tax-funded politics, however, a  small number of zealots with access
to the public purse can  obtain resources to advance its views even though few
individuals  in society share the group's philosophy. Whenever  government funds
any political advocacy group, it effectively  penalizes those groups that
advocate opposing public policies and  provides a distinct advantage to the
group or groups it favors  in the clash of ideas.<A
HREF="ftnt12.htm#6">6</A>
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 15 --> 
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>In 1995, Congress began to address the significant problem of  welfare for
lobbyists. In the House, Representatives Ernest Istook  (R-OK), David McIntosh
(R-IN), and Robert Ehrlich (R-MD)  proposed an amendment to an appropriations
bill that would limit  the amount of money federal grantees could spend on
political  advocacy to not more than 5 percent of their non-grant  revenue.<A
HREF="ftnt12.htm#7">7</A>  Even though this formula permitted
charities to spend generous  amounts of money on lobbying, it was bitterly
opposed. The  amendment died in conference.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>The Huge Growth in Committees and Staff
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Until action was taken in the 104th Congress, the explosion  in committees
and staff led to the growth of a powerful staff  bureaucracy and made it easier
for interest groups to influence  legislation.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>-     House committee staff had grown almost twelvefold since 
World War II. In the last two decades alone, committee staffs in  the House of
Representatives had grown by 158 percent. Congress  was the most heavily staffed
legislature in the world by a factor of  five, with nearly 40,000 employees.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>-     The number of committees and subcommittees totaled under  200 in 1947,
exploded in the post-Watergate era, and did not fall  significantly under 300
until the early 1990s. The new Congress  cut this number to 198.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><A NAME="RECORD">THE RECORD</A></B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>THE 104TH CONGRESS
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The 104th Congress acted swiftly to change its rules and  practices. The
1994 elections changed the partisan control of Congress  and delivered a clear
reform mandate. The Contract With  America promised numerous changes in House
rules, and the new  leadership of the House of Representatives took this mandate
and  ran with it. On January 4, 1995, the opening day of the 104th  Congress,
the House voted to end procedures that had become  increasingly arbitrary and
secretive. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The new House rules package largely achieved the goals of  the institution's
critics. The rules were designed to:
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>-     Improve deliberation</B> by banning proxy (absentee) voting in 
committees, ensuring minority rights in the amendment process,  and requiring
fuller reporting on spending bills.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>-     Streamline the legislative process</B> by cutting the number of 
committees and subcommittees, abolishing joint referrals of  legislation, and
slashing committee staff.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>-     Promote accountability</B> by requiring that committee meetings 
be open to the public and to the broadcast media, requiring roll  call votes on
major legislation, prohibiting alterations in debate  transcripts, and
conducting a comprehensive audit of House finances.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>-     Increase responsiveness</B> by imposing term limits on the 
Speaker and committee chairmen and providing for consideration of a  measure to
apply federal laws to Congress as the first legislative  vote 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 17 -->  in the 104th Congress.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The Republicans' Contract With America provided for eight  specific
first-day reforms that the House succeeded in passing:
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>1)  Staff Cuts and Committee Reforms.</B> The new rules  package
eliminated three House committees  Post Office and Civil  Service, District of
Columbia, and Merchant Marine and Fisheries   and 25 subcommittees. The
committee reform provision also  will shrink House committee staff by one-third.

</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B> 2)  Truth in Budgeting.</B> Appropriations committees are now  required
to compare new spending recommendations to the  current spending level. Under
the old system, tax-and-spend liberals  had the upper hand because spending
increases were judged not  against what was actually spent last year, but
against projected  spending for next year. With these rules, even a spending
increase could  be called a &quot;cut.&quot;
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>3)  Term Limits for Committee Chairmen and the Speaker.</B>  House
committee chairmen will be prohibited from serving more  than three consecutive
Congresses (six years). Limiting the tenure  of committee chairmen begins to
address some of the concerns  of advocates of full-scale legislative term
limits. A central problem  of previous Congresses had been that committee
chairmen, who  set the agenda, had spent decades in office. In the 103rd
Congress,  for example, the chairmen of two of the House's three most  powerful
committees (Ways and Means and Energy and Commerce)  had held these positions
for over a decade; the chairman of the  third (Appropriations) had just vacated
his position after holding it  since the 1970s.
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 18 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>In addition, the Speaker will be prohibited from serving more  than four
Congresses (eight years), bringing the top constitutional  officer of the
legislative branch in line with the President, his  executive branch
counterpart.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>4)  Elimination of Proxy Voting.</B> Elimination of the practice  of
allowing absent members of a committee to loan their votes  to other members was
critical to ensuring fairness and  improving committee deliberation. Although
House rules strictly  prohibited one Member from casting votes for another on
the House  floor (indeed, ethics reprimands have been triggered by this rule's 
violation), proxy voting was the norm in most committees in the  103rd Congress.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Historically, proxy voting allowed the majority party leadership  to extend
its control over committee outcomes by scheduling  multiple, contemporaneous
committee and subcommittee  meetings. Proxy voting also promoted committee
absenteeism by  ensuring that legislators who skipped meetings would retain
their ability  to cast votes in absentia, in addition to allowing legislators to
 abandon their deliberative responsibilities by voting for or against 
legislation without hearing any discussion or argument on its  merits.
Abolishing proxy voting will reduce the power of committee  chairmen and force
Members to show up and actually participate in  the work of their committees if
they want their votes to count.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>5)  Open Meetings.</B> The 1995 rules changes also ensure public  access
to committee meetings. In previous Congresses,  committees frequently closed
their doors to the press and public, a step  the panels could take for nearly
any reason. In fact, the two  House 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 19 -->  committees that most often
operated in secret   Appropriations and Ways and Means  were the ones making 
controversial choices about federal taxation and spending. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Further, broadcast media are permitted to cover any open  hearing or meeting
(previously, media coverage was subject to a vote  of approval). The new rules
also require that committees publish  recorded committee votes in their reports
(most voting records  previously were available only at committee offices) and
that  hearing transcripts not be altered other than for minor  grammatical
changes.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>6)  Tax Hikes More Difficult.</B> The new rules require a  three-fifths
vote of the House to pass any income tax rate increase and  prohibit retroactive
taxation of income. The 60 percent rule has been  particularly controversial,
with some Washington  commentators claiming the new rule is anti-democratic or
even  unconstitutional. Behind the heated rhetoric inside the Beltway is the
conviction  that new tax increases are needed.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The supermajority requirement is similar to restrictions  voters have
imposed on numerous state legislatures. Among the  most beneficial aspects of
the 60 percent tax rule is that any future  Congress desiring to raise taxes
would have to alter or waive the  rule, thereby signaling a potential tax boost.
The provision also  balances the burden of a 1990 budget law which effectively
requires a  60 percent vote in the Senate to cut taxes (unless the reductions 
are offset by increases in other taxes or cuts in entitlement spending).
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>7)  Authorization of House Audit.</B> Another 1995 rules change 
authorized a comprehensive audit of House records, assets, and  fa
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 20 -->  cilities by an independent
accounting firm. Some House  accounts previously had been audited sporadically
by the General  Accounting Office, an internal congressional agency. Despite the
fact  that one such audit uncovered the House Bank scandal, most  House accounts
were not examined regularly, and some may never  have been reviewed by an
independent examiner. This audit was  the first complete accounting of the
House's financial status  ever made available to the public.<A
HREF="ftnt12.htm#8">8</A>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>8)  Applying Federal Laws to Congress.</B> The last of the  Contract
reforms was the Congressional Accountability Act (CAA).  This measure has both
substantive and symbolic importance. It  underscores the principle that no
American should be immune from  the law or receive special treatment in its
application. The bill  also should encourage legislators to review the burdens
that  federal laws place upon American citizens and ensure that the  benefits
they bring exceed their attendant costs.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Term Limits </B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The new Congress also held the first-ever votes on term  limits. Although
the House fell short of the necessary two-thirds  majority by 63 votes (227
ayes, 204 nays), the vote marked a  significant improvement over previous
Congresses that refused even to  debate the issue. Seven months after the House
vote, the Senate took up  a nonbinding resolution supporting term limits. The
resolution  failed to win majority support (45 ayes, 49 nays). Still, by putting
 members of the House and Senate on record as publicly supporting  or opposing
term limits, supporters now have a standard  against which they can measure
future Congresses. In addition, the  voters will know  unequivocally  where
their representatives stand  on 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 21 -->  this important issue. A Senate
vote on a constitutional  amendment is planned for early 1996, though supporters
concede they are  certain to fail. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Budget Cuts </B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The new Congress voted to slash its own budget. The FY  1996 legislative
branch appropriations bill provided systemic  congressional reforms as important
as any yet enacted, including  spending cuts, staff cuts, privatization, and
abolition of unnecessary  offices and functions. The FY 1996 congressional
budget would  reduce spending in real dollars  not phony &quot;baseline&quot;
cuts  by  $242 million, or 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Congress succeeded in setting an example for the rest of the  government by
slashing its staff and eliminating unneeded  agencies, including the $21 million
Office of Technology  Assessment, which had provided redundant services to the
national  legislature. The reforms push the General Accounting Office to
privatize  its administrative functions, such as printing, mail handling, and 
library services. The GAO also will receive funds to contract  out some of its
auditing work so that it can benefit from the  lower costs available in the
private sector. The result is a real cut of  more than one-fourth in the GAO's
budget.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Despite Congress's effort to lead by example by cutting its  own budget
first, President Clinton vetoed the legislative branch  appropriations bill the
first time it reached his desk. He stated that  he liked the bill but did not
want to let Congress receive its  funding early in the budget process. In other
words, the President  decided that scoring political points was more important
than  achieving 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 22 -->  real spending cuts.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Lobbying Reform and Gift Ban</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>In 1995, the House and Senate both enacted rules restricting  the types and
amounts of gifts lawmakers may receive. The  Senate passed a complex rule that
allowed single gifts up to $50, with  a $100 annual limit. Any item less than
$10 fell outside the  Senate's rules. The House chose to adopt a more sweeping
proposal  offered by Speaker Newt Gingrich to prohibit all gifts. Both the 
Senate rule and the House ban include exceptions for  commemorative items and
expenses related to official activities.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Lobbying disclosure legislation was approved by both the  House and Senate
in late 1995. While this legislation would adopt  new reporting requirements and
close loopholes in the original  1946 Lobby Reform Act, it carefully avoids many
potential pitfalls.  It successfully protects legitimate grassroots organizing,
as well  as part-time and small lobbying operations.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>A glaring omission from the so-called reform bill was any  meaningful effort
to address taxpayer-subsidized lobbying.  Opponents of this reform argued for
months that welfare for lobbyists  should be addressed in the lobby reform
debate, then turned around  and argued against any House amendments to this
important  legislation. The result is a flawed lobby reform bill.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>THE CLINTON ADMINISTRATION</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The Clinton Administration has a very poor record on  political reform
issues. The President has supported an overregulatory  cam
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 23 -->  paign finance &quot;reform&quot;
scheme that would impose spending  limits and public financing. He promoted
lobbying reform but  adamantly opposed provisions that would have restricted the
abuse of  taxpayer grants through government-subsidized lobbying.  Moreover, he
has not supported the most important reform needed to shake  up the current
political process: term limits.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The Clinton Administration has promoted the concept of  &quot;reinventing
government,&quot; but a close examination of the fine print  of the
Administration's plan shows that it makes federal  management even worse.
Clinton proposals weaken merit standards in  hiring, promotion, and pay and
strengthen the role of federal unions  in setting salary levels of work
assignments in federal agencies,  thus directly undermining management
authority. The result: a  federal bureaucracy even less accountable to the
public.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>WHAT TO DO IN 1997</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The 104th Congress achieved dramatic reforms in the structure  and operation
of Congress, but many other reforms are needed.  Among them, the new Congress
should:
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>-     Pass a constitutional amendment for term limits.</B> Although  the
104th Congress put all its members on record for or against  term limits, the
failure to enact the reform means that Members of  Congress still can remain in
office as long as they want. The  Supreme Court's ruling against state-based
term limits leaves Congress  no choice but to enact a constitutional amendment
to end  congressional careerism.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>-     Slash congressional perks and privileges. </B>Congress should  end

<!-- Generation of PM publication page 24 -->  wasteful, inefficient spending
and perquisites that separate  lawmakers from their constituents. The reforms in
the Contract  With America were good first steps, but Congress should continue 
to reform its own pay, pensions, perks, and staff. Specifically,  it should: 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>Eliminate</B> the automatic pay raise mechanism currently
in effect; 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Enforce</B> the law docking Members' pay during extended  unexcused
absences; 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Establish</B> a defined contribution pension system that forces  career
legislators either to leave with their old pensions or to  continue without
them, thus saving taxpayers money and reducing  incentives for congressional
careerism; 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Disallow</B> personal use of frequent flier miles acquired on  official
business;
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Prohibit</B> Members from receiving free medical care from local  area
military hospitals; and
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Eliminate</B> free parking for Members at National and Dulles  airports.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>The Citizen Congress Act, introduced in the House by  Representatives Mark
Sanford (R-SC) and Wayne Allard (R-CO) and in  the Senate by Bill Frist (R-TN),
is a sensible effort to address  these perks and privileges, including the items
listed above. The  bill (H.R. 2610/S. 1405) also would eliminate mass mailings
paid  for by the taxpayers  a tremendous incumbent advantage. These  re
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 25 -->  forms are needed to bring
Congress more in contact with the  challenges faced by average citizens and to
help restore  Americans' trust in government.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Action on the political reform that the American public has  demanded is
beginning to materialize, as shown by the 23 states  that passed term limits
legislation and by the provisions of the  Contract With America providing for
congressional committee and  staff reductions. To make challengers more
competitive and ensure  that incumbents are not abusing taxpayers' funds in
their  re-election campaigns, Congress should:
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>-     Curtail franked mass mailings</B> from House Members
through a  75 percent cut in the franking allowance; 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>-     End support for all congressional perquisites,</B> such as 
television recording studios and calendars mailed out at taxpayers'  expense,
that have no genuine legislative function; 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>-     Discourage aides from performing campaign reelection work,</B> 
either through simple prohibition of the practice or tighter  regulation of
official travel; and 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>-      Cut clerk-hire budgets by 10 percent,</B> using some of the
savings  to create a central constituent service office to handle routine 
requests. 
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>Eliminating these advantages, in addition to saving  taxpayers money, would
represent true campaign finance reform by  diminishing the overwhelming
advantages incumbents enjoy in  elections. Reformers who seek genuinely
competitive elections and  a 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 26 -->  more efficient, representative,
and deliberative Congress  should place cuts in congressional pay, perks,
pensions, and staff at  the top of their agenda.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*      Enact campaign finance reform.</B> While the most important 
steps toward improving the American electoral system are term  limits and
reducing the incumbency advantage, other improvements  can be made in campaign
financing.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The Wamp Congress Act of 1995 (H.R. 2148), named for  sponsor Zach Wamp
(R-TN), provides productive and realistic reforms  that reduce special-interest
and incumbent advantages with a  minimum of new regulation. The legislation
would:
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>-      Lower</B> the PAC contribution limit from $5,000 to
$2,000 per  election;
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>-      Raise</B> the individual contributor limit from $1,000 to $2,000 
per election; and
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>-     Require</B> that 50 percent of individual campaign contributions 
be from the candidate's home state.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>Wamp points out that the proposed increase in individual  donation limits is
less than the level required to offset inflation since  1974. His proposal
achieves the two most important goals of  campaign finance reform. It would:
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>-     Equalize</B> the individual and PAC contributions by
increasing  the $1,000 individual cap, and
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 27 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>-     Avoid</B> overregulation of the sort that resulted from the 
reforms adopted 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><B>*     Apply the Freedom of Information Act to Congress.</B> The  major
flaw in the Congressional Accountability Act was its exclusion  of the Freedom
of Information Act (FOIA) from the list of  covered laws. The FOIA does not
apply to the private sector because it  is intended to give the public access to
government information.  Excluding the Act makes it appear that Congress thinks
it has  something to hide and runs counter to the openness in government 
principles embodied in most other House reforms.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*     End welfare for lobbyists.</B> Although Congress has begun to 
address the issue of taxpayer-subsidized political advocacy, much  remains to be
done. In the 105th Congress, investigative hearings  must continue to examine
existing abuses, and further remedies must  be considered. The information
gained from these hearings and  from further investigation into the activities
of federal grantees must  be used to develop a meaningful reform proposal that,
as nearly  as possible, eliminates this outrageous abuse of taxpayers' funds.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>At its root, the issue of welfare for lobbyists is one of fairness  and
fiscal responsibility. True reform can be achieved only if it  includes the
following principles:
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>-     Full Disclosure.</B> Strong reporting requirements
are necessary  to shed light on the extent of this problem. Widespread abuse is 
already apparent  even from the limited and often confusing  data currently
gathered by the government. Federal grantees must  be tracked carefully and
should be required to indicate how  much money they dedicate to advocacy.
Furthermore, whatever  informa
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 28 -->  tion the government collects
should be readily available to  the public for inspection. To the greatest
extent feasible, this  should include availability via the Internet at no cost
to users. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>-     Truth in Testimony.</B> Witnesses testifying before Congress 
should be required to divulge whether they receive federal funds and,  if so,
for what purposes and in what amounts.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>-     No Federal Funding for Advocacy.</B> No advocacy organization 
that receives federal funds should be permitted to engage in  anything but
incidental lobbying except on issues related directly to its  tax status.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>-     No Bureaucratic Shell Games.</B> No organization that receives 
federal funds should be permitted to provide financial assistance  to any
affiliated organization that engages in lobbying activity.  All sub-grantees
should be treated as if they received the funds  directly from the federal
government. Organizations should not  be able to create sham &quot;foundations&quot;
that launder taxpayer funding  to support lobbying.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>-     Tough Penalties.</B> The consequences for violating the
prohibition  on federally subsidized lobbying must be firm enough to  discourage
organizations from violating the standards. Under no  circumstances should any
organization that willingly and knowingly  violates this prohibition receive
additional federal funding.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Civil Service Reform. </B>The new Congress and the new  President must
cooperate in tackling the toughest management chore in  the country: running the
federal bureaucracy. To do this, they  must examine every agency and bureau of
the government to:
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 29 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>-     Eliminate</B> duplication and privatize those federal
functions that  can best be performed by the private sector;
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>-     Devolve</B> those functions to the states and local governments 
that can best be performed at those levels; and
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>-     Eliminate</B> wasteful or unnecessary agencies and departments 
altogether.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>While reforming federal hiring, pay, and benefit policies, both  the
President and Congress must be sure to enforce the merit  principles of the
civil service system and maintain a bright line  between career and non-career
jobs. The usurpation of policy  functions by career staff undermines the
accountability of political  appointees to the President and the taxpayer, while
political abuse  of career staff undermines the integrity and professionalism of
 the civil service. Under no circumstance should Congress  undermine the
President's authority to appoint his own people to positions  of responsibility
and thus carry out his agenda and fulfill his  promises to the taxpayers. Good
government is accountable government. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>In the meantime, the President and Congress should advance  serious reform
of the federal civil service system:
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>*     Establish serious pay-for-performance standards for
federal  employees.</B> The Reagan Administration's program of rewarding 
federal managers for performance, including a bonus system for  good performers,
should be revised and the principle of pay for  performance should be extended
throughout the federal workforce.
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 30 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*     Modernize federal benefits.</B> The federal government should 
adopt a defined contribution for federal retirement and expand  investment
options for employees. Federal workers and their  families should be allowed to
open medical savings accounts for the  payment of routine medical services and
to roll these accounts  over each year tax free.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*     Consolidate federal management and personnel agencies.</B>  The
President and Congress should consolidate the Office of  Management and Budget
(OMB), the Office of Personnel  management (OPM), and the General Services
Administration (GSA) into a  new Office of Management. At the same time, federal
employee  appeals and grievances, now scattered among EEOC, the  Federal Labor
Relations Board (FLRB), and the Merit Systems  Protection Board (MSPB), should
be consolidated into one agency. 
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><A NAME="Q&A">Q &amp; A</A></B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Q. Aren't the Republicans hypocritical to attack  congressional
careerism in 1994, then fail to pass term limits in 1995?
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>A.</B> The 104th Congress made great progress on term limits just  by
bringing the measure up for a vote in the House and Senate.  Although both
houses failed to come up with the two-thirds  majority needed to move the
amendment forward, they have provided  term limit supporters with a solid
benchmark to use in pressing ahead  in the 105th Congress.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>It will likely take at least one more election before Congress  has enough
conservative members dedicated to the cause of term  limits to muster the
supermajority needed to press ahead with a  con
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 31 -->  stitutional amendment.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Q. Isn't Congress really just trying to &quot;muzzle&quot; opponents
with  its effort to end welfare for lobbyists?
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>A.</B> No. The attempts to end taxpayer-subsidized lobbying all  seek to
end 40 years of corrupt political patronage. The proposals  considered by the
104th Congress applied to groups all across  the ideological spectrum. Despite
cries that the reform  efforts amounted to nothing more than &quot;defunding the
left,&quot; the  Simpson-Istook compromise language that reached the floor of
the  House and Senate would affect corporations that receive grants  (primarily
for research and development) just as much as nonprofits.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Welfare for lobbyists is a fundamental question of fiscal  responsibility.
With the drive to achieve a balanced budget in 2002, it  is utterly
irresponsible for the government to be feeding hungry  lobbyists instead of
hungry children.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Q. Why are some of the most vocal supporters of term limits  career
politicians?  Why don't they apply term limits to themselves?
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>A.</B> Some Members, particularly those elected since 1990,  have agreed
to self-imposed term limits. This marks significant  progress toward a true &quot;citizen
Congress.&quot;  However, many Members  are reluctant to agree voluntarily to
term limits. If reformers  unilaterally &quot;disarm themselves&quot; by leaving
Congress now, the  career politicians left behind will enjoy an even tighter
control of  Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Q. How can the influence of big money contributions be reduced?
</B><!-- Generation of PM publication page 32 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>A.</B> The best way to reduce the impact of special interests on 
elections is to reduce the role of Washington. This can be  accomplished in
several ways. First, reducing the size of  government would reduce the number of
programs subject to  special-interest lobbying and would lower the taxes from
which corporations  routinely seek exceptions. Similarly, imposition of a flat
tax  would eliminate the bidding for tax code loopholes that currently  drives
much Washington lobbying.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The second step is to reduce Washington's role in the  political process.
Ending taxpayer-subsidized lobbying and forcing  special interests to raise
their money directly from supporters will place  all groups on a level playing
field. At the same time, the federal  government should remain out of the
business of overregulating  elections. In fact, current regulatory schemes are
part of the problem.  It is important to recall that the 1970s campaign finance
reform  effort produced PACs, now the target of reform themselves.  Elections
should not be government-funded, the media should not  be forced to carry
no-cost or low-cost political advertising, and  the government should not impose
spending limits. Moreover,  individual and PAC contribution levels should be
equalized to  ensure that special interests do not enjoy an advantage over 
individual voters.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Of course, the ultimate solution to the influence of money in  politics is
to adopt term limits. Limiting the tenure of Members  of Congress forces them to
focus more on policies than politics.  With the understanding that they will not
be part of a &quot;career  Congress,&quot; Members will not be as dependent on
special interests to remain  in office.
<P>
<a name="EXP">
<b>EXPERTS</b>
<p>
<a href="/heritage/staff/wittmann.htm">Marshall Wittmann</a><br>
The Heritage Foundation<br>
214 Massachusetts Ave., N.E.<br>
Washington, D.C. 20002<br>
phone: 202-608-6076<br>
email: <a href="mailto: wittmannm@heritage.org">wittmannm@heritage.org</a>
